stant overlapping runs. Kontoes also got the most assists for Panionios in the season 2010\u201311. Kontoes was listed as best Left Back in the starting 11 by [[Superleague Greece]] due to his consistent performances.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Panionios===\nWhen [[Panionios]] signed him, everybody in the club trusted him and he was ready to improve himself in order to meet the expectations of Panionios. He was rewarded for his efforts as Panionios fans loved him and his passion. So, the club decided to renew his contract with Kontoes. He was teammate of [[Grigoris Makos]]. Some years later, both of them played for [[AEK Athens]].\n\n===AEK Athens===\nOn August 1, 2011, Kontoes signed a three-year deal with [[AEK Athens]] on a free transfer keeping him at the club until 2014. Kontoes was a key target for AEK Athens as he is a versatile player who can play as right back, left back and centre back. He also had a very impressive season at Panionios and was named Panionios player of the year and MVP Left back in the [[Superleague Greece]]. Just before signing with AEK Athens, Panionios tried one last attempt on keeping Kontoes at Panionios and offered a higher contract than AEK Athens, however Kontoes declined the offer and signed with AEK Athens as he wanted to play in [[Europe]]an competitions and contend for the [[Superleague Greece]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aekfc.gr/index.asp?a_id=1355&n_id=6889 |title=AEK Athens sign Kontoes |access-date=1 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604111819/http://www.aekfc.gr/index.asp?a_id=1355&n_id=6889 |archive-date=4 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Kontoes made his debut for AEK Athens in a 1-0 away win against [[Skoda Xanthi]]. Kontoes' second match of the season was against his former club [[Panionios]] where he received a lot of criticism from the fans as he left the club after 4 years and joined Athens rivals, AEK. Despite the criticism, Kontoes played a very solid game and was awarded the MVP award, the final score was a 1-0 away win for AEK Athens.\n\nKontoes became quickly very important for his team and for 2012-13 season he is expected to be one of the leaders in the \"yellow-black\" squad. He played mainly as a left back, but also and as a center back. In December 2012, Kontoes decided to \"break\" his contract with AEK Athens due to financial reasons.\n\n===Asteras Tripolis===\nOn January 30, 2013, Kontoes signed a deal with [[Asteras Tripoli F.C.|Asteras Tripolis]]. On 24 February 2013, he made his debut with the club in a 1-0 home win against [[Levadiakos]].\n\n===Atromitos===\nOn September 4, 2014 Kontoes signed a deal with [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]], replacing [[Kostas Giannoulis]] who moved to [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiakos]]. On 14 September, he made his debut with the club in a 0-0 home draw against [[Panetolikos]].<ref>[http://www.enet.gr/?i=news.el.article&id=446020 \u0391\u03c4\u03c1\u03cc\u03bc\u03b7\u03c4\u03bf\u03c2 \u03bf \u039a\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03ad\u03c2!]</ref> On 19 June 2015, he extended his contract with the club by two years for an undisclosed fee.<ref>[http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/Atromitos/ananewse-o-kontoes-exase-vitolo.3537341.html \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd\u03ad\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03bf \u039a\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03ad\u03c2, \u03ad\u03c7\u03b1\u03c3\u03b5 \u0392\u03b9\u03c4\u03cc\u03bb\u03bf]</ref> On 17 May 2017, he solved his contract with [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]] after 3 consecutive years with the club.\n\n===Apollon Smyrnis===\nOn 29 June 2017 [[Apollon Smyrni F.C.|Apollon Smyrnis]] announced the signing of Kontoes.<ref>[http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/apollonon-smirnis/ston-apollwna-smurnhs-o-kontoes.4742107.html \u03a3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u0391\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd\u03b1 \u03a3\u03bc\u03cd\u03c1\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u03bf \u039a\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03ad\u03c2]</ref> On 5 February 2018, he scored his first goal in his professional career in a 1-1 away draw game against [[Platanias F.C.|Platanias]].<ref>[https://www.to10.gr/podosfero/superleague/130281/apollon-smyrnis-proto-gkol-stin-epangelmatiki-kariera-tou-kontoe/ \u0391\u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd \u03a3\u03bc\u03cd\u03c1\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 : \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf \u03b3\u03ba\u03bf\u03bb \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03c0\u03b1\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u03bb\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03ba\u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u039a\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03ad]</ref>\n\n===Academica Clinceni===\nOn 31 January 2020, Romanian club [[FC Academica Clinceni|Academica Clinceni]] announced the signing of Kontoes on loan from [[CFR Cluj]], until the end of the 2019-20 season. The 33-year-old defender was signed a contract with Cluj for the [[2019\u201320 CFR Cluj season|2019-20 season]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://academica-clinceni.ro/ioannis-kontoes-va-juca-la-academica-clinceni/|title=IOANNIS KONTOES VA JUCA LA ACADEMICA CLINCENI|accessdate=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020|author=Mihaitalazarica|publisher=[[FC Academica Clinceni|Academica Clinceni]]|language=Romanian}}</ref> <ref>[https://www.novasports.gr/podosfairo/super_league/article/1686564/metakomizei_roumania_o_kontoes \u039c\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03bc\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03a1\u03bf\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1 \u03bf \u039a\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03ad\u03c2]</ref>, but did not play in any official game during the first half of the season.<ref>[https://top-highlights.gr/b/193793/%CE%A3%CE%B5-%CF%80%CE%BF%CE%B9%CE%B1-%CE%BF%CE%BC%CE%AC%CE%B4%CE%B1-%CF%80%CE%AE%CF%81%CE%B5-%CE%BC%CE%B5%CF%84%CE%B1%CE%B3%CF%81%CE%B1%CF%86%CE%AE-%CE%BF-%CE%9A%CE%BF%CE%BD%CF%84%CF%8C%CE%B5%CF%82 \u03a3\u03b5 \u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03b1 \u03bf\u03bc\u03ac\u03b4\u03b1 \u03c0\u03ae\u03c1\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03bf \u039a\u03bf\u03bd\u03c4\u03cc\u03b5\u03c2]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150924142942/http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=player&id=18796 Scoresway.com Profile]\n* [http://guardian.touch-line.com/StatsCentre.asp?Lang=0&CTID=31&CPID=76&pStr=Player&PLID=206394&TEID=682 Guardian Football]\n\n{{FC Academica Clinceni squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kontoes, Giannis}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Gamma Ethniki players]]\n[[Category:Delta Ethniki players]]\n[[Category:Superleague Greece players]]\n[[Category:Liga I players]]\n[[Category:Agios Dimitrios F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Athinaikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Fostiras F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Panionios F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AEK Athens F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Asteras Tripoli F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Atromitos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Apollon Smyrni F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Academica Clinceni players]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Romania]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate sportspeople in Romania]]\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giannis_Kontoes"}
{"title_page": "EPR (nuclear reactor)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n[[File:EPR OLK3 lage.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Computer generated view of an '''EPR''' power station]]\n[[File:EPR pressure vessel.png|upright|thumb|Reactor pressure vessel of the EPR]]\nThe '''EPR''' is a [[Generation III reactor|third generation]] [[pressurised water reactor]] design. It has been designed and developed mainly by [[Framatome]] (part of [[Areva]] between 2001 and 2017) and [[\u00c9lectricit\u00e9 de France]] (EDF) in France, and [[Siemens]] in Germany. In Europe this reactor design was called '''European Pressurised Reactor''', and the internationalised name was '''Evolutionary Power Reactor''', but it is now simply named '''EPR'''.\n\nThe first operational EPR unit was China's [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant|Taishan 1]], which started in December 2018.<ref name=wnn-20181214>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/First-EPR-enters-commercial-operation |title=First EPR enters commercial operation |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=14 December 2018 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> Taishan 2 started operations in September 2019.<ref name=wnn-20190909>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/World-s-second-EPR-starts-operations |title=World's second EPR starts operations |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=9 September 2019 |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> The first two EPR units to start construction, at [[Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant#Unit 3|Olkiluoto]] in Finland and [[Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant|Flamanville]] in France, are both facing costly delays (to 2021 and 2023, respectively).<ref name=wnn-20191219>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/System-tests-further-delay-Finnish-EPR-start-up |title=System tests further delay Finnish EPR start-up |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=19 December 2019 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=wnn-20191009>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-warns-of-added-costs-of-Flamanville-EPR-weld-r |title=EDF warns of added costs of Flamanville EPR weld repairs |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=10 October 2019 |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> Two units at [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station|Hinkley Point]] in the United Kingdom received final approval in September 2016 and are expected to be completed around 2026.<ref name=\"guardian-20160915\"/><ref name=wnn-20190925>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Hinkley-Point-C-cost-rises-by-nearly-15 |title=Hinkley Point C cost rises by nearly 15% |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=25 September 2019 |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nEDF has acknowledged severe difficulties in building the EPR design. In September 2015 EDF stated that the design of a \"New Model\" EPR was being worked on, which will be easier and cheaper to build.<ref name=\"independent-20150923\"/>\n\n==Design==\n===First EPR design===\nThe main design objectives of the [[Generation III reactor|third generation]] EPR design are increased safety while providing enhanced economic competitiveness through improvements to previous [[pressurised water reactor]] designs scaled up to an electrical power output of around 1650&nbsp;[[MWe]] (net)<ref name=\"areva-fieldrep-20101006\">{{cite web |url=http://www.areva.com/mediatheque/liblocal/docs/pdf/energies/pdf-field-report-3-va.pdf |page=4 |title=New Build Field Report |date=6 October 2010 |publisher=Areva |accessdate=5 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521234633/http://www.areva.com/mediatheque/liblocal/docs/pdf/energies/pdf-field-report-3-va.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> with thermal power of 4500&nbsp;MW. The reactor can use [[enriched uranium|5% enriched uranium oxide]] fuel, [[reprocessed uranium]] fuel or 100%&nbsp;[[MOX fuel|mixed uranium plutonium oxide]] fuel. The EPR is the evolutionary descendant of the [[Framatome]] N4 and [[Siemens AG|Siemens Power Generation Division]] \"Konvoi\" reactors.<ref name=\"EPR-presentation\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iaea.org/NuclearPower/Downloads/INPRO/Files/2010-Feb-DF-WS/15-Teller.pdf |format=PDF |title=The EPR Reactor: Evolution to Gen III+ based on proven technology |author=Andrew Teller |publisher=Areva |date=2 February 2010 |accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"EPR-brochure\">{{cite web |url=http://www.areva-np.com/common/liblocal/docs/Brochure/EPR_US_%20May%202005.pdf |format=PDF |title=EPR \u2013 Areva brochure |publisher=Areva NP |date=May 2005 |accessdate=2 January 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129121411/http://www.areva-np.com/common/liblocal/docs/Brochure/EPR_US_%20May%202005.pdf |archive-date=29 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Siemens ceased its nuclear activities in 2011.<ref name=\"DeutscheWelle1\">{{cite web|last1=Borrud|first1=Gabriel|title=Siemens to quit nuclear industry|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-to-quit-nuclear-industry/a-15396964|website=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\nThe EPR was designed to use [[uranium]] more efficiently than older [[Generation II reactor]]s, using approximately 17% less uranium per unit of electricity generated than these older reactor technologies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Forsythe|first=Jan|title=3 R's of Nuclear Power: Reading, Recycling, and Reprocessing: ...Making a Better Tomorrow for Little Joe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LZ7zBwWLyLEC&pg=PA126|year=2009|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4389-6731-8|page=126}}</ref>\n\nThe design had gone through a number of iterations. The 1994 conceptual design had a power output of 1450 MWe, the same as the Framatome N4, but using Siemens Konvoi derived instrumentation and including a new [[core catcher]] safety system. In 1995 there was concern over excessive cost per MW, and output was increased to 1800 MWe in the 2007 design, though this was subsequently reduced to 1650 MWe in the final certified design.<ref name=thomas-2010>{{cite report |url=https://gala.gre.ac.uk/id/eprint/4699/3/(ITEM_4699)_THOMAS_2010-11-E-EPR.pdf |title=The EPR in Crisis |last=Thomas |first=Steve |publisher=University of Greenwich |date=November 2010 |access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe EPR design has several active and passive protection measures against accidents:\n*Four independent emergency cooling systems, each providing the required cooling of the [[decay heat]] that continues for 1 to 3 years after the reactor's initial shutdown (i.e., 300% redundancy)<ref name=\"ShirzadiJackson2014\">{{cite book|author1=A. Shirzadi|author2=S. Jackson|title=Structural Alloys for Power Plants: Operational Challenges and High-Temperature Materials|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_SN0AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA94|date=30 July 2014|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-85709-755-2|pages=94\u2013}}</ref>\n*Leaktight containment around the reactor\n*An extra container and cooling area if a molten core manages to escape the reactor (see [[containment building]] and [[core catcher]])\n*Two-layer concrete wall with total thickness 2.6&nbsp;m, designed to withstand impact by aeroplanes and internal overpressure\n\nThe EPR has a design maximum [[core damage frequency]] of 6.1&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;10<sup>\u22127</sup> per station per year.<ref>''[http://www.epr-reactor.co.uk/ssmod/liblocal/docs/V3/Volume%202%20-%20Design%20and%20Safety/2.R%20-%20Probabilistic%20Safety%20Assessment/2.R.1%20-%20Level%201%20Probabilistic%20Safety%20Assessment%20-%20v2.pdf EPR Level 1 Probabilistic Safety Assessment]''. Author: UK EPR.</ref>\n\nThe EPR has a single [[steam turbine]] capable of using all the steam generated.<ref name=wnn-20180620>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-GE-Power-starts-Arabelle-production-for-Hinkley-Point-C-20061802.html |title=GE Power starts Arabelle production for Hinkley Point C |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=20 June 2018 |accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===\"New Model\" EPR design===\n{{as of|2013|alt=In 2013}} EDF acknowledged the difficulties it was having building the EPR design, with its head of production and engineering, Herv\u00e9 Machenaud, saying EDF had lost its dominant international position in design and construction of nuclear power stations. Machenaud indicated EDF was considering designing two new lower powered reactors, one with output of 1,500&nbsp;MWe and the other 1,000&nbsp;MWe. Machenaud stated there would be a period of reflection on the best way to improve the EPR design to lower its price and incorporate [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|post-Fukushima]] safety improvements.<ref name=\"reuters-20130321\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/21/edf-reactors-idUSL6N0CD1J820130321 |title=EDF eyes development of new, smaller reactors - papers |publisher=Reuters |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015 EDF's chief executive [[Jean-Bernard L\u00e9vy]] stated that the design of a \"New Model\" EPR, or \"EPR 2\",<ref name=edf-epr>{{cite web |url=https://www.edf.fr/en/the-edf-group/our-energies/nuclear/epr/designing-and-building-the-nuclear-plant-of-tomorrow |title=EPR: showcasing French nuclear expertise |publisher=EDF |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> was being worked on, which will be easier to build, to be ready for orders from about 2020,<ref name=\"independent-20150923\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/only-china-wants-to-invest-in-britains-new-2bn-hinkley-point-nuclear-plant-because-no-one-else-10513752.html |title=Only China wants to invest in Britain's new \u00a32bn Hinkley Point nuclear station because no one else thinks it will work, EDF admits |author=Geert De Clercq |newspaper=The Independent |date=23 September 2015 |accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref> describing it in 2016 as \"a reactor offering the same characteristics as today\u2019s EPR but it will be cheaper to build with optimised construction times and costs\".<ref name=\"theenergycollective-20161018\">{{cite web |url=https://www.energycentral.com/c/ec/interview-jean-bernard-l%C3%A9vy-ceo-edf-our-future-lies-combination-nuclear-and |title=Interview Jean-Bernard L\u00e9vy, CEO EDF: \"Our Future Lies in Combination Nuclear and Renewables\" |publisher=the energycollective |date=18 October 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 EDF planned to build two New Model EPR reactors in France by 2030 to prepare for renewing its fleet of older reactors.<ref name=reuters-20160121>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/edf-nuclear-epr/edf-plans-two-new-nuclear-reactors-in-france-by-2030-document-idUKL8N1554S4 |title=EDF plans two new nuclear reactors in France by 2030-document |publisher=Reuters |date=21 January 2016 |accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> However following financial difficulties at Areva, and its merger with EDF, French Ecology Minister [[Nicolas Hulot]] said in January 2018 \"for now [building a New Model EPR] is neither a priority or a plan. Right now the priority is to develop renewable energy and to reduce the share of nuclear.\"<ref name=reuters-20180122>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/france-nuclear/update-1-separate-unit-for-edf-nuclear-arm-has-been-discussed-says-minister-hulot-idUSL8N1PH4D6 |title=UPDATE 1-Separate unit for EDF nuclear arm has been discussed, says minister Hulot |publisher=Reuters |date=22 January 2018 |accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> The industry-government plan for 2019\u20132022 included work on \"a new version of the EPR\".<ref name=wnn-20190128>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/French-nuclear-industry-sets-medium-term-plans |title=French nuclear industry sets medium-term plans |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=28 January 2019 |accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 the French nuclear safety authority [[Autorit\u00e9 de s\u00fbret\u00e9 nucl\u00e9aire|ASN]] issued an opinion on the safety of an outline EPR New Model (EPR 2) design. It found that general safety was on the whole satisfactory, though identifying areas for further examination. The most notable simplification is a single layer containment building as opposed to the EPR\u2019s double layer. ASN highlighted that the EPR design basis assumption that primary and secondary cooling circuit piping could not fail may no longer be appropriate for the simplified EPR 2, and requires additional safety demonstrations.<ref name=reuters-20190718>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-edf-nuclearpower/french-regulator-to-edf-dont-assume-new-reactor-model-is-accident-proof-idUSKCN1UD2W0 |title=French regulator to EDF: don't assume new reactor model is accident-proof |author=Geert De Clercq |publisher=Reuters |date=18 July 2019 |accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=asn-20190729>{{cite web |url=http://www.french-nuclear-safety.fr/Information/News-releases/ASN-issues-its-opinion-on-the-safety-options-for-the-EPR-New-model-reactor-and-its-EPR-2-upgrade |title=ASN issues its opinion on the safety options for the EPR New model reactor and its EPR 2 upgrade |publisher=ASN |date=29 July 2019 |accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 Energy Minister [[\u00c9lisabeth Borne]] announced the government would not decide on the construction of any new reactors until the much delayed [[Flamanville 3]] started operation after 2022.  EDF had estimated building six EPR 2 nuclear reactors would cost at least \u20ac46&nbsp;billion.<ref name=nei-20200114>{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsfrance-to-decide-on-new-nuclear-build-after-2022-7598148 |title=France to decide on new nuclear build after 2022 |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=14 January 2020 |access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Olkiluoto 3 (Finland)==\n{{See also|Nuclear power in Finland|Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant}}\n[[File:OL3.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Olkiluoto-3 under construction in 2009. It is scheduled to start regular electricity generation in 2021, a delay of twelve years.<ref name=\"wnn-20191219\"/>]]\nThe construction of the [[Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant|Olkiluoto]] 3<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ol3.areva-np.com/ |title=OLKILUOTO 3 PROJECT by AREVA |access-date=24 July 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210133742/http://www.ol3.areva-np.com/ |archive-date=10 February 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> power station in Finland commenced in August 2005. The station will have an electrical power output of 1600&nbsp;[[MWe]] (net).<ref name=\"areva-fieldrep-20101006\" /> The construction was a joint effort of French [[Areva]] and German [[Siemens AG]] through their common subsidiary Areva NP, for Finnish operator [[Teollisuuden Voima|TVO]]. Siemens ceased nuclear activities in 2011. Initial cost estimates were about \u20ac3.7&nbsp;billion,<ref>{{cite web | title=EPR IN FINLAND: FOUNDATION STONE-LAYING DAY AT OLKILUOTO 3 | website=de.framatome-anp.com | date=2006-10-18 | url=http://www.de.framatome-anp.com/anp/e/foa/anp/press/anp054.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018024548/http://www.de.framatome-anp.com/anp/e/foa/anp/press/anp054.htm | archive-date=2006-10-18 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> but the project has since seen several severe cost increments and delays, with latest cost estimates (from 2012) of more than \u20ac8&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.helsinkitimes.fi/business/8486-daily-olkiluoto-3-may-cost-over-8bn.html|title=Daily: Olkiluoto 3 may cost over \u20ac8bn|last=HT|website=www.helsinkitimes.fi|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref> The station was initially scheduled to go online in 2009,<ref>{{cite web | title=Olkiluoto 3 \"Chronology of the Project\" | website=ol3.areva-np.com | date=2007-09-27 | url=http://www.ol3.areva-np.com/project/chrono.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927094543/http://www.ol3.areva-np.com/project/chrono.htm | archive-date=2007-09-27 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> but operations are now expected to start in 2021.<ref name=\"wnn-20191219\"/>\n\nIn May 2006, construction delays of about one year were announced, following quality control problems across the construction. In part the delays were due to the lack of oversight of subcontractors inexperienced in nuclear construction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsregulator-reports-as-ol3-delays-reach-one-year/|title=Regulator reports as OL3 delays reach one year|date=2006-07-19|website=Nuclear Engineering International|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsconcrete-composition-delays-finland-s-olkiluoto-3/|title=Concrete composition delays Finland's Olkiluoto 3|date=2006-05-09|website=Nuclear Engineering International|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> The delays led to disappointing financial results for the Areva NP. It blamed delays on the Finnish approach to approving technical documentation and designs.<ref>{{cite web | title=Areva's first half results hit by Olkiluoto 3 delays | website=Nuclear Engineering International | date=2007-09-27 | url=http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectioncode=132&storyCode=2039298 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927190831/http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectioncode=132&storyCode=2039298 | archive-date=2007-09-27 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.largeassociates.com/3149%20Olkiluoto/R3149-A1%20Final%20Issue.pdf|title=European Pressurised Reactor at Olkiluoto 3, Finland \u2013 Brief & Interim Review of the Porosity and Durability Properties of the In Situ Cast Concrete at the Olkiluoto EPR Construction Site|date=2006-06-08|website=Large and Associates|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927034349/http://www.largeassociates.com/3149%20Olkiluoto/R3149-A1%20Final%20Issue.pdf|archive-date=2007-09-27|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, TVO announced construction was about 18 months behind schedule so completion was now expected 2010\u201311, and there were reports that Areva was preparing to take a \u20ac500&nbsp;million charge on its accounts for the delay.<ref>{{cite web | title=Finland nuclear reactor delayed again | website=MSN.com | date=2006-12-04 | url=http://news.moneycentral.msn.com/provider/providerarticle.aspx?Feed=AP&Date=20061204&ID=6245665 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308085958/http://news.moneycentral.msn.com/provider/providerarticle.aspx?Feed=AP&Date=20061204&ID=6245665 | archive-date=2007-03-08 | url-status=dead }}{{deadlink|date=August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Areva to take 500 mln eur charge for Finnish reactor delay | website=Forbes.com | date=2006-12-05 | url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/afx/2006/12/05/afx3228309.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603234546/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/afx/2006/12/05/afx3228309.html | archive-date=2011-06-03 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of June 2007, it was reported that [[Radiation and Nuclear Safety Authority|S\u00e4teilyturvakeskus]] (STUK), the Finnish Radiation and Nuclear Safety Authority, had found a number of safety-related design and manufacturing 'deficiencies'.<ref>{{cite web | title=Nuclear industry revival hits roadblocks | website=New Scientist | date=2007-07-01 | url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn12167-nuclear-industry-revival-hits-roadblocks/ | access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> In August 2007, a further construction delay of up to a year was reported associated with construction problems in reinforcing the reactor building to withstand an aeroplane crash, and the timely supply of adequate documentation to the Finnish authorities.<ref>{{cite web | title=Dates revised again for Olkiluoto 3 | website=World Nuclear News | date=2007-08-10 | url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newNuclear/Dates_revised_again_for_Olkiluoto_3_100807.shtml | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huliq.com/30247/nuclear-industrys-flagship-plant-delayed-again|title=Nuclear industry's flagship plant delayed again|last=Anastvatz|date=2007-08-11|website=HULIQ|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b48f8022-4762-11dc-9096-0000779fd2ac|title=Areva delay threatens China contract|last=Hollinger|first=Peggy|date=2007-08-11|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, TVO reported the construction delay as \"at least two years\" and costs more than 25% over budget.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aFh1ySJ.lYQc |title=Nuclear Bid to Rival Coal Chilled by Flaws, Delay in Finland |author=Alan Katz |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=5 September 2007|accessdate=17 June 2008}}</ref> Cost estimates by analysts for the overrun range up to \u20ac1.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/newstex/AFX-0013-21958415.htm Areva-Siemens sees Olkiluoto 3 reactor operational in summer 2011]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[CNN]], 31 December 2007.</ref>\n\nA further delay was announced in October 2008, making the total delay three years, giving an expected online date of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/10/17/business/EU-Finland-Nuclear-Plant.php |title=3-year delay expected at Finnish nuclear plant |work=International Herald Tribune |date=17 October 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2008}}</ref> The parties are in arbitration to resolve a dispute over responsibility for the delays and final cost overruns.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/a144c686-9b9d-11dd-ae76-000077b07658.html |title=Areva in talks with TVO over EPR delays |author=Peggy Hollinger |work=Financial Times |date=16 October 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/tvo-arevasiemens/finland-nuclear-reactor-costs-headed-to-arbitration-tvo-idUKLV55678920081231 |title=Finland nuclear reactor costs headed to arbitration \u2013 TVO |publisher=Reuters |date=31 December 2008 |accessdate=5 January 2009 | first=Sakari | last=Suoninen}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2009|5}}, the station was at least three and a half years behind schedule and more than 50 percent over-budget. [[Areva]] and the utility involved \"are in bitter dispute over who will bear the cost overruns and there is a real risk now that the utility will default\".<ref name=tom>{{Cite web|url=http://www.salem-news.com/articles/may212009/us_nuke_race_5-21-09.php|title=U.K. Expert Says U.S. Is Not LOSING International Nuclear Power 'Race'|website=Salem-News|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> In August 2009, Areva announced \u20ac550&nbsp;million additional provisions for the build, taking station costs to \u20ac5.3&nbsp;billion, and wiped out interim operating profits for the first half-year of 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/0c9b59aa-9665-11de-84d1-00144feabdc0.html|title=Finnish reactor provisions hit Areva profits|author=Peggy Hollinger|date=31 August 2009|work=Financial Times|accessdate=1 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe dome of the containment structure was topped out in September 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.areva.com/servlet/cp_ol3_06_09_2009-c-PressRelease-cid-1251741544566-en.html | title = Olkiluoto 3: EPR dome installed | publisher = AREVA NC | date=6 August 2009 | accessdate=1 November 2009}}</ref> 90% of procurement, 80% of engineering works and 73% of civil works were completed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oJhyoZ8R4Ko | title=AREVA \u2013 Olkiluoto 3 : EPR dome installed | publisher = YouTube | date=10 August 2008 | accessdate=29 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, Areva announced \u20ac400&nbsp;million of further provisions, taking the cost overrun to \u20ac2.7&nbsp;billion. The timescale slipped from June 2012 to the end of 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mineweb.co.za/mineweb/view/mineweb/en/page72103?oid=107035&sn=Detail&pid=102055 |title=S&P downgrades French nuclear-uranium giant AREVA on weakened profitability |author=Dorothy Kosich |publisher=Mineweb |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004210130/http://www.mineweb.co.za/mineweb/view/mineweb/en/page72103?oid=107035&sn=Detail&pid=102055 |archivedate=4 October 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-06-24/areva-s-overruns-at-finnish-nuclear-plant-approach-initial-cost.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100907020504/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-06-24/areva-s-overruns-at-finnish-nuclear-plant-approach-initial-cost.html |publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek |title=Areva\u2019s Overruns at Finnish Nuclear Station Approach Initial Cost with operation set to start in 2013 |date=24 June 2010 |archivedate=7 September 2010 |first=Fran\u00e7ois |last=De Beaupuy }}</ref><ref name=\"wnn-20100608\">{{cite news |title=Start-up of Finnish EPR pushed back to 2013 |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=8 June 2010 |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Startup_of_Finnish_EPR_pushed_back_to_2013-0806104.html |accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref> In December 2011, TVO announced a further delay to August 2014.<ref name=\"reuters-20111221\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/12/21/finland-olkiluoto-idUSL6E7NL2DI20111221 |title=Finland's Olkiluoto 3 reactor delayed to August 2014 |publisher=Reuters |date=21 December 2011 |accessdate=21 December 2011 |first=Ritsuko |last=Ando}}</ref> As of July 2012, the station was scheduled to start electricity production no earlier than 2015, a schedule slippage of at least six years.<ref name = \"world-nuclear-news20120716\">{{cite news | title = Olkiluoto 3 delayed beyond 2014 | publisher = World Nuclear News | date = 17 July 2012 | url = https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Olkiluoto_3_delayed_beyond_2014-1707124.html | accessdate = 31 July 2012}}</ref> In December 2012 Areva's Chief Executive estimated costs to \u20ac8&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news | title = Costs of Finland's Olkiluoto nuclear reactor go up yet again | publisher = Nuclear-news | date = 14 December 2012 | url = http://nuclear-news.net/2012/12/14/costs-of-finlands-olkiluoto-nuclear-reactor-go-up-yet-again/ | accessdate = 6 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014 Areva announced that operations would start in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Olkiluoto-3-start-up-pushed-back-to-2018-0109147.html|title=Olkiluoto 3 startup pushed back to 2018|date=1 September 2014|work=World Nuclear News|accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> In October 2017 the date was pushed back to the beginning of 2019.<ref>{{Cite News|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-09/finland-s-10-year-wait-for-a-new-nuclear-reactor-just-got-longer|title=Finland\u2019s 10-Year Wait for a Nuclear Reactor Just Got Longer|publisher=Bloomberg|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010211648/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-09/finland-s-10-year-wait-for-a-new-nuclear-reactor-just-got-longer|archive-date=October 10, 2017|url-status=live|date= 9 October 2017|access-date = 10 October 2017}}</ref> During testing in 2018 and 2019 three further delays were announced, of over a year in total.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Start-up-of-Finnish-EPR-put-back-four-months-1406184.html |title=Start-up of Finnish EPR put back four months |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=14 June 2018 |accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/New-delay-in-start-up-of-Finnish-EPR |title=New delay in start-up of Finnish EPR |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=29 November 2018 |accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Olkiluoto-faces-further-delay-to-July-2020 |title=Olkiluoto faces further delay to July 2020 |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=18 July 2019 |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019 the commissioning schedule was revised again: regular electricity generation is due to start in March 2021.<ref name=\"wnn-20191219\" />\n\n==Flamanville 3 (France)==\n{{See also|Nuclear power in France|Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant}}\n[[File:Flamanville-3 2010-07-15.jpg|thumb|EDF has said its Flamanville 3 project (seen here in 2010) will be delayed until 2023.<ref name=\"wnn-20191009\" />]]\n\nFirst concrete was poured for the demonstration EPR reactor at the [[Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant]] on 6 December 2007.<ref>''Nuclear Engineering International''. [https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsflamanville-3-concrete-poured/ Flamanville 3 concrete poured] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613091002/http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectionCode=132&storyCode=2048041 |date=13 June 2011 }}</ref>\nAs the name implies, this will be the third nuclear reactor on the Flamanville site, and the second instance of an EPR being built. Electrical output will be 1630&nbsp;MWe (net).<ref name=\"areva-fieldrep-20101006\" /> The project was planned to involve around \u20ac3.3&nbsp;billion of capital expenditure from [[\u00c9lectricit\u00e9 de France|EDF]],<ref name=\"EDF-F3-project\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edf.fr/html/epr/uk/projet.html |title=EDF Official Site \u2013 Flamanville 3 |publisher=Edf.fr | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630101014/http://energy.edf.com/edf-fr-accueil/edf-and-power-generation/nuclear-power/the-future-of-nuclear-power/epr-y-flamanville-3/the-flamanville-3-project-122321.html |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archive-date=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> but latest cost estimates (from 2019) are at \u20ac12.4&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"wnn-20191009\" />\n\nFrom 19 October 2005 to 18 February 2006, the project was submitted to a national public debate. On 4 May 2006, the decision was made by EDF's Board of Directors to continue with the construction. Between 15 June and 31 July 2006, the unit underwent a public enquiry, which rendered a \"favourable opinion\" on the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://construction.ecnext.com/coms2/summary_0249-218321_ITM_platts |title=Public inquiry commission favours plan to build Flamanville-3 EPR |date=5 October 2006 |work=Nucleonics Week |accessdate=17 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929135733/http://construction.ecnext.com/coms2/summary_0249-218321_ITM_platts |archivedate=29 September 2007 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> That summer, site preparation works began.\n\nIn December 2007 construction of the unit itself began. This was expected to last 54 months, with commissioning planned for 2012.<ref name=\"EDF-F3-project\" />\n\nIn April 2008, the French nuclear safety authority (''[[Autorit\u00e9 de s\u00fbret\u00e9 nucl\u00e9aire]]'', ASN) reported that a quarter of the welds inspected in the secondary containment steel liner are not in accordance with norms, and that cracks have been found in the concrete base. EDF stated that progress was being made on these issues, which were raised very early in construction;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/defects-found-in-nuclear-reactor-the-french-want-to-build-in-britain-808461.html |title=Defects found in nuclear reactor the French want to build in Britain |author1=Geoffrey Lean |author2=Jonathan Owen |date=13 April 2008 |work=The Independent |accessdate=19 April 2004 |location=London}}</ref> however, on 21 May, ASN ordered a suspension of concrete pouring on the site.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssIndustryMaterialsUtilitiesNews/idUSL2762459720080527 |title=French nuke body partly halts work on new reactor |date=27 May 2008 |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=27 May 2008}}</ref> A month later, concreting work resumed after ASN accepted EDF's corrective action plan, which included external oversight checks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS_EdF_allowed_to_continue_concreting_2006081.html |title= EdF allowed to continue concreting |date=20 June 2008 |publisher=World Nuclear News |accessdate=21 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, professor [[Stephen Thomas (professor)|Stephen Thomas]] reported that after 18 months of construction, and after a series of quality control problems, the project is \"more than 20 percent over budget and EDF is struggling to keep it on schedule\".<ref name=\"tom\"/>\n\nIn August 2010, the regulator, ASN, reported further welding problems on the secondary containment steel liner.<ref name=\"bloomberg-20100830\" /> The same month, EDF announced that costs had increased 50% to \u20ac5&nbsp;billion, and commissioning was delayed by about two years to 2014.<ref name=\"bloomberg-20100830\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-30/edf-has-welding-problems-at-flamanville-epr-reactor-french-watchdog-says.html |title=French Nuclear Watchdog Says EDF Has Problems With Flamanville EPR Liner |author=Tara Patel |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=30 August 2010 |accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, EDF announced that the estimated costs had escalated to \u20ac6&nbsp;billion, and that completion of construction was delayed to 2016.<ref name=neimagazine>\n{{Cite news | url = https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsedf-delays-flamanville-3-epr-project-/ | agency= Nuclear Engineering International | date=20 July 2011 | title= EDF delays Flamanville 3 EPR project | accessdate=21 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 December 2012, EDF announced that the estimated costs had escalated to \u20ac8.5&nbsp;billion.<ref name=lemonde>\n{{Cite news | url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2012/12/03/le-cout-de-l-epr-de-flamanville-encore-revu-a-la-hausse_1799417_3244.html | agency=Le Monde | date=3 December 2012 | title=Le co\u00fbt de l'EPR de Flamanville encore revu \u00e0 la hausse| accessdate=4 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, the Italian power company [[Enel]] announced it was relinquishing its 12.5% stake in the project, and five future EPRs, so would be reimbursed its project stake of \u20ac613&nbsp;million, plus interest.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.powermag.com/enel-drops-participation-in-flamanville-epr-as-project-costs-soar-by-2-6b/ |title=Enel Drops Participation in Flamanville EPR as Project Costs Soar by $2.6B |newspaper=POWER |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enel.com/en-GB/media/press_releases/enel-and-edf-terminate-their-cooperation-on-epr-in-france/r/1656525 |title=Enel and Edf Terminate their cooperation on EPR in France |publisher=Enel |date=4 December 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, EDF announced that completion of construction was delayed to 2017, due to delays in component delivery by Areva.<ref name=\"ft-20141118\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/adc90b3e-6f67-11e4-8d86-00144feabdc0.html |title=EDF in fresh delay for flagship nuclear plant |author=Michael Stothard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=18 November 2014 |accessdate=21 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Areva informed the French nuclear regulator ASN that anomalies had been detected in the reactor vessel steel, causing \"lower than expected mechanical toughness values\". Further tests are underway.<ref name=\"wnn-20150407\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-Flamanville-EPR-vessel-anomalies-under-scrutiny-0704154.html |title=Flamanville EPR vessel anomalies under scrutiny |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=7 April 2015 |accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref> In July 2015 [[The Daily Telegraph]] reported that Areva had been aware of this problem since 2006.<ref name=\"telegraph-20150709\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/earth/energy/nuclearpower/11727000/Areva-aware-as-early-as-2006-of-serious-fault-in-nuclear-reactor-destined-for-UK.html |title=Areva aware 'as early as 2006' of serious fault in nuclear reactor destined for UK |author=Henry Samuel |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=9 July 2015 |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, multiple faults in cooling system safety valves were discovered by ASN.<ref name=\"telegraph-20150609\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/11662889/Faulty-valves-in-new-generation-EPR-nuclear-reactor-pose-meltdown-risk-inspectors-warn.html |title=Faulty valves in new-generation EPR nuclear reactor pose meltdown risk, inspectors warn |author=Henry Samuel |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=9 June 2015 |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, EDF announced that the estimated costs had escalated to \u20ac10.5&nbsp;billion, and the start-up of the reactor was delayed to the fourth quarter of 2018.<ref>{{cite web | title=Flamanville EPR: optimised project management and a new timetable | website=EDF France | date=2015-09-03 | url=https://www.edf.fr/en/edf/flamanville-epr-optimised-project-management-and-a-new-timetable | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, ASN announced that additional weak spots had been found in the reactor steel, and Areva and EDF responded that new tests would be conducted, though construction work would continue.<ref name=\"nei-20160412\">{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newseprs-to-face-more-tests-4862270 |title=EPRs to face more tests |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=12 April 2016 |accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, the [[Financial Times]] stated the project was six years late, and \u20ac7.2&nbsp;billion over budget,<ref name=ft-20170214>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/416a2c9c-f2d3-11e6-8758-6876151821a6 |title=Downfall of Toshiba, a nuclear industry titan |newspaper=Financial Times |date=14 February 2017 |accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref> while renewed delays in the construction of the EPR-reactors at [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant]] prompted EDF to state that Flamanville 3 remains on schedule to start operations by the end of 2018, assuming it receives regulatory approval.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/international-business/edf-confirms-flamanville-timetable-after-taishan-epr-delay/articleshow/57294950.cms |title= EDF confirms Flamanville timetable after Taishan EPR delay |work= [[Times of India]] |date= 2017-02-22 |accessdate= 2017-03-09}}</ref> In June 2017, the French regulator issued a provisional ruling that Flamanville 3 is safe to start.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-French-regulator-says-Flamanville-3-is-safe-to-start-29061701.html |title= French regulator says Flamanville 3 is safe to start |publisher=World Nuclear News |date= 28 June 2017 |accessdate= 3 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe discovery of quality deviations in the welding led to a further revision of the schedule in July 2018. Fuel loading was delayed until the end of 2019, and the cost estimate was increased from \u20ac10.5&nbsp;billion to \u20ac10.9&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-revises-schedule,-costs-of-Flamanville-EPR |title= EDF revises schedule, costs of Flamanville EPR |publisher=World Nuclear News |date= 25 July 2018 |accessdate= 30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019 the regulator ASN determined that eight welds in steam transfer pipes passing through the two wall containment, that EDF had hoped to repair after startup, must be repaired before the reactor is commissioned.<ref>{{cite web |title=Deviations on the Flamanville EPR steam lines: the eight penetration welds will have to be repaired |url=http://www.french-nuclear-safety.fr/Information/News-releases/Deviations-on-the-Flamanville-EPR-steam-lines-the-eight-penetration-welds-will-have-to-be-repaired |website=ASN |accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=wnn-20190620>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Weld-repairs-to-delay-Flamanville-EPR-start-up |title=Weld repairs to delay Flamanville EPR start-up |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=20 June 2019 |accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> In October 2019 EDF announced that because of this issue costs would increase to \u20ac12.4&nbsp;billion and that fuel loading would be delayed until the end of 2022 (with regular electricity generation starting in 2023 at the earliest).<ref name=\"wnn-20191009\" />\n\n==Taishan 1 and 2 (China)==\n{{See also|Nuclear power in China|Taishan Nuclear Power Plant}}\nIn 2006, Areva took part in the first bidding process for the construction of four new nuclear reactors in China, together with Toshiba-owned [[Westinghouse Electric Company|Westinghouse]] and Russian [[Atomstroyexport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.people.cn/200409/12/eng20040912_156691.html |title=Foreign energy giants bid for China's nuclear contracts |work=People's Daily |date=12 September 2004 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> However Areva lost this bid in favour of Westinghouse's [[AP1000]] reactors, in part because of Areva's refusal to transfer the expertise and knowledge to China.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nSubsequently Areva managed to win a deal in February 2007, worth about \u20ac8&nbsp;billion ($10.5&nbsp;billion) for two EPRs located in [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant|Taishan]], [[Guangdong|Guangdong Province]] in southern China, in spite of sticking to its previous conditions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Areva-lands-world-s-biggest-ever-nuclear-power-ord |title=Areva lands world's biggest ever nuclear power order |date=26 November 2007 |work=World Nuclear News |accessdate=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413014154/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=14454&LangType=2057 |archive-date=13 April 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/business/feeds/afx/2007/07/30/afx3965097.html |title=Signing of Areva EPR order in China delayed \u2013 French source |date=30 July 2007 |work=Forbes |accessdate=1 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215151621/http://www.forbes.com/business/feeds/afx/2007/07/30/afx3965097.html |archivedate=15 December 2008 }}</ref> The [[General Contractor]] and [[Operator (profession)|Operator]] is the [[China General Nuclear Power Group]] (CGN).\n\nThe construction of the first reactor at [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant|Taishan]] started officially on 18 November 2009, and the second on 15 April 2010.<ref name=\"IAEA-PRIS-china\">{{cite web |title=China, People's Republic of: Nuclear Power Reactors |url=http://www.iaea.org/cgi-bin/db.page.pl/pris.powrea.htm?country=CN |work=PRIS database |publisher=[[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA) |accessdate=18 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620074942/http://www.iaea.org/cgi-bin/db.page.pl/pris.powrea.htm?country=CN |archivedate=20 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nConstruction of each unit was then planned to take 46&nbsp;months, significantly faster and cheaper than the first two EPRs in Finland and France.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-24/china-builds-french-designed-nuclear-reactor-for-40-less-areva-ceo-says.html | title= China Builds Nuclear Reactor for 40% Less Than Cost in France, Areva Says | first= Tara | last= Patel |author2=Fran\u00e7ois de Beaupuy |date= 24 November 2010|publisher= [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | accessdate=2 December 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[reactor pressure vessel]] of the first reactor was installed in June 2012,<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.areva.com/EN/news-9361/china-the-construction-of-the-epr-reactor-unit-1-at-taishan-takes-a-major-step-forward-with-the-installation-of-the-vessel.html | title= China: The Construction of the EPR reactor Unit 1 at Taishan Takes a Major Step Forward with the Installation of the Vessel |date= 5 June 2012|publisher= [[AREVA]] | accessdate=5 June 2012 }}</ref> and the second in November 2014. The first pressure vessel had been imported from [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] in Japan, and [[Steam generator (nuclear power)|steam generators]] from Areva in France. The second pressure vessel and associated steam generators had been made in China, by [[Dongfang Electric]] and [[Shanghai Electric]].<ref name=\"wnn-20141105\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Construction-milestone-at-Taishan-2-EPR-0511141.html |title=Construction milestone at Taishan 2 EPR |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 construction was reported to be running over two years late, mainly due to key component delays and project management issues.<ref name=\"nei-20150223\">{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/opinion/opinionhow-serious-are-the-delays-in-chinas-nuclear-programme-4517469/ |title=How serious are the delays in China's nuclear programme? |author=Steve Kidd |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=23 February 2015 |accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nCold function tests were performed on Taishan 1 in February 2016, with start up expected in the first half of 2017. Taishan 2 was scheduled to start up later that year.<ref name=\"wnn-20160201\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-First-Taishan-EPR-completes-cold-tests-0102164.html |title=First Taishan EPR completes cold tests |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=1 February 2016 |accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\nHowever, commissioning dates were put back six months in February 2017, with commercial operation expected in the second half of 2017 and the first half of 2018.<ref name=wnn-20170222>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-China-revises-commissioning-dates-of-EPRs-2202174.html |title=China revises commissioning dates of EPRs |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=22 February 2017 |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Hong Kong media reported that a component had cracked during testing, needing to be replaced.<ref name=\"crackinkey\">{{cite news|title=Tests reveal crack in key component of Chinese nuclear power plant, 130 km west of Hong Kong|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2017/12/12/tests-reveal-crack-key-component-chinese-nuclear-power-plant-130km-west-hong-kong/|work=[[Hong Kong Free Press]]|agency=[[FactWire]]|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref>\nIn January 2018 commissioning was rescheduled again, with commercial operation expected in 2018 and 2019.<ref name=\"wnn-20180102\">{{cite news|url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Taishan-schedule-factors-in-commissioning-tests-0201181.html|title=Taishan schedule factors in commissioning tests|date=2 January 2018|accessdate=3 January 2018|publisher=World Nuclear News}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Taishan 1 achieved [[Criticality (status)|criticality]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-First-criticality-achieved-at-Chinese-EPR-0706184.html |title=First criticality achieved at Chinese EPR |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=7 June 2018 |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref> It entered commercial operation in December 2018.<ref name=wnn-20181214 /><ref>{{cite web |title=Bernard Fontana's statement - EPR: the first Generation III+ nuclear reactor enters commercial operation |url=http://www.framatome.com/EN/businessnews-1445/nbspbernard-fontana-s-statement-epr-the-first-generation-iii-nuclear-reactor-enters-commercial-operation.html |publisher=Framatome |date=14 December 2018 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> Taishan 2 reached these milestones in May 2019<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Second-Chinese-EPR-achieves-criticality |title=Second Chinese EPR achieves criticality - World Nuclear News |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=29 May 2019 |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> and September 2019,<ref name=wnn-20190909 /> respectively.\n\n==Hinkley Point C (United Kingdom)==\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the United Kingdom|Hinkley Point C nuclear power station}}\nThe EPR underwent Generic Design Assessment by the [[Office for Nuclear Regulation]], along with the Westinghouse [[AP1000]].<ref>{{cite web|title=New Nuclear Power Stations \u2013 Progress so far|url=http://www.hse.gov.uk/newreactors/progress.htm|publisher=[[Health and Safety Executive]]|accessdate=15 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601205003/http://www.hse.gov.uk/newreactors/progress.htm|archive-date=1 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Interim Design Acceptance Confirmations were postponed until lessons from the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]] had been taken into account.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hse.gov.uk/newreactors/gda-japan.htm |title=News \u2013 Taking GDA work forward in the light of the unprecedented events in Japan |publisher=Hse.gov.uk |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228221748/http://www.hse.gov.uk/newreactors/gda-japan.htm |archive-date=28 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> EDF bought [[British Energy]] in 2009. EDF planned to build 4 new EPRs,<ref>{{cite web|author=This website was built by the EDF Energy WCM |url=http://www.edfenergy.com/about-us/energy-generation/nuclear.shtml |title=Nuclear Generation |publisher=Edfenergy.com |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> subject to electricity pricing agreement with the government.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nce.co.uk/news/energy/edf-still-undecided-about-hinkley-point-c-go-ahead/8646617.article?blocktitle=Exclusive-news-from-NCE-magazine&contentID=204 |title=EdF still undecided about Hinkley Point C go-ahead |author=Declan Lynch |newspaper=New Civil Engineer |date=18 April 2013 |accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph-20130418\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/10004699/EDF-prepared-to-let-UK-nuclear-talks-fail.html |title=EDF prepared to let UK nuclear talks fail |author=Andrew Trotman |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=18 April 2013 |accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref> Areva has signed a strategic partnership with [[Rolls-Royce plc|Rolls-Royce]] to support the build of EPRs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsareva-signs-up-rolls-royce-for-epr/ |title=Areva signs up Rolls-Royce for EPR |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=11 March 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> On 19 March 2013 planning consent for [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station]] was given,<ref name=\"bbc-20130320\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-21839684 |title=New nuclear power plant at Hinkley Point C is approved |publisher=BBC |date=20 March 2013 |accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> but difficult negotiations with the UK government about electricity pricing, and project financing with private investors, still needed to be concluded.<ref name=\"bbc-20130319\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-21774652 |title=What price nuclear power? The final hurdle for Hinkley |author=Dave Harvey |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2013 |accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October 2013, EDF Energy announced that an agreement had been reached regarding the nuclear stations to be built on the site of Hinkley Point C. EDF Group and the UK Government agreed on the key commercial terms of the investment contract. The final investment decision was conditional on completion of the remaining key steps, including the agreement of the [[European Commission]].\n\nOn 8 October 2014 the European Commission announced their agreement, with 16 out of 28 commissioners agreeing with the go ahead of the construction. On 21 September 2015 the British government announced it would provide a \u00a32&nbsp;billion support package for Hinkley Point C as Britain's first nuclear power station in 20 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-somerset-34306997|title=UK guarantees \u00a32bn China nuclear deal|last=|first=|date=2015-09-21|work=BBC News|access-date=2019-08-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October 2015, during Chinese [[Xi Jinping|president Xi Jinping's]] state visit to the United Kingdom, EDF and CGN signed an investment agreement for the \u00a318&nbsp;billion (\u20ac20&nbsp;billion) project to build two reactors at Hinkley Point.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/oct/21/hinkley-point-reactor-costs-rise-by-2bn-as-deal-confirmed|title=Work to begin on Hinkley Point reactor within weeks after China deal signed|last=Farrell|first=Sean|date=2015-10-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-11|last2=Macalister|first2=Terry|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> However, legally binding contracts had not been agreed yet.<ref name=\"guardian-20160309\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/mar/09/no-legally-binding-contract-18bn-hinkley-point-nuclear-project-edf-china |title=No legally binding contract in \u00a318bn Hinkley Point nuclear project |author=Terry Macalister |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 March 2016 |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, EDF managers told Members of Parliament that the Hinkley Point C proposal should be postponed, until it has \"solved a litany of problems\", including EDFs \"soaring debts\".<ref>Terry Macalister, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jun/17/edf-senior-managers-hinkley-point-postpone-letter-mps-energy-committee Hinkley Point should be postponed]\", ''The Guardian'', 18 June 2016.</ref> On 28 July 2016, after the resignation of a board member, the EDF board approved the project.<ref name=\"guardian-20160728\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jul/28/hinkley-point-c-to-go-ahead-after-edf-board-approves-project |title=Hinkley Point C in doubt after British government delays approval |author=Graham Ruddick |newspaper=The Guardian |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> However [[Greg Clark]], the new [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]] in the new [[First May ministry|government of Theresa May]], then announced that the government would not sign the contract over the next few days as expected, but delay the contract to autumn to \"consider carefully all the component parts of this project\".<ref name=\"telegraph-20160728\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/07/28/green-light-for-hinkley-point-as-new-18bn-nuclear-plant-approved/ |title=Government delays Hinkley nuclear decision despite EDF approval for \u00a318bn project |author=Emily Gosden |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> Final government approval was given in September 2016.<ref name=\"guardian-20160915\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/sep/15/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-station-gets-go-ahead |title=Hinkley Point C nuclear power station gets government green light |author1=Rowena Mason |author2=Simon Goodley |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 September 2016 |accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, following an internal review, EDF announced revised estimates for the scheme, which included at least \u00a31.5&nbsp;billion of additional costs and up to 15 months of additional programme, leading to updated total cost estimates of \u00a319.6-20.3&nbsp;billion (\u20ac21.9-22.6&nbsp;billion).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d4333820-5fcf-11e7-8814-0ac7eb84e5f1?mhq5j=e1 |title= EDF warns Hinkley Point could cost extra \u00a31.5bn |work= [[Financial Times]] |date= 2017-07-03 |accessdate= 2017-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globalconstructionreview.com/news/hinkley-nuclear-plant-already-15bn-over-budget-edf/|title= Hinkley nuclear plant already \u00a31.5bn over budget, EDF admits |work= Global Construction Review |date= 2017-07-03 |accessdate= 2017-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/07/03/hinkley-nuclear-costs-climb-almost-20bn-start-delayed/|title=Cost of Hinkley Point nuclear plant climbs another \u00a31.5bn to over \u00a320bn, as project faces further delay|last=Ambrose|first=Jillian|date=2017-07-03|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-09-17|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> In September 2019 cost estimates were revised again, to between \u00a321.5 and \u00a322.5&nbsp;billion (\u20ac24-25.1&nbsp;billion).<ref name=\"wnn-20190925\" />\n\n==Possible future power stations==\n\n===France===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in France|Penly Nuclear Power Plant|Gravelines Nuclear Power Plant}}\n\nIn July 2008 the French President announced a second EPR would be built in France due to high oil and gas prices.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second new reactor for France |publisher=World Nuclear News|date=3 July 2008 |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_Second_new_reactor_for_France_0307082.html |accessdate=3 July 2008}}</ref> [[Penly Nuclear Power Plant|Penly]] was chosen as the site in 2009, with construction planned to start in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sa.areva.com/EN/news-6760/areva-pleased-with-the-announcement-of-the-construction-of-france-s-second-epr.html|title=AREVA pleased with the announcement of the construction of France\u2019s second EPR\u2122|date=2009-01-30|website=www.sa.areva.com|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> However, in 2011, following the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]], EDF postponed public consultations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/04/france-nuclear-idUSL5E7L43HE20111004 |title=France says Penly reactor on course despite delays |date=4 October 2011 |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> In February 2013, the Minister of Industrial Renewal [[Arnaud Montebourg]] stated that the plans for a new EPR reactor at Penly had been cancelled, citing the capacity for electricity production and massive investments in [[renewable energy]] along with his confidence in the EPR as a competitive project in foreign countries.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://bfmbusiness.bfmtv.com/entreprise/pas-depr-a-centrale-penly-439064.html |title= Pas d'EPR \u00e0 la centrale de Penly |work= [[BFM Business]] |date= 2013-04-25 |accessdate= 2017-03-09 |language= fr |trans-title=No EPR at the Penly power plant}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://normandie.canalblog.com/archives/2013/02/03/26314510.html |title= Montebourg enterre l'EPR de Penly |website= normandie.canalblog.com |date= 2013-03-03 |accessdate= 2017-03-09 |language= fr |trans-title=Montebourg buries the Penly EPR }}</ref>\n\nPlans to build new reactors in France were later revived. In 2019, EDF plans to select a site for the installation of a pair of EPR reactors. [[Penly Nuclear Power Plant|Penly]] and [[Gravelines Nuclear Power Plant|Gravelines]] are among the candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lepoint.fr/economie/la-normandie-prete-a-accueillir-un-nouveau-reacteur-epr-06-03-2019-2298429_28.php|title=La Normandie pr\u00eate \u00e0 accueillir un nouveau r\u00e9acteur EPR|last=Beuve|first=Jean-Pierre|date=2019-03-06|website=Le Point|language=fr|trans-title=Normandy ready to welcome a new EPR reactor|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, newspaper ''[[Le Monde]]'' reported that the French government had sent EDF a \"mission letter\" in which it asked the company to prepare to build a total of six EPR reactors across three sites in the next 15 years.<ref name=\"reuters-20191014\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-edf-nuclear-epr/france-asks-edf-to-prepare-to-build-6-epr-reactors-in-15-years-le-monde-idUSKBN1WT27T |title=France asks EDF to prepare to build 6 EPR reactors in 15 years -Le Monde |publisher=Reuters |date=14 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===India===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in India|Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project}}\nIn February 2009, the [[Nuclear Power Corporation of India]] (NPCIL) signed a memorandum of understanding with Areva to set up two 1650&nbsp;MWe reactors at [[Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project|Jaitapur]] in Maharashtra. This was followed by a framework agreement in December 2010.<ref>[http://www.npcil.nic.in//pdf/news_07dec2010_Business_Line.pdf India, France ink pact for Areva reactors, fuel] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927225957/http://www.npcil.nic.in//pdf/news_07dec2010_Business_Line.pdf |date=27 September 2011 }} npcil.nic.in</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, during French president [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]]'s state visit to India a joint statement with Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] was issued. According to the statement the two leaders \"have agreed on a roadmap of cooperation to speed up discussions on the Jaitapur project in 2016. Their shared aim is to start the implementation of the project in early 2017.\"<ref name=\"wnn-201690125\">{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Jaitapur-agreement-due-by-year-end-2501165.html |title=Jaitapur agreement due by year-end |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=25 January 2016 |accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2018 an Industrial Way Forward Agreement between EDF and NPCIL was signed, with an objective of producing a tender later in the year.<ref name=wnn-20180312>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Way-forward-agreed-for-Jaitapur-reactors-1203187.html |title=Way forward agreed for Jaitapur reactors |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=12 March 2018 |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=wnn-20180627>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-EDF-and-GE-sign-strategic-deal-for-six-EPRs-in-India-26061802.html |title=EDF and GE sign strategic deal for six EPRs in India |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=27 June 2018 |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nNPCIL has ambitions to build up to 9900&nbsp;MW at the Jaitapur site, equating to six EPRs.<ref name=\"wnn-20150413\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Areva-signs-Jaitapur-agreements-1304154.html |title=Areva signs Jaitapur agreements |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=13 April 2015 |accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the United Kingdom|Sizewell nuclear power stations#Sizewell C}}\nTwo EPR units at [[Sizewell nuclear power stations|Sizewell]] in the United Kingdom are in the early stages of planning.<ref name=wnn-20180118>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-Energy-expects-20-cost-saving-for-Sizewell-C |title=EDF Energy expects 20% cost saving for Sizewell C |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=18 January 2018 |accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> If the project goes ahead electricity production is expected to start in 2031 at the earliest.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gosden|first1=Emily|title=Sizewell C nuclear power to come on stream in 2031|work=The Times|issue=72367|date=20 October 2017|page=42|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==Unsuccessful proposals==\n\n===Canada===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in Canada}}\n\nEPR was considered for the two (possible expansion to four) reactor addition to the [[Darlington Nuclear Generating Station]] in [[Ontario, Canada]]. However, the official bids had to include all contingencies, and Areva failed to enter a final bid meeting these requirements. The project was ultimately abandoned when the only bid, made by Canada's [[AECL]], came in at well over $10/Wp.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thinkingpower.ca/PDFs/Commentary/CCRE%20Commentary%20-%20CANDU%20at%20Darlington%20-%20Securing%20Jobs%20and%20Energy%20for%20the%20new%20Economy%20-%20February%202012.pdf |title=CANDU at Darlington: Securing Jobs and Energy for the new Economy |website=February 2012}}</ref>\n\nEPR was briefly considered for an installation in [[New Brunswick]], replacing or supplanting that province's single [[CANDU reactor|CANDU 6]]. These plans lasted only from June 2010 until an election two months later, when the plan immediately disappeared from further study.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_New_Brunswick_deals_with_Areva_0907101.html|title=New Brunswick deals with Areva|last=|first=|date=2010-07-09|website=www.world-nuclear-news.org|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Czech Republic ===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the Czech Republic}}\nIn October 2012 [[\u010cEZ Group|CEZ]] announced that Areva was eliminated from the tender for the construction of 2 reactors for [[Temel\u00edn Nuclear Power Station|Temelin nuclear plant]]. Areva failed to comply with legal requirements of the tender.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/cez-excludes-areva-from-temelin-expansion-tender/r~i:article:759491/|title=CEZ excludes Areva from Temelin expansion tender|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz|first=Tereza |last=Sidlova|date=2012-10-05}}</ref> In April 2014 CEZ cancelled a tender, because of low power prices and the government's refusal to support a minimum guaranteed energy price.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/cez-temelin-idUKL6N0N23OO20140410|title=UPDATE 4-CEZ scraps tender to expand Temelin nuclear power plant|date=2014-04-10|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-08-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Finland===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in Finland}}\nIn 2010 the Finnish parliament decided to allow two new reactors. Both [[Teollisuuden Voima|TVO]] and [[Fennovoima]] were considering the EPR.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvo.fi/www/page/2842/ |title=TVO Plant type alternatives |publisher=Tvo.fi |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422163719/http://www.tvo.fi/www/page/2842/ |archive-date=22 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fennovoima.com/press-releases/current/fennovoima-signed-technical-development-agreements-with-areva-and-toshiba |title=Current &#124; Fennovoima signed technical development agreements with Areva and Toshiba &#124; Current &#124; Fennovoima Oy |publisher=Fennovoima.com |date=20 December 2010 |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320101615/http://www.fennovoima.com/press-releases/current/fennovoima-signed-technical-development-agreements-with-areva-and-toshiba |archive-date=20 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nIn December 2013 Fennovoima confirmed it had selected a Russian AES-2006 [[VVER]] pressurised water reactor in preference to the EPR.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/12/21/us-fennovoima-rosatom-idUSBRE9BK05G20131221 | title = Finland's Fennovoima signs reactor deal with Rosatom | publisher = Reuters | date = 21 December 2013 | accessdate = 12 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in Italy}}\n\nOn 24 February 2009, Italy and France agreed to study the feasibility of building 4 new nuclear power stations in Italy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7908434.stm |title=Italy and France pen nuclear deal |date=24 February 2009 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=24 February 2009}}</ref> Following this, on 3 August 2009, EDF and [[Enel]] established a joint venture, Sviluppo Nucleare Italia, to study the feasibility of building at least four EPRs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124932829249202353 |title=Enel, EDF to Build Nuclear Plants in Italy |date=4 August 2009 |author1=Selina Williams |author2=Liam Moloney |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in the [[Italian referendum, 2011|2011 referendum]], soon after the [[Fukushima nuclear disaster]], Italians voted to [[repeal]] the new regulations permitting nuclear power in Italy. Abrogation of laws is put in effect when at least 50%+1 electors make a valid vote and a majority of these voters are in favour of abrogation. In this referendum there was a 55% valid [[voter turnout]] and 94% voted to abrogate the new regulations.\n\n===United Arab Emirates===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the United Arab Emirates}}\nIn March 2008, French president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] reached an agreement with the UAE cabinet that \"outlines a cooperation framework for the assessment and possible use of nuclear energy for peaceful ends\". This agreement was not a contract for EPR construction by any of the French nuclear companies, [[Total S.A.]], [[Suez (company)|Suez]] or Areva.<ref>{{cite web | last=Bowman| first=Joel| title=UAE endorses France nuclear deal | website=ArabianBusiness.com | date=2010-03-08| url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/uae-endorses-france-nuclear-deal-52693.html | access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, US President [[Barack Obama]] signed a [[U.S.\u2013UAE 123 Agreement for Peaceful Civilian Nuclear Energy Cooperation|similar agreement]] with the UAE. Contracts for reactors were not given, nor was there any guarantee made that US companies would receive them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/22/world/middleeast/22emirates.html|title=Despite Torture Video, U.S. and Emirates Sign Key Pact|last=Landler|first=Mark|date=2009-05-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009 the [[United Arab Emirates]] declined both the American and French bids and awarded a contract for construction of four non-EPR stations ([[APR-1400]]) to a South Korean group including [[Korea Electric Power Corporation]], [[Hyundai Engineering and Construction]], [[Samsung]] and [[Doosan Heavy Industries]].<ref>{{cite news |title=S. Koreans win $20B UAE nuclear power contract |author1=Andrew England |author2=Peggy Hollinger |author3=Song Jung-a |work=Financial Times |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/BUSINESS/12/28/skorea.nuclear.uae.ft/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114064741/http://www.cnn.com/2009/BUSINESS/12/28/skorea.nuclear.uae.ft/index.html |archivedate=14 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing this order, Areva considered whether it should reintroduce the marketing of a smaller and simpler second-generation reactor design alongside the EPR, for countries that are new to nuclear power.<ref name=\"ft-20100115\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/00767364-0175-11df-8c54-00144feabdc0.html|title=Areva considers producing cheaper reactors|author=Peggy Hollinger|date=15 January 2010|work=Financial Times|accessdate=19 January 2010}}</ref> As of 2011 Areva and [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] offer a smaller 1100&nbsp;MWe [[Atmea|ATMEA1]] Generation III PWR.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-19/french-atmea-would-make-reactor-credible-export-gdf-suez-says.html |title=French Atmea Would Make Reactor \u2018Credible\u2019 Export, GDF Suez Says |author=Tara Patel |date=19 January 2011 |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=21 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the United States}}\nThe US-EPR, the version of the EPR submitted to the U.S. regulator,<ref name=\"wnn-20150306\"/> is one of the competitors for the next generation of nuclear stations in the United States, along with the [[AP1000]] and the [[ESBWR]]. In February 2015 Areva asked to suspend the Design Certification Application Review process at the U.S. [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC).<ref name=\"wnn-20150306\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-US-EPR-plans-suspended-0603157.html |title=US EPR plans suspended |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=6 March 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> It had been under review there with expectation to submit an application for final design approval and standard design certification since 14 December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrc.gov/reactors/new-licensing/design-cert/epr.html|title=Design Certification Application Review \u2013 U.S. EPR |publisher=[[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]]|accessdate=3 July 2008}}</ref> UniStar, Amarillo Power, PPL Corp and [[AmerenUE]] announced plans to file a [[Combined Construction and Operating License]] application in 2008 for the US-EPR at its [[Callaway Nuclear Generating Station|Callaway]] station. UniStar filed a partial application in July 2007 for a proposed third unit at the [[Calvert Cliffs Nuclear Power Plant]] in Maryland. However, both proposals were subsequently cancelled.\n\nIn April 2009, Missouri legislators balked at preconstruction rate increases, prompting AmerenUE to suspend plans for its reactor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primebuzz.kcstar.com/?q=node/18179 |title=Nuke plant is, well, nuked. Not gonna happen |publisher=Primebuzz.kcstar.com |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>Terry Ganey. [https://archive.is/20120728210332/http://www.columbiatribune.com/news/2009/apr/23/amerenue-pulls-plug-callaway-2/ AmerenUE pulls plug on project] ''Columbia Daily Tribune'', 23 April 2009.</ref> In July 2010, Constellation Energy Group cut spending on UniStar for the Calvert Cliffs Nuclear Power Station because of uncertainties for a loan guarantee from the U.S. Department of Energy,<ref name=\"nyt-20100730\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/cwire/2010/07/30/30climatewire-a-late-scramble-to-fund-nuclear-renaissance-83656.html |title=A Late Scramble to Fund 'Nuclear Renaissance' Kick-Start |author=Peter Behr |work=New York Times |date=30 July 2010 |accessdate=30 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"TradingMarkets-20100729\">{{cite news |url=http://www.tradingmarkets.com/news/stock-alert/ceg_constellation-energy-cuts-spending-on-areva-reactor-venture-1075217.html |title=Constellation Energy cuts spending on Areva reactor venture |work=McClatchy-Tribune Information Services |publisher=TradingMarkets |date=29 July 2010 |accessdate=30 July 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and subsequently pulled out of the project.<ref name=\"ft-20101019\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/fd5ee326-dbb9-11df-a1df-00144feabdc0.html |title=Energy: Cooling ambitions |author=Peggy Hollinger |date=19 October 2010 |work=Financial Times |accessdate=29 October 2010}}</ref> In October 2008, Areva announced that it will partner with US defense firm [[Northrop Grumman]] to establish a $380&nbsp;million facility to construct modules and assemblies for the EPR and US-EPR reactors at Northrop Grumman's [[Northrop Grumman Shipbuilding|Newport News Shipyard]] in [[Virginia]].<ref>\n{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Dedicated-nuclear-component-factory |title=Dedicated nuclear component factory |date=24 October 2008 |work= World Nuclear News |accessdate= 31 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.powermag.com/areva-inches-closer-to-u-s-epr-construction/ |title= AREVA inches closer to U.S. EPR construction |author= Sonal Patel |date=1 December 2008 |work= POWER |accessdate=31 January 2009}}</ref>\nThe project was suspended indefinitely in May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nuclearstreet.com/nuclear_power_industry_news/b/nuclear_power_news/archive/2011/05/11/areva-halts-construction-of-virginia-reactor-component-plant-051102.aspx |title=Areva Halts Construction of Virginia Reactor Component Plant \u2013 Nuclear Power Industry News \u2013 Nuclear Power Industry News \u2013 Nuclear Street \u2013 Nuclear Power Portal |publisher=Nuclear Street |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|EPR (nuclear reactor)}}\n{{Portal|Energy|Nuclear technology}}\n*[[Economics of new nuclear power plants]]\n*[[Nuclear power by country]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Nuclear fission reactors}}\n{{Nuclear power in France}}\n\n[[Category:Pressurized water reactors]]\n[[Category:EPR (nuclear reactor)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n[[File:EPR OLK3 lage.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Computer generated view of an '''EPR''' power station]]\n[[File:EPR pressure vessel.png|upright|thumb|Reactor pressure vessel of the EPR]]\nThe '''EPR''' is a [[Generation III reactor|third generation]] [[pressurised water reactor]] design. It has been designed and developed mainly by [[Framatome]] (part of [[Areva]] between 2001 and 2017) and [[\u00c9lectricit\u00e9 de France]] (EDF) in France, and [[Siemens]] in Germany. In Europe this reactor design was called '''European Pressurised Reactor''', and the internationalised name was '''Evolutionary Power Reactor''', but it is now simply named '''EPR'''.\n\nThe first operational EPR unit was China's [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant|Taishan 1]], which started in December 2018.<ref name=wnn-20181214>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/First-EPR-enters-commercial-operation |title=First EPR enters commercial operation |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=14 December 2018 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> Taishan 2 started operations in September 2019.<ref name=wnn-20190909>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/World-s-second-EPR-starts-operations |title=World's second EPR starts operations |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=9 September 2019 |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> The first two EPR units to start construction, at [[Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant#Unit 3|Olkiluoto]] in Finland and [[Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant|Flamanville]] in France, are both facing costly delays (to 2021 and 2023, respectively).<ref name=wnn-20191219>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/System-tests-further-delay-Finnish-EPR-start-up |title=System tests further delay Finnish EPR start-up |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=19 December 2019 |accessdate=19 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=wnn-20191009>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-warns-of-added-costs-of-Flamanville-EPR-weld-r |title=EDF warns of added costs of Flamanville EPR weld repairs |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=10 October 2019 |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> Two units at [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station|Hinkley Point]] in the United Kingdom received final approval in September 2016 and are expected to be completed around 2026.<ref name=\"guardian-20160915\"/><ref name=wnn-20190925>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Hinkley-Point-C-cost-rises-by-nearly-15 |title=Hinkley Point C cost rises by nearly 15% |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=25 September 2019 |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nEDF has acknowledged severe difficulties in building the EPR design. In September 2015 EDF stated that the design of a \"New Model\" EPR was being worked on, which will be easier and cheaper to build.<ref name=\"independent-20150923\"/>\n\n==Design==\n===First EPR design===\nThe main design objectives of the [[Generation III reactor|third generation]] EPR design are increased safety while providing enhanced economic competitiveness through improvements to previous [[pressurised water reactor]] designs scaled up to an electrical power output of around 1650&nbsp;[[MWe]] (net)<ref name=\"areva-fieldrep-20101006\">{{cite web |url=http://www.areva.com/mediatheque/liblocal/docs/pdf/energies/pdf-field-report-3-va.pdf |page=4 |title=New Build Field Report |date=6 October 2010 |publisher=Areva |accessdate=5 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521234633/http://www.areva.com/mediatheque/liblocal/docs/pdf/energies/pdf-field-report-3-va.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> with thermal power of 4500&nbsp;MW. The reactor can use [[enriched uranium|5% enriched uranium oxide]] fuel, [[reprocessed uranium]] fuel or 100%&nbsp;[[MOX fuel|mixed uranium plutonium oxide]] fuel. The EPR is the evolutionary descendant of the [[Framatome]] N4 and [[Siemens AG|Siemens Power Generation Division]] \"Konvoi\" reactors.<ref name=\"EPR-presentation\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iaea.org/NuclearPower/Downloads/INPRO/Files/2010-Feb-DF-WS/15-Teller.pdf |format=PDF |title=The EPR Reactor: Evolution to Gen III+ based on proven technology |author=Andrew Teller |publisher=Areva |date=2 February 2010 |accessdate=19 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"EPR-brochure\">{{cite web |url=http://www.areva-np.com/common/liblocal/docs/Brochure/EPR_US_%20May%202005.pdf |format=PDF |title=EPR \u2013 Areva brochure |publisher=Areva NP |date=May 2005 |accessdate=2 January 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071129121411/http://www.areva-np.com/common/liblocal/docs/Brochure/EPR_US_%20May%202005.pdf |archive-date=29 November 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Siemens ceased its nuclear activities in 2011.<ref name=\"DeutscheWelle1\">{{cite web|last1=Borrud|first1=Gabriel|title=Siemens to quit nuclear industry|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-to-quit-nuclear-industry/a-15396964|website=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>\nThe EPR was designed to use [[uranium]] more efficiently than older [[Generation II reactor]]s, using approximately 17% less uranium per unit of electricity generated than these older reactor technologies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Forsythe|first=Jan|title=3 R's of Nuclear Power: Reading, Recycling, and Reprocessing: ...Making a Better Tomorrow for Little Joe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LZ7zBwWLyLEC&pg=PA126|year=2009|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4389-6731-8|page=126}}</ref>\n\nThe design had gone through a number of iterations. The 1994 conceptual design had a power output of 1450 MWe, the same as the Framatome N4, but using Siemens Konvoi derived instrumentation and including a new [[core catcher]] safety system. In 1995 there was concern over excessive cost per MW, and output was increased to 1800 MWe in the 2007 design, though this was subsequently reduced to 1650 MWe in the final certified design.<ref name=thomas-2010>{{cite report |url=https://gala.gre.ac.uk/id/eprint/4699/3/(ITEM_4699)_THOMAS_2010-11-E-EPR.pdf |title=The EPR in Crisis |last=Thomas |first=Steve |publisher=University of Greenwich |date=November 2010 |access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe EPR design has several active and passive protection measures against accidents:\n*Four independent emergency cooling systems, each providing the required cooling of the [[decay heat]] that continues for 1 to 3 years after the reactor's initial shutdown (i.e., 300% redundancy)<ref name=\"ShirzadiJackson2014\">{{cite book|author1=A. Shirzadi|author2=S. Jackson|title=Structural Alloys for Power Plants: Operational Challenges and High-Temperature Materials|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_SN0AwAAQBAJ&pg=PA94|date=30 July 2014|publisher=Elsevier Science|isbn=978-0-85709-755-2|pages=94\u2013}}</ref>\n*Leaktight containment around the reactor\n*An extra container and cooling area if a molten core manages to escape the reactor (see [[containment building]] and [[core catcher]])\n*Two-layer concrete wall with total thickness 2.6&nbsp;m, designed to withstand impact by aeroplanes and internal overpressure\n\nThe EPR has a design maximum [[core damage frequency]] of 6.1&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;10<sup>\u22127</sup> per station per year.<ref>''[http://www.epr-reactor.co.uk/ssmod/liblocal/docs/V3/Volume%202%20-%20Design%20and%20Safety/2.R%20-%20Probabilistic%20Safety%20Assessment/2.R.1%20-%20Level%201%20Probabilistic%20Safety%20Assessment%20-%20v2.pdf EPR Level 1 Probabilistic Safety Assessment]''. Author: UK EPR.</ref>\n\nThe EPR has a single [[steam turbine]] capable of using all the steam generated.<ref name=wnn-20180620>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-GE-Power-starts-Arabelle-production-for-Hinkley-Point-C-20061802.html |title=GE Power starts Arabelle production for Hinkley Point C |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=20 June 2018 |accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===\"New Model\" EPR design===\n{{as of|2013|alt=In 2013}} EDF acknowledged the difficulties it was having building the EPR design, with its head of production and engineering, Herv\u00e9 Machenaud, saying EDF had lost its dominant international position in design and construction of nuclear power stations. Machenaud indicated EDF was considering designing two new lower powered reactors, one with output of 1,500&nbsp;MWe and the other 1,000&nbsp;MWe. Machenaud stated there would be a period of reflection on the best way to improve the EPR design to lower its price and incorporate [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|post-Fukushima]] safety improvements.<ref name=\"reuters-20130321\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/21/edf-reactors-idUSL6N0CD1J820130321 |title=EDF eyes development of new, smaller reactors - papers |publisher=Reuters |date=21 March 2013 |accessdate=18 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015 EDF's chief executive [[Jean-Bernard L\u00e9vy]] stated that the design of a \"New Model\" EPR, or \"EPR 2\",<ref name=edf-epr>{{cite web |url=https://www.edf.fr/en/the-edf-group/our-energies/nuclear/epr/designing-and-building-the-nuclear-plant-of-tomorrow |title=EPR: showcasing French nuclear expertise |publisher=EDF |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> was being worked on, which will be easier to build, to be ready for orders from about 2020,<ref name=\"independent-20150923\">{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/only-china-wants-to-invest-in-britains-new-2bn-hinkley-point-nuclear-plant-because-no-one-else-10513752.html |title=Only China wants to invest in Britain's new \u00a32bn Hinkley Point nuclear station because no one else thinks it will work, EDF admits |author=Geert De Clercq |newspaper=The Independent |date=23 September 2015 |accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref> describing it in 2016 as \"a reactor offering the same characteristics as today\u2019s EPR but it will be cheaper to build with optimised construction times and costs\".<ref name=\"theenergycollective-20161018\">{{cite web |url=https://www.energycentral.com/c/ec/interview-jean-bernard-l%C3%A9vy-ceo-edf-our-future-lies-combination-nuclear-and |title=Interview Jean-Bernard L\u00e9vy, CEO EDF: \"Our Future Lies in Combination Nuclear and Renewables\" |publisher=the energycollective |date=18 October 2016 |accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 EDF planned to build two New Model EPR reactors in France by 2030 to prepare for renewing its fleet of older reactors.<ref name=reuters-20160121>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/edf-nuclear-epr/edf-plans-two-new-nuclear-reactors-in-france-by-2030-document-idUKL8N1554S4 |title=EDF plans two new nuclear reactors in France by 2030-document |publisher=Reuters |date=21 January 2016 |accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> However following financial difficulties at Areva, and its merger with EDF, French Ecology Minister [[Nicolas Hulot]] said in January 2018 \"for now [building a New Model EPR] is neither a priority or a plan. Right now the priority is to develop renewable energy and to reduce the share of nuclear.\"<ref name=reuters-20180122>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/france-nuclear/update-1-separate-unit-for-edf-nuclear-arm-has-been-discussed-says-minister-hulot-idUSL8N1PH4D6 |title=UPDATE 1-Separate unit for EDF nuclear arm has been discussed, says minister Hulot |publisher=Reuters |date=22 January 2018 |accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> The industry-government plan for 2019\u20132022 included work on \"a new version of the EPR\".<ref name=wnn-20190128>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/French-nuclear-industry-sets-medium-term-plans |title=French nuclear industry sets medium-term plans |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=28 January 2019 |accessdate=30 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 the French nuclear safety authority [[Autorit\u00e9 de s\u00fbret\u00e9 nucl\u00e9aire|ASN]] issued an opinion on the safety of an outline EPR New Model (EPR 2) design. It found that general safety was on the whole satisfactory, though identifying areas for further examination. The most notable simplification is a single layer containment building as opposed to the EPR\u2019s double layer. ASN highlighted that the EPR design basis assumption that primary and secondary cooling circuit piping could not fail may no longer be appropriate for the simplified EPR 2, and requires additional safety demonstrations.<ref name=reuters-20190718>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-edf-nuclearpower/french-regulator-to-edf-dont-assume-new-reactor-model-is-accident-proof-idUSKCN1UD2W0 |title=French regulator to EDF: don't assume new reactor model is accident-proof |author=Geert De Clercq |publisher=Reuters |date=18 July 2019 |accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=asn-20190729>{{cite web |url=http://www.french-nuclear-safety.fr/Information/News-releases/ASN-issues-its-opinion-on-the-safety-options-for-the-EPR-New-model-reactor-and-its-EPR-2-upgrade |title=ASN issues its opinion on the safety options for the EPR New model reactor and its EPR 2 upgrade |publisher=ASN |date=29 July 2019 |accessdate=11 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020 Energy Minister [[\u00c9lisabeth Borne]] announced the government would not decide on the construction of any new reactors until the much delayed [[Flamanville 3]] started operation after 2022.  EDF had estimated building six EPR 2 nuclear reactors would cost at least \u20ac46 billion.<ref name=nei-20200114>{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsfrance-to-decide-on-new-nuclear-build-after-2022-7598148 |title=France to decide on new nuclear build after 2022 |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=14 January 2020 |access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Olkiluoto 3 (Finland)==\n{{See also|Nuclear power in Finland|Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant}}\n[[File:OL3.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|Olkiluoto-3 under construction in 2009. It is scheduled to start regular electricity generation in 2021, a delay of twelve years.<ref name=\"wnn-20191219\"/>]]\nThe construction of the [[Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant|Olkiluoto]] 3<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ol3.areva-np.com/ |title=OLKILUOTO 3 PROJECT by AREVA |access-date=24 July 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210133742/http://www.ol3.areva-np.com/ |archive-date=10 February 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> power station in Finland commenced in August 2005. The station will have an electrical power output of 1600&nbsp;[[MWe]] (net).<ref name=\"areva-fieldrep-20101006\" /> The construction was a joint effort of French [[Areva]] and German [[Siemens AG]] through their common subsidiary Areva NP, for Finnish operator [[Teollisuuden Voima|TVO]]. Siemens ceased nuclear activities in 2011. Initial cost estimates were about \u20ac3.7&nbsp;billion,<ref>{{cite web | title=EPR IN FINLAND: FOUNDATION STONE-LAYING DAY AT OLKILUOTO 3 | website=de.framatome-anp.com | date=2006-10-18 | url=http://www.de.framatome-anp.com/anp/e/foa/anp/press/anp054.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018024548/http://www.de.framatome-anp.com/anp/e/foa/anp/press/anp054.htm | archive-date=2006-10-18 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> but the project has since seen several severe cost increments and delays, with latest cost estimates (from 2012) of more than \u20ac8&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.helsinkitimes.fi/business/8486-daily-olkiluoto-3-may-cost-over-8bn.html|title=Daily: Olkiluoto 3 may cost over \u20ac8bn|last=HT|website=www.helsinkitimes.fi|access-date=2018-12-04}}</ref> The station was initially scheduled to go online in 2009,<ref>{{cite web | title=Olkiluoto 3 \"Chronology of the Project\" | website=ol3.areva-np.com | date=2007-09-27 | url=http://www.ol3.areva-np.com/project/chrono.htm | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927094543/http://www.ol3.areva-np.com/project/chrono.htm | archive-date=2007-09-27 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref> but operations are now expected to start in 2021.<ref name=\"wnn-20191219\"/>\n\nIn May 2006, construction delays of about one year were announced, following quality control problems across the construction. In part the delays were due to the lack of oversight of subcontractors inexperienced in nuclear construction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsregulator-reports-as-ol3-delays-reach-one-year/|title=Regulator reports as OL3 delays reach one year|date=2006-07-19|website=Nuclear Engineering International|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsconcrete-composition-delays-finland-s-olkiluoto-3/|title=Concrete composition delays Finland's Olkiluoto 3|date=2006-05-09|website=Nuclear Engineering International|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> The delays led to disappointing financial results for the Areva NP. It blamed delays on the Finnish approach to approving technical documentation and designs.<ref>{{cite web | title=Areva's first half results hit by Olkiluoto 3 delays | website=Nuclear Engineering International | date=2007-09-27 | url=http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectioncode=132&storyCode=2039298 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927190831/http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectioncode=132&storyCode=2039298 | archive-date=2007-09-27 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.largeassociates.com/3149%20Olkiluoto/R3149-A1%20Final%20Issue.pdf|title=European Pressurised Reactor at Olkiluoto 3, Finland \u2013 Brief & Interim Review of the Porosity and Durability Properties of the In Situ Cast Concrete at the Olkiluoto EPR Construction Site|date=2006-06-08|website=Large and Associates|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927034349/http://www.largeassociates.com/3149%20Olkiluoto/R3149-A1%20Final%20Issue.pdf|archive-date=2007-09-27|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, TVO announced construction was about 18 months behind schedule so completion was now expected 2010\u201311, and there were reports that Areva was preparing to take a \u20ac500&nbsp;million charge on its accounts for the delay.<ref>{{cite web | title=Finland nuclear reactor delayed again | website=MSN.com | date=2006-12-04 | url=http://news.moneycentral.msn.com/provider/providerarticle.aspx?Feed=AP&Date=20061204&ID=6245665 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070308085958/http://news.moneycentral.msn.com/provider/providerarticle.aspx?Feed=AP&Date=20061204&ID=6245665 | archive-date=2007-03-08 | url-status=dead }}{{deadlink|date=August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Areva to take 500 mln eur charge for Finnish reactor delay | website=Forbes.com | date=2006-12-05 | url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/afx/2006/12/05/afx3228309.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110603234546/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/afx/2006/12/05/afx3228309.html | archive-date=2011-06-03 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of June 2007, it was reported that [[Radiation and Nuclear Safety Authority|S\u00e4teilyturvakeskus]] (STUK), the Finnish Radiation and Nuclear Safety Authority, had found a number of safety-related design and manufacturing 'deficiencies'.<ref>{{cite web | title=Nuclear industry revival hits roadblocks | website=New Scientist | date=2007-07-01 | url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn12167-nuclear-industry-revival-hits-roadblocks/ | access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> In August 2007, a further construction delay of up to a year was reported associated with construction problems in reinforcing the reactor building to withstand an aeroplane crash, and the timely supply of adequate documentation to the Finnish authorities.<ref>{{cite web | title=Dates revised again for Olkiluoto 3 | website=World Nuclear News | date=2007-08-10 | url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newNuclear/Dates_revised_again_for_Olkiluoto_3_100807.shtml | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huliq.com/30247/nuclear-industrys-flagship-plant-delayed-again|title=Nuclear industry's flagship plant delayed again|last=Anastvatz|date=2007-08-11|website=HULIQ|language=en|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b48f8022-4762-11dc-9096-0000779fd2ac|title=Areva delay threatens China contract|last=Hollinger|first=Peggy|date=2007-08-11|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, TVO reported the construction delay as \"at least two years\" and costs more than 25% over budget.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=aFh1ySJ.lYQc |title=Nuclear Bid to Rival Coal Chilled by Flaws, Delay in Finland |author=Alan Katz |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=5 September 2007|accessdate=17 June 2008}}</ref> Cost estimates by analysts for the overrun range up to \u20ac1.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/newstex/AFX-0013-21958415.htm Areva-Siemens sees Olkiluoto 3 reactor operational in summer 2011]{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[CNN]], 31 December 2007.</ref>\n\nA further delay was announced in October 2008, making the total delay three years, giving an expected online date of 2012.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/10/17/business/EU-Finland-Nuclear-Plant.php |title=3-year delay expected at Finnish nuclear plant |work=International Herald Tribune |date=17 October 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2008}}</ref> The parties are in arbitration to resolve a dispute over responsibility for the delays and final cost overruns.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/a144c686-9b9d-11dd-ae76-000077b07658.html |title=Areva in talks with TVO over EPR delays |author=Peggy Hollinger |work=Financial Times |date=16 October 2008 |accessdate=17 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/oilRpt/idUKLV55678920081231 |title=Finland nuclear reactor costs headed to arbitration \u2013 TVO |publisher=Reuters |date=31 December 2008 |accessdate=5 January 2009 | first=Sakari | last=Suoninen}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2009|5}}, the station was at least three and a half years behind schedule and more than 50 percent over-budget. [[Areva]] and the utility involved \"are in bitter dispute over who will bear the cost overruns and there is a real risk now that the utility will default\".<ref name=tom>{{Cite web|url=http://www.salem-news.com/articles/may212009/us_nuke_race_5-21-09.php|title=U.K. Expert Says U.S. Is Not LOSING International Nuclear Power 'Race'|website=Salem-News|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> In August 2009, Areva announced \u20ac550&nbsp;million additional provisions for the build, taking station costs to \u20ac5.3&nbsp;billion, and wiped out interim operating profits for the first half-year of 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/0c9b59aa-9665-11de-84d1-00144feabdc0.html|title=Finnish reactor provisions hit Areva profits|author=Peggy Hollinger|date=31 August 2009|work=Financial Times|accessdate=1 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe dome of the containment structure was topped out in September 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.areva.com/servlet/cp_ol3_06_09_2009-c-PressRelease-cid-1251741544566-en.html | title = Olkiluoto 3: EPR dome installed | publisher = AREVA NC | date=6 August 2009 | accessdate=1 November 2009}}</ref> 90% of procurement, 80% of engineering works and 73% of civil works were completed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oJhyoZ8R4Ko | title=AREVA \u2013 Olkiluoto 3 : EPR dome installed | publisher = YouTube | date=10 August 2008 | accessdate=29 November 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, Areva announced \u20ac400&nbsp;million of further provisions, taking the cost overrun to \u20ac2.7&nbsp;billion. The timescale slipped from June 2012 to the end of 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mineweb.co.za/mineweb/view/mineweb/en/page72103?oid=107035&sn=Detail&pid=102055 |title=S&P downgrades French nuclear-uranium giant AREVA on weakened profitability |author=Dorothy Kosich |publisher=Mineweb |date=29 June 2010 |accessdate=6 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004210130/http://www.mineweb.co.za/mineweb/view/mineweb/en/page72103?oid=107035&sn=Detail&pid=102055 |archivedate=4 October 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-06-24/areva-s-overruns-at-finnish-nuclear-plant-approach-initial-cost.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100907020504/http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-06-24/areva-s-overruns-at-finnish-nuclear-plant-approach-initial-cost.html |publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek |title=Areva\u2019s Overruns at Finnish Nuclear Station Approach Initial Cost with operation set to start in 2013 |date=24 June 2010 |archivedate=7 September 2010 |first=Fran\u00e7ois |last=De Beaupuy }}</ref><ref name=\"wnn-20100608\">{{cite news |title=Start-up of Finnish EPR pushed back to 2013 |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=8 June 2010 |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Startup_of_Finnish_EPR_pushed_back_to_2013-0806104.html |accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref> In December 2011, TVO announced a further delay to August 2014.<ref name=\"reuters-20111221\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/12/21/finland-olkiluoto-idUSL6E7NL2DI20111221 |title=Finland's Olkiluoto 3 reactor delayed to August 2014 |publisher=Reuters |date=21 December 2011 |accessdate=21 December 2011 |first=Ritsuko |last=Ando}}</ref> As of July 2012, the station was scheduled to start electricity production no earlier than 2015, a schedule slippage of at least six years.<ref name = \"world-nuclear-news20120716\">{{cite news | title = Olkiluoto 3 delayed beyond 2014 | publisher = World Nuclear News | date = 17 July 2012 | url = https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Olkiluoto_3_delayed_beyond_2014-1707124.html | accessdate = 31 July 2012}}</ref> In December 2012 Areva's Chief Executive estimated costs to \u20ac8&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news | title = Costs of Finland's Olkiluoto nuclear reactor go up yet again | publisher = Nuclear-news | date = 14 December 2012 | url = http://nuclear-news.net/2012/12/14/costs-of-finlands-olkiluoto-nuclear-reactor-go-up-yet-again/ | accessdate = 6 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014 Areva announced that operations would start in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Olkiluoto-3-start-up-pushed-back-to-2018-0109147.html|title=Olkiluoto 3 startup pushed back to 2018|date=1 September 2014|work=World Nuclear News|accessdate=1 September 2014}}</ref> In October 2017 the date was pushed back to the beginning of 2019.<ref>{{Cite News|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-09/finland-s-10-year-wait-for-a-new-nuclear-reactor-just-got-longer|title=Finland\u2019s 10-Year Wait for a Nuclear Reactor Just Got Longer|publisher=Bloomberg|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010211648/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-09/finland-s-10-year-wait-for-a-new-nuclear-reactor-just-got-longer|archive-date=October 10, 2017|url-status=live|date= 9 October 2017|access-date = 10 October 2017}}</ref> During testing in 2018 and 2019 three further delays were announced, of over a year in total.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Start-up-of-Finnish-EPR-put-back-four-months-1406184.html |title=Start-up of Finnish EPR put back four months |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=14 June 2018 |accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/New-delay-in-start-up-of-Finnish-EPR |title=New delay in start-up of Finnish EPR |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=29 November 2018 |accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Olkiluoto-faces-further-delay-to-July-2020 |title=Olkiluoto faces further delay to July 2020 |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=18 July 2019 |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2019 the commissioning schedule was revised again: regular electricity generation is due to start in March 2021.<ref name=\"wnn-20191219\" />\n\n==Flamanville 3 (France)==\n{{See also|Nuclear power in France|Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant}}\n[[File:Flamanville-3 2010-07-15.jpg|thumb|EDF has said its Flamanville 3 project (seen here in 2010) will be delayed until 2023.<ref name=\"wnn-20191009\" />]]\n\nFirst concrete was poured for the demonstration EPR reactor at the [[Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant]] on 6 December 2007.<ref>''Nuclear Engineering International''. [https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsflamanville-3-concrete-poured/ Flamanville 3 concrete poured] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613091002/http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectionCode=132&storyCode=2048041 |date=13 June 2011 }}</ref>\nAs the name implies, this will be the third nuclear reactor on the Flamanville site, and the second instance of an EPR being built. Electrical output will be 1630&nbsp;MWe (net).<ref name=\"areva-fieldrep-20101006\" /> The project was planned to involve around \u20ac3.3&nbsp;billion of capital expenditure from [[\u00c9lectricit\u00e9 de France|EDF]],<ref name=\"EDF-F3-project\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edf.fr/html/epr/uk/projet.html |title=EDF Official Site \u2013 Flamanville 3 |publisher=Edf.fr | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630101014/http://energy.edf.com/edf-fr-accueil/edf-and-power-generation/nuclear-power/the-future-of-nuclear-power/epr-y-flamanville-3/the-flamanville-3-project-122321.html |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archive-date=30 June 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> but latest cost estimates (from 2019) are at \u20ac12.3&nbsp;billion.<ref name=\"wnn-20191009\" />\n\nFrom 19 October 2005 to 18 February 2006, the project was submitted to a national public debate. On 4 May 2006, the decision was made by EDF's Board of Directors to continue with the construction. Between 15 June and 31 July 2006, the unit underwent a public enquiry, which rendered a \"favourable opinion\" on the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://construction.ecnext.com/coms2/summary_0249-218321_ITM_platts |title=Public inquiry commission favours plan to build Flamanville-3 EPR |date=5 October 2006 |work=Nucleonics Week |accessdate=17 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929135733/http://construction.ecnext.com/coms2/summary_0249-218321_ITM_platts |archivedate=29 September 2007 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> That summer, site preparation works began.\n\nIn December 2007 construction of the unit itself began. This was expected to last 54 months, with commissioning planned for 2012.<ref name=\"EDF-F3-project\" />\n\nIn April 2008, the French nuclear safety authority (''[[Autorit\u00e9 de s\u00fbret\u00e9 nucl\u00e9aire]]'', ASN) reported that a quarter of the welds inspected in the secondary containment steel liner are not in accordance with norms, and that cracks have been found in the concrete base. EDF stated that progress was being made on these issues, which were raised very early in construction;<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/defects-found-in-nuclear-reactor-the-french-want-to-build-in-britain-808461.html |title=Defects found in nuclear reactor the French want to build in Britain |author1=Geoffrey Lean |author2=Jonathan Owen |date=13 April 2008 |work=The Independent |accessdate=19 April 2004 |location=London}}</ref> however, on 21 May, ASN ordered a suspension of concrete pouring on the site.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/rbssIndustryMaterialsUtilitiesNews/idUSL2762459720080527 |title=French nuke body partly halts work on new reactor |date=27 May 2008 |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=27 May 2008}}</ref> A month later, concreting work resumed after ASN accepted EDF's corrective action plan, which included external oversight checks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS_EdF_allowed_to_continue_concreting_2006081.html |title= EdF allowed to continue concreting |date=20 June 2008 |publisher=World Nuclear News |accessdate=21 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, professor [[Stephen Thomas (professor)|Stephen Thomas]] reported that after 18 months of construction, and after a series of quality control problems, the project is \"more than 20 percent over budget and EDF is struggling to keep it on schedule\".<ref name=\"tom\"/>\n\nIn August 2010, the regulator, ASN, reported further welding problems on the secondary containment steel liner.<ref name=\"bloomberg-20100830\" /> The same month, EDF announced that costs had increased 50% to \u20ac5&nbsp;billion, and commissioning was delayed by about two years to 2014.<ref name=\"bloomberg-20100830\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-30/edf-has-welding-problems-at-flamanville-epr-reactor-french-watchdog-says.html |title=French Nuclear Watchdog Says EDF Has Problems With Flamanville EPR Liner |author=Tara Patel |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=30 August 2010 |accessdate=31 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, EDF announced that the estimated costs had escalated to \u20ac6&nbsp;billion, and that completion of construction was delayed to 2016.<ref name=neimagazine>\n{{Cite news | url = https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsedf-delays-flamanville-3-epr-project-/ | agency= Nuclear Engineering International | date=20 July 2011 | title= EDF delays Flamanville 3 EPR project | accessdate=21 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 December 2012, EDF announced that the estimated costs had escalated to \u20ac8.5&nbsp;billion.<ref name=lemonde>\n{{Cite news | url=https://www.lemonde.fr/planete/article/2012/12/03/le-cout-de-l-epr-de-flamanville-encore-revu-a-la-hausse_1799417_3244.html | agency=Le Monde | date=3 December 2012 | title=Le co\u00fbt de l'EPR de Flamanville encore revu \u00e0 la hausse| accessdate=4 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012, the Italian power company [[Enel]] announced it was relinquishing its 12.5% stake in the project, and five future EPRs, so would be reimbursed its project stake of \u20ac613&nbsp;million, plus interest.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.powermag.com/enel-drops-participation-in-flamanville-epr-as-project-costs-soar-by-2-6b/ |title=Enel Drops Participation in Flamanville EPR as Project Costs Soar by $2.6B |newspaper=POWER |date=6 December 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.enel.com/en-GB/media/press_releases/enel-and-edf-terminate-their-cooperation-on-epr-in-france/r/1656525 |title=Enel and Edf Terminate their cooperation on EPR in France |publisher=Enel |date=4 December 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, EDF announced that completion of construction was delayed to 2017, due to delays in component delivery by Areva.<ref name=\"ft-20141118\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/adc90b3e-6f67-11e4-8d86-00144feabdc0.html |title=EDF in fresh delay for flagship nuclear plant |author=Michael Stothard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=18 November 2014 |accessdate=21 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Areva informed the French nuclear regulator ASN that anomalies had been detected in the reactor vessel steel, causing \"lower than expected mechanical toughness values\". Further tests are underway.<ref name=\"wnn-20150407\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-Flamanville-EPR-vessel-anomalies-under-scrutiny-0704154.html |title=Flamanville EPR vessel anomalies under scrutiny |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=7 April 2015 |accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref> In July 2015 [[The Daily Telegraph]] reported that Areva had been aware of this problem since 2006.<ref name=\"telegraph-20150709\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/earth/energy/nuclearpower/11727000/Areva-aware-as-early-as-2006-of-serious-fault-in-nuclear-reactor-destined-for-UK.html |title=Areva aware 'as early as 2006' of serious fault in nuclear reactor destined for UK |author=Henry Samuel |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=9 July 2015 |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, multiple faults in cooling system safety valves were discovered by ASN.<ref name=\"telegraph-20150609\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/france/11662889/Faulty-valves-in-new-generation-EPR-nuclear-reactor-pose-meltdown-risk-inspectors-warn.html |title=Faulty valves in new-generation EPR nuclear reactor pose meltdown risk, inspectors warn |author=Henry Samuel |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=9 June 2015 |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, EDF announced that the estimated costs had escalated to \u20ac10.5&nbsp;billion, and the start-up of the reactor was delayed to the fourth quarter of 2018.<ref>{{cite web | title=Flamanville EPR: optimised project management and a new timetable | website=EDF France | date=2015-09-03 | url=https://www.edf.fr/en/edf/flamanville-epr-optimised-project-management-and-a-new-timetable | access-date=2019-08-11}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2016, ASN announced that additional weak spots had been found in the reactor steel, and Areva and EDF responded that new tests would be conducted, though construction work would continue.<ref name=\"nei-20160412\">{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newseprs-to-face-more-tests-4862270 |title=EPRs to face more tests |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=12 April 2016 |accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, the [[Financial Times]] stated the project was six years late, and \u20ac7.2&nbsp;billion over budget,<ref name=ft-20170214>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/416a2c9c-f2d3-11e6-8758-6876151821a6 |title=Downfall of Toshiba, a nuclear industry titan |newspaper=Financial Times |date=14 February 2017 |accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref> while renewed delays in the construction of the EPR-reactors at [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant]] prompted EDF to state that Flamanville 3 remains on schedule to start operations by the end of 2018, assuming it receives regulatory approval.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/international-business/edf-confirms-flamanville-timetable-after-taishan-epr-delay/articleshow/57294950.cms |title= EDF confirms Flamanville timetable after Taishan EPR delay |work= [[Times of India]] |date= 2017-02-22 |accessdate= 2017-03-09}}</ref> In June 2017, the French regulator issued a provisional ruling that Flamanville 3 is safe to start.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-French-regulator-says-Flamanville-3-is-safe-to-start-29061701.html |title= French regulator says Flamanville 3 is safe to start |publisher=World Nuclear News |date= 28 June 2017 |accessdate= 3 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe discovery of quality deviations in the welding led to a further revision of the schedule in July 2018. Fuel loading was delayed until the end of 2019, and the cost estimate was increased from \u20ac10.5&nbsp;billion to \u20ac10.9&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-revises-schedule,-costs-of-Flamanville-EPR |title= EDF revises schedule, costs of Flamanville EPR |publisher=World Nuclear News |date= 25 July 2018 |accessdate= 30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019 the regulator ASN determined that eight welds in steam transfer pipes passing through the two wall containment, that EDF had hoped to repair after startup, must be repaired before the reactor is commissioned.<ref>{{cite web |title=Deviations on the Flamanville EPR steam lines: the eight penetration welds will have to be repaired |url=http://www.french-nuclear-safety.fr/Information/News-releases/Deviations-on-the-Flamanville-EPR-steam-lines-the-eight-penetration-welds-will-have-to-be-repaired |website=ASN |accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=wnn-20190620>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Weld-repairs-to-delay-Flamanville-EPR-start-up |title=Weld repairs to delay Flamanville EPR start-up |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=20 June 2019 |accessdate=21 June 2019}}</ref> In October 2019 EDF announced that because of this issue costs would increase to \u20ac12.3&nbsp;billion and that fuel loading would be delayed until the end of 2022 (with regular electricity generation starting in 2023 at the earliest).<ref name=\"wnn-20191009\" />\n\n==Taishan 1 and 2 (China)==\n{{See also|Nuclear power in China|Taishan Nuclear Power Plant}}\nIn 2006, Areva took part in the first bidding process for the construction of four new nuclear reactors in China, together with Toshiba-owned [[Westinghouse Electric Company|Westinghouse]] and Russian [[Atomstroyexport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.people.cn/200409/12/eng20040912_156691.html |title=Foreign energy giants bid for China's nuclear contracts |work=People's Daily |date=12 September 2004 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> However Areva lost this bid in favour of Westinghouse's [[AP1000]] reactors, in part because of Areva's refusal to transfer the expertise and knowledge to China.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nSubsequently Areva managed to win a deal in February 2007, worth about \u20ac8&nbsp;billion ($10.5&nbsp;billion) for two EPRs located in [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant|Taishan]], [[Guangdong|Guangdong Province]] in southern China, in spite of sticking to its previous conditions.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Areva-lands-world-s-biggest-ever-nuclear-power-ord |title=Areva lands world's biggest ever nuclear power order |date=26 November 2007 |work=World Nuclear News |accessdate=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413014154/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/newsarticle.aspx?id=14454&LangType=2057 |archive-date=13 April 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/business/feeds/afx/2007/07/30/afx3965097.html |title=Signing of Areva EPR order in China delayed \u2013 French source |date=30 July 2007 |work=Forbes |accessdate=1 August 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215151621/http://www.forbes.com/business/feeds/afx/2007/07/30/afx3965097.html |archivedate=15 December 2008 }}</ref> The [[General Contractor]] and [[Operator (profession)|Operator]] is the [[China General Nuclear Power Group]] (CGN).\n\nThe construction of the first reactor at [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant|Taishan]] started officially on 18 November 2009, and the second on 15 April 2010.<ref name=\"IAEA-PRIS-china\">{{cite web |title=China, People's Republic of: Nuclear Power Reactors |url=http://www.iaea.org/cgi-bin/db.page.pl/pris.powrea.htm?country=CN |work=PRIS database |publisher=[[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA) |accessdate=18 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620074942/http://www.iaea.org/cgi-bin/db.page.pl/pris.powrea.htm?country=CN |archivedate=20 June 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\nConstruction of each unit was then planned to take 46&nbsp;months, significantly faster and cheaper than the first two EPRs in Finland and France.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-24/china-builds-french-designed-nuclear-reactor-for-40-less-areva-ceo-says.html | title= China Builds Nuclear Reactor for 40% Less Than Cost in France, Areva Says | first= Tara | last= Patel |author2=Fran\u00e7ois de Beaupuy |date= 24 November 2010|publisher= [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] | accessdate=2 December 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[reactor pressure vessel]] of the first reactor was installed in June 2012,<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.areva.com/EN/news-9361/china-the-construction-of-the-epr-reactor-unit-1-at-taishan-takes-a-major-step-forward-with-the-installation-of-the-vessel.html | title= China: The Construction of the EPR reactor Unit 1 at Taishan Takes a Major Step Forward with the Installation of the Vessel |date= 5 June 2012|publisher= [[AREVA]] | accessdate=5 June 2012 }}</ref> and the second in November 2014. The first pressure vessel had been imported from [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] in Japan, and [[Steam generator (nuclear power)|steam generators]] from Areva in France. The second pressure vessel and associated steam generators had been made in China, by [[Dongfang Electric]] and [[Shanghai Electric]].<ref name=\"wnn-20141105\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Construction-milestone-at-Taishan-2-EPR-0511141.html |title=Construction milestone at Taishan 2 EPR |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=5 November 2014 |accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 construction was reported to be running over two years late, mainly due to key component delays and project management issues.<ref name=\"nei-20150223\">{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/opinion/opinionhow-serious-are-the-delays-in-chinas-nuclear-programme-4517469/ |title=How serious are the delays in China's nuclear programme? |author=Steve Kidd |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=23 February 2015 |accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nCold function tests were performed on Taishan 1 in February 2016, with start up expected in the first half of 2017. Taishan 2 was scheduled to start up later that year.<ref name=\"wnn-20160201\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-First-Taishan-EPR-completes-cold-tests-0102164.html |title=First Taishan EPR completes cold tests |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=1 February 2016 |accessdate=13 April 2016}}</ref>\nHowever, commissioning dates were put back six months in February 2017, with commercial operation expected in the second half of 2017 and the first half of 2018.<ref name=wnn-20170222>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-China-revises-commissioning-dates-of-EPRs-2202174.html |title=China revises commissioning dates of EPRs |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=22 February 2017 |accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Hong Kong media reported that a component had cracked during testing, needing to be replaced.<ref name=\"crackinkey\">{{cite news|title=Tests reveal crack in key component of Chinese nuclear power plant, 130 km west of Hong Kong|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2017/12/12/tests-reveal-crack-key-component-chinese-nuclear-power-plant-130km-west-hong-kong/|work=[[Hong Kong Free Press]]|agency=[[FactWire]]|date=12 December 2017|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref>\nIn January 2018 commissioning was rescheduled again, with commercial operation expected in 2018 and 2019.<ref name=\"wnn-20180102\">{{cite news|url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Taishan-schedule-factors-in-commissioning-tests-0201181.html|title=Taishan schedule factors in commissioning tests|date=2 January 2018|accessdate=3 January 2018|publisher=World Nuclear News}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Taishan 1 achieved [[Criticality (status)|criticality]] for the first time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-First-criticality-achieved-at-Chinese-EPR-0706184.html |title=First criticality achieved at Chinese EPR |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=7 June 2018 |accessdate=18 June 2018}}</ref> It entered commercial operation in December 2018.<ref name=wnn-20181214 /><ref>{{cite web |title=Bernard Fontana's statement - EPR: the first Generation III+ nuclear reactor enters commercial operation |url=http://www.framatome.com/EN/businessnews-1445/nbspbernard-fontana-s-statement-epr-the-first-generation-iii-nuclear-reactor-enters-commercial-operation.html |publisher=Framatome |date=14 December 2018 |accessdate=16 December 2018}}</ref> Taishan 2 reached these milestones in May 2019<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Second-Chinese-EPR-achieves-criticality |title=Second Chinese EPR achieves criticality - World Nuclear News |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=29 May 2019 |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> and September 2019,<ref name=wnn-20190909 /> respectively.\n\n==Hinkley Point C (United Kingdom)==\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the United Kingdom|Hinkley Point C nuclear power station}}\nThe EPR underwent Generic Design Assessment by the [[Office for Nuclear Regulation]], along with the Westinghouse [[AP1000]].<ref>{{cite web|title=New Nuclear Power Stations \u2013 Progress so far|url=http://www.hse.gov.uk/newreactors/progress.htm|publisher=[[Health and Safety Executive]]|accessdate=15 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090601205003/http://www.hse.gov.uk/newreactors/progress.htm|archive-date=1 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> Interim Design Acceptance Confirmations were postponed until lessons from the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]] had been taken into account.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hse.gov.uk/newreactors/gda-japan.htm |title=News \u2013 Taking GDA work forward in the light of the unprecedented events in Japan |publisher=Hse.gov.uk |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228221748/http://www.hse.gov.uk/newreactors/gda-japan.htm |archive-date=28 December 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> EDF bought [[British Energy]] in 2009. EDF planned to build 4 new EPRs,<ref>{{cite web|author=This website was built by the EDF Energy WCM |url=http://www.edfenergy.com/about-us/energy-generation/nuclear.shtml |title=Nuclear Generation |publisher=Edfenergy.com |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> subject to electricity pricing agreement with the government.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nce.co.uk/news/energy/edf-still-undecided-about-hinkley-point-c-go-ahead/8646617.article?blocktitle=Exclusive-news-from-NCE-magazine&contentID=204 |title=EdF still undecided about Hinkley Point C go-ahead |author=Declan Lynch |newspaper=New Civil Engineer |date=18 April 2013 |accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph-20130418\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/10004699/EDF-prepared-to-let-UK-nuclear-talks-fail.html |title=EDF prepared to let UK nuclear talks fail |author=Andrew Trotman |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=18 April 2013 |accessdate=21 April 2013}}</ref> Areva has signed a strategic partnership with [[Rolls-Royce plc|Rolls-Royce]] to support the build of EPRs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsareva-signs-up-rolls-royce-for-epr/ |title=Areva signs up Rolls-Royce for EPR |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International |date=11 March 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref> On 19 March 2013 planning consent for [[Hinkley Point C nuclear power station]] was given,<ref name=\"bbc-20130320\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-21839684 |title=New nuclear power plant at Hinkley Point C is approved |publisher=BBC |date=20 March 2013 |accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> but difficult negotiations with the UK government about electricity pricing, and project financing with private investors, still needed to be concluded.<ref name=\"bbc-20130319\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-21774652 |title=What price nuclear power? The final hurdle for Hinkley |author=Dave Harvey |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2013 |accessdate=19 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October 2013, EDF Energy announced that an agreement had been reached regarding the nuclear stations to be built on the site of Hinkley Point C. EDF Group and the UK Government agreed on the key commercial terms of the investment contract. The final investment decision was conditional on completion of the remaining key steps, including the agreement of the [[European Commission]].\n\nOn 8 October 2014 the European Commission announced their agreement, with 16 out of 28 commissioners agreeing with the go ahead of the construction. On 21 September 2015 the British government announced it would provide a \u00a32&nbsp;billion support package for Hinkley Point C as Britain's first nuclear power station in 20 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-somerset-34306997|title=UK guarantees \u00a32bn China nuclear deal|last=|first=|date=2015-09-21|work=BBC News|access-date=2019-08-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 October 2015, during Chinese [[Xi Jinping|president Xi Jinping's]] state visit to the United Kingdom, EDF and CGN signed an investment agreement for the \u00a318&nbsp;billion (\u20ac20&nbsp;billion) project to build two reactors at Hinkley Point.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/oct/21/hinkley-point-reactor-costs-rise-by-2bn-as-deal-confirmed|title=Work to begin on Hinkley Point reactor within weeks after China deal signed|last=Farrell|first=Sean|date=2015-10-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-11|last2=Macalister|first2=Terry|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> However, legally binding contracts had not been agreed yet.<ref name=\"guardian-20160309\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/mar/09/no-legally-binding-contract-18bn-hinkley-point-nuclear-project-edf-china |title=No legally binding contract in \u00a318bn Hinkley Point nuclear project |author=Terry Macalister |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 March 2016 |accessdate=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, EDF managers told Members of Parliament that the Hinkley Point C proposal should be postponed, until it has \"solved a litany of problems\", including EDFs \"soaring debts\".<ref>Terry Macalister, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jun/17/edf-senior-managers-hinkley-point-postpone-letter-mps-energy-committee Hinkley Point should be postponed]\", ''The Guardian'', 18 June 2016.</ref> On 28 July 2016, after the resignation of a board member, the EDF board approved the project.<ref name=\"guardian-20160728\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jul/28/hinkley-point-c-to-go-ahead-after-edf-board-approves-project |title=Hinkley Point C in doubt after British government delays approval |author=Graham Ruddick |newspaper=The Guardian |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref> However [[Greg Clark]], the new [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]] in the new [[First May ministry|government of Theresa May]], then announced that the government would not sign the contract over the next few days as expected, but delay the contract to autumn to \"consider carefully all the component parts of this project\".<ref name=\"telegraph-20160728\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/07/28/green-light-for-hinkley-point-as-new-18bn-nuclear-plant-approved/ |title=Government delays Hinkley nuclear decision despite EDF approval for \u00a318bn project |author=Emily Gosden |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=28 July 2016}}</ref> Final government approval was given in September 2016.<ref name=\"guardian-20160915\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/sep/15/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-station-gets-go-ahead |title=Hinkley Point C nuclear power station gets government green light |author1=Rowena Mason |author2=Simon Goodley |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 September 2016 |accessdate=15 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, following an internal review, EDF announced revised estimates for the scheme, which included at least \u00a31.5&nbsp;billion of additional costs and up to 15 months of additional programme, leading to updated total cost estimates of \u00a319.6-20.3&nbsp;billion (\u20ac21.9-22.6&nbsp;billion).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/d4333820-5fcf-11e7-8814-0ac7eb84e5f1?mhq5j=e1 |title= EDF warns Hinkley Point could cost extra \u00a31.5bn |work= [[Financial Times]] |date= 2017-07-03 |accessdate= 2017-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.globalconstructionreview.com/news/hinkley-nuclear-plant-already-15bn-over-budget-edf/|title= Hinkley nuclear plant already \u00a31.5bn over budget, EDF admits |work= Global Construction Review |date= 2017-07-03 |accessdate= 2017-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/07/03/hinkley-nuclear-costs-climb-almost-20bn-start-delayed/|title=Cost of Hinkley Point nuclear plant climbs another \u00a31.5bn to over \u00a320bn, as project faces further delay|last=Ambrose|first=Jillian|date=2017-07-03|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-09-17|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> In September 2019 cost estimates were revised again, to between \u00a321.5 and \u00a322.5&nbsp;billion (\u20ac24-25.1&nbsp;billion).<ref name=\"wnn-20190925\" />\n\n==Possible future power stations==\n\n===France===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in France|Penly Nuclear Power Plant|Gravelines Nuclear Power Plant}}\n\nIn July 2008 the French President announced a second EPR would be built in France due to high oil and gas prices.<ref>{{cite web |title=Second new reactor for France |publisher=World Nuclear News|date=3 July 2008 |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_Second_new_reactor_for_France_0307082.html |accessdate=3 July 2008}}</ref> [[Penly Nuclear Power Plant|Penly]] was chosen as the site in 2009, with construction planned to start in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sa.areva.com/EN/news-6760/areva-pleased-with-the-announcement-of-the-construction-of-france-s-second-epr.html|title=AREVA pleased with the announcement of the construction of France\u2019s second EPR\u2122|date=2009-01-30|website=www.sa.areva.com|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref> However, in 2011, following the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]], EDF postponed public consultations.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/04/france-nuclear-idUSL5E7L43HE20111004 |title=France says Penly reactor on course despite delays |date=4 October 2011 |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=5 October 2011}}</ref> In February 2013, the Minister of Industrial Renewal [[Arnaud Montebourg]] stated that the plans for a new EPR reactor at Penly had been cancelled, citing the capacity for electricity production and massive investments in [[renewable energy]] along with his confidence in the EPR as a competitive project in foreign countries.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://bfmbusiness.bfmtv.com/entreprise/pas-depr-a-centrale-penly-439064.html |title= Pas d'EPR \u00e0 la centrale de Penly |work= [[BFM Business]] |date= 2013-04-25 |accessdate= 2017-03-09 |language= fr |trans-title=No EPR at the Penly power plant}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://normandie.canalblog.com/archives/2013/02/03/26314510.html |title= Montebourg enterre l'EPR de Penly |website= normandie.canalblog.com |date= 2013-03-03 |accessdate= 2017-03-09 |language= fr |trans-title=Montebourg buries the Penly EPR }}</ref>\n\nPlans to build new reactors in France were later revived. In 2019, EDF plans to select a site for the installation of a pair of EPR reactors. [[Penly Nuclear Power Plant|Penly]] and [[Gravelines Nuclear Power Plant|Gravelines]] are among the candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lepoint.fr/economie/la-normandie-prete-a-accueillir-un-nouveau-reacteur-epr-06-03-2019-2298429_28.php|title=La Normandie pr\u00eate \u00e0 accueillir un nouveau r\u00e9acteur EPR|last=Beuve|first=Jean-Pierre|date=2019-03-06|website=Le Point|language=fr|trans-title=Normandy ready to welcome a new EPR reactor|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019, newspaper ''[[Le Monde]]'' reported that the French government had sent EDF a \"mission letter\" in which it asked the company to prepare to build a total of six EPR reactors across three sites in the next 15 years.<ref name=\"reuters-20191014\">{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-edf-nuclear-epr/france-asks-edf-to-prepare-to-build-6-epr-reactors-in-15-years-le-monde-idUSKBN1WT27T |title=France asks EDF to prepare to build 6 EPR reactors in 15 years -Le Monde |publisher=Reuters |date=14 October 2019 |accessdate=19 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===India===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in India|Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project}}\nIn February 2009, the [[Nuclear Power Corporation of India]] (NPCIL) signed a memorandum of understanding with Areva to set up two 1650&nbsp;MWe reactors at [[Jaitapur Nuclear Power Project|Jaitapur]] in Maharashtra. This was followed by a framework agreement in December 2010.<ref>[http://www.npcil.nic.in//pdf/news_07dec2010_Business_Line.pdf India, France ink pact for Areva reactors, fuel] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927225957/http://www.npcil.nic.in//pdf/news_07dec2010_Business_Line.pdf |date=27 September 2011 }} npcil.nic.in</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, during French president [[Fran\u00e7ois Hollande]]'s state visit to India a joint statement with Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] was issued. According to the statement the two leaders \"have agreed on a roadmap of cooperation to speed up discussions on the Jaitapur project in 2016. Their shared aim is to start the implementation of the project in early 2017.\"<ref name=\"wnn-201690125\">{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Jaitapur-agreement-due-by-year-end-2501165.html |title=Jaitapur agreement due by year-end |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=25 January 2016 |accessdate=19 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2018 an Industrial Way Forward Agreement between EDF and NPCIL was signed, with an objective of producing a tender later in the year.<ref name=wnn-20180312>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Way-forward-agreed-for-Jaitapur-reactors-1203187.html |title=Way forward agreed for Jaitapur reactors |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=12 March 2018 |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=wnn-20180627>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-EDF-and-GE-sign-strategic-deal-for-six-EPRs-in-India-26061802.html |title=EDF and GE sign strategic deal for six EPRs in India |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=27 June 2018 |accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nNPCIL has ambitions to build up to 9900&nbsp;MW at the Jaitapur site, equating to six EPRs.<ref name=\"wnn-20150413\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-Areva-signs-Jaitapur-agreements-1304154.html |title=Areva signs Jaitapur agreements |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=13 April 2015 |accessdate=14 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the United Kingdom|Sizewell nuclear power stations#Sizewell C}}\nTwo EPR units at [[Sizewell nuclear power stations|Sizewell]] in the United Kingdom are in the early stages of planning.<ref name=wnn-20180118>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-Energy-expects-20-cost-saving-for-Sizewell-C |title=EDF Energy expects 20% cost saving for Sizewell C |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=18 January 2018 |accessdate=14 August 2018}}</ref> If the project goes ahead electricity production is expected to start in 2031 at the earliest.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gosden|first1=Emily|title=Sizewell C nuclear power to come on stream in 2031|work=The Times|issue=72367|date=20 October 2017|page=42|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n==Unsuccessful proposals==\n\n===Canada===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in Canada}}\n\nEPR was considered for the two (possible expansion to four) reactor addition to the [[Darlington Nuclear Generating Station]] in [[Ontario, Canada]]. However, the official bids had to include all contingencies, and Areva failed to enter a final bid meeting these requirements. The project was ultimately abandoned when the only bid, made by Canada's [[AECL]], came in at well over $10/Wp.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thinkingpower.ca/PDFs/Commentary/CCRE%20Commentary%20-%20CANDU%20at%20Darlington%20-%20Securing%20Jobs%20and%20Energy%20for%20the%20new%20Economy%20-%20February%202012.pdf |title=CANDU at Darlington: Securing Jobs and Energy for the new Economy |website=February 2012}}</ref>\n\nEPR was briefly considered for an installation in [[New Brunswick]], replacing or supplanting that province's single [[CANDU reactor|CANDU 6]]. These plans lasted only from June 2010 until an election two months later, when the plan immediately disappeared from further study.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_New_Brunswick_deals_with_Areva_0907101.html|title=New Brunswick deals with Areva|last=|first=|date=2010-07-09|website=www.world-nuclear-news.org|publisher=|access-date=2016-08-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Czech Republic ===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the Czech Republic}}\nIn October 2012 [[\u010cEZ Group|CEZ]] announced that Areva was eliminated from the tender for the construction of 2 reactors for [[Temel\u00edn Nuclear Power Station|Temelin nuclear plant]]. Areva failed to comply with legal requirements of the tender.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zpravy.aktualne.cz/cez-excludes-areva-from-temelin-expansion-tender/r~i:article:759491/|title=CEZ excludes Areva from Temelin expansion tender|website=Aktu\u00e1ln\u011b.cz|first=Tereza |last=Sidlova|date=2012-10-05}}</ref> In April 2014 CEZ cancelled a tender, because of low power prices and the government's refusal to support a minimum guaranteed energy price.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/cez-temelin-idUKL6N0N23OO20140410|title=UPDATE 4-CEZ scraps tender to expand Temelin nuclear power plant|date=2014-04-10|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-08-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Finland===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in Finland}}\nIn 2010 the Finnish parliament decided to allow two new reactors. Both [[Teollisuuden Voima|TVO]] and [[Fennovoima]] were considering the EPR.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvo.fi/www/page/2842/ |title=TVO Plant type alternatives |publisher=Tvo.fi |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422163719/http://www.tvo.fi/www/page/2842/ |archive-date=22 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fennovoima.com/press-releases/current/fennovoima-signed-technical-development-agreements-with-areva-and-toshiba |title=Current &#124; Fennovoima signed technical development agreements with Areva and Toshiba &#124; Current &#124; Fennovoima Oy |publisher=Fennovoima.com |date=20 December 2010 |accessdate=19 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320101615/http://www.fennovoima.com/press-releases/current/fennovoima-signed-technical-development-agreements-with-areva-and-toshiba |archive-date=20 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nIn December 2013 Fennovoima confirmed it had selected a Russian AES-2006 [[VVER]] pressurised water reactor in preference to the EPR.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/12/21/us-fennovoima-rosatom-idUSBRE9BK05G20131221 | title = Finland's Fennovoima signs reactor deal with Rosatom | publisher = Reuters | date = 21 December 2013 | accessdate = 12 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in Italy}}\n\nOn 24 February 2009, Italy and France agreed to study the feasibility of building 4 new nuclear power stations in Italy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7908434.stm |title=Italy and France pen nuclear deal |date=24 February 2009 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=24 February 2009}}</ref> Following this, on 3 August 2009, EDF and [[Enel]] established a joint venture, Sviluppo Nucleare Italia, to study the feasibility of building at least four EPRs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124932829249202353 |title=Enel, EDF to Build Nuclear Plants in Italy |date=4 August 2009 |author1=Selina Williams |author2=Liam Moloney |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |accessdate=9 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in the [[Italian referendum, 2011|2011 referendum]], soon after the [[Fukushima nuclear disaster]], Italians voted to [[repeal]] the new regulations permitting nuclear power in Italy. Abrogation of laws is put in effect when at least 50%+1 electors make a valid vote and a majority of these voters are in favour of abrogation. In this referendum there was a 55% valid [[voter turnout]] and 94% voted to abrogate the new regulations.\n\n===United Arab Emirates===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the United Arab Emirates}}\nIn March 2008, French president [[Nicolas Sarkozy]] reached an agreement with the UAE cabinet that \"outlines a cooperation framework for the assessment and possible use of nuclear energy for peaceful ends\". This agreement was not a contract for EPR construction by any of the French nuclear companies, [[Total S.A.]], [[Suez (company)|Suez]] or Areva.<ref>{{cite web | last=Bowman| first=Joel| title=UAE endorses France nuclear deal | website=ArabianBusiness.com | date=2010-03-08| url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/uae-endorses-france-nuclear-deal-52693.html | access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, US President [[Barack Obama]] signed a [[U.S.\u2013UAE 123 Agreement for Peaceful Civilian Nuclear Energy Cooperation|similar agreement]] with the UAE. Contracts for reactors were not given, nor was there any guarantee made that US companies would receive them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/22/world/middleeast/22emirates.html|title=Despite Torture Video, U.S. and Emirates Sign Key Pact|last=Landler|first=Mark|date=2009-05-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-08-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2009 the [[United Arab Emirates]] declined both the American and French bids and awarded a contract for construction of four non-EPR stations ([[APR-1400]]) to a South Korean group including [[Korea Electric Power Corporation]], [[Hyundai Engineering and Construction]], [[Samsung]] and [[Doosan Heavy Industries]].<ref>{{cite news |title=S. Koreans win $20B UAE nuclear power contract |author1=Andrew England |author2=Peggy Hollinger |author3=Song Jung-a |work=Financial Times |publisher=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/BUSINESS/12/28/skorea.nuclear.uae.ft/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114064741/http://www.cnn.com/2009/BUSINESS/12/28/skorea.nuclear.uae.ft/index.html |archivedate=14 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing this order, Areva considered whether it should reintroduce the marketing of a smaller and simpler second-generation reactor design alongside the EPR, for countries that are new to nuclear power.<ref name=\"ft-20100115\">{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/00767364-0175-11df-8c54-00144feabdc0.html|title=Areva considers producing cheaper reactors|author=Peggy Hollinger|date=15 January 2010|work=Financial Times|accessdate=19 January 2010}}</ref> As of 2011 Areva and [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] offer a smaller 1100&nbsp;MWe [[Atmea|ATMEA1]] Generation III PWR.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-19/french-atmea-would-make-reactor-credible-export-gdf-suez-says.html |title=French Atmea Would Make Reactor \u2018Credible\u2019 Export, GDF Suez Says |author=Tara Patel |date=19 January 2011 |publisher=Bloomberg |accessdate=21 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\n{{See also|Nuclear power in the United States}}\nThe US-EPR, the version of the EPR submitted to the U.S. regulator,<ref name=\"wnn-20150306\"/> is one of the competitors for the next generation of nuclear stations in the United States, along with the [[AP1000]] and the [[ESBWR]]. In February 2015 Areva asked to suspend the Design Certification Application Review process at the U.S. [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC).<ref name=\"wnn-20150306\">{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-US-EPR-plans-suspended-0603157.html |title=US EPR plans suspended |publisher=World Nuclear News |date=6 March 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref> It had been under review there with expectation to submit an application for final design approval and standard design certification since 14 December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrc.gov/reactors/new-licensing/design-cert/epr.html|title=Design Certification Application Review \u2013 U.S. EPR |publisher=[[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]]|accessdate=3 July 2008}}</ref> UniStar, Amarillo Power, PPL Corp and [[AmerenUE]] announced plans to file a [[Combined Construction and Operating License]] application in 2008 for the US-EPR at its [[Callaway Nuclear Generating Station|Callaway]] station. UniStar filed a partial application in July 2007 for a proposed third unit at the [[Calvert Cliffs Nuclear Power Plant]] in Maryland. However, both proposals were subsequently cancelled.\n\nIn April 2009, Missouri legislators balked at preconstruction rate increases, prompting AmerenUE to suspend plans for its reactor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://primebuzz.kcstar.com/?q=node/18179 |title=Nuke plant is, well, nuked. Not gonna happen |publisher=Primebuzz.kcstar.com |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref><ref>Terry Ganey. [https://archive.is/20120728210332/http://www.columbiatribune.com/news/2009/apr/23/amerenue-pulls-plug-callaway-2/ AmerenUE pulls plug on project] ''Columbia Daily Tribune'', 23 April 2009.</ref> In July 2010, Constellation Energy Group cut spending on UniStar for the Calvert Cliffs Nuclear Power Station because of uncertainties for a loan guarantee from the U.S. Department of Energy,<ref name=\"nyt-20100730\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/cwire/2010/07/30/30climatewire-a-late-scramble-to-fund-nuclear-renaissance-83656.html |title=A Late Scramble to Fund 'Nuclear Renaissance' Kick-Start |author=Peter Behr |work=New York Times |date=30 July 2010 |accessdate=30 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"TradingMarkets-20100729\">{{cite news |url=http://www.tradingmarkets.com/news/stock-alert/ceg_constellation-energy-cuts-spending-on-areva-reactor-venture-1075217.html |title=Constellation Energy cuts spending on Areva reactor venture |work=McClatchy-Tribune Information Services |publisher=TradingMarkets |date=29 July 2010 |accessdate=30 July 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and subsequently pulled out of the project.<ref name=\"ft-20101019\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/fd5ee326-dbb9-11df-a1df-00144feabdc0.html |title=Energy: Cooling ambitions |author=Peggy Hollinger |date=19 October 2010 |work=Financial Times |accessdate=29 October 2010}}</ref> In October 2008, Areva announced that it will partner with US defense firm [[Northrop Grumman]] to establish a $380&nbsp;million facility to construct modules and assemblies for the EPR and US-EPR reactors at Northrop Grumman's [[Northrop Grumman Shipbuilding|Newport News Shipyard]] in [[Virginia]].<ref>\n{{cite news |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Dedicated-nuclear-component-factory |title=Dedicated nuclear component factory |date=24 October 2008 |work= World Nuclear News |accessdate= 31 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.powermag.com/areva-inches-closer-to-u-s-epr-construction/ |title= AREVA inches closer to U.S. EPR construction |author= Sonal Patel |date=1 December 2008 |work= POWER |accessdate=31 January 2009}}</ref>\nThe project was suspended indefinitely in May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nuclearstreet.com/nuclear_power_industry_news/b/nuclear_power_news/archive/2011/05/11/areva-halts-construction-of-virginia-reactor-component-plant-051102.aspx |title=Areva Halts Construction of Virginia Reactor Component Plant \u2013 Nuclear Power Industry News \u2013 Nuclear Power Industry News \u2013 Nuclear Street \u2013 Nuclear Power Portal |publisher=Nuclear Street |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|EPR (nuclear reactor)}}\n{{Portal|Energy|Nuclear technology}}\n*[[Economics of new nuclear power plants]]\n*[[Nuclear power by country]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{Nuclear fission reactors}}\n{{Nuclear power in France}}\n\n[[Category:Pressurized water reactors]]\n[[Category:EPR (nuclear reactor)]]\n", "name_user": "Buxtehude", "label": "safe", "comment": "Small corrections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/EPR_(nuclear_reactor)"}
{"title_page": "Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox United States proposed legislation\n| name = Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act\n| image_seal = <!--Defaults to the Great Seal-->\n| fullname = To amend the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 to repeal the excise tax on high cost employer-sponsored health coverage.\n| acronym = CARES Act\n| nickname = <!--Unofficial name used by the press or general public-->\n| introduced in the = 116th\n| sponsored by = \n| number of co-sponsors = <!--give a number; could add a time period such as \"when introduced\"-->\n| public law url = \n| cite public law = {{USPL|116|136}}<!--{{USPL|XXX|YY}} where X is the congress number and Y is the law number-->\n| cite statutes at large = <!--{{usstat}} can be used-->\n| acts affected = <!--list, if applicable; make wikilinks where possible-->\n| acts repealed = <!--list, if applicable; make wikilinks where possible-->\n| title affected = <!--US code titles changed-->\n| sections created = <!--{{USC}} can be used-->\n| sections affected = <!--list, if applicable; make wikilinks where possible-->\n| agenciesaffected = <!--list of federal agencies that would be affected by the legislation, wikilinks where possible-->\n| authorizationsofappropriations = <!--a dollar amount, with dollar sign, possibly including a time period-->\n| appropriations = <!--a dollar amount, with dollar sign, possibly including a time period-->\n| leghisturl = \n| introducedin = House\n| introducedbill = {{USBill|116|HR|748}} (Middle Class Health Benefits Tax Repeal Act of 2019)\n| introduceddate = January 24, 2019 \n| introducedby = [[Joe Courtney (politician)|Joe Courtney]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Connecticut|CT]])\n| committees = [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means]]\n| passedbody1 = House\n| passeddate1 = July 17, 2019\n| passedvote1 = [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2019/roll493.xml 419\u20136]\n| passedbody2 = Senate\n| passedas2 = Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act\n| passeddate2 = March 25, 2020\n| passedvote2 = [https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=116&session=2&vote=00080 96\u20130]\n| conferencedate = \n| passedbody3 = \n| passeddate3 = \n| passedvote3 = \n| agreedbody3 = House\n| agreeddate3 = March 27, 2020\n| agreedvote3 = [[voice vote]]\n| agreedbody4 = <!--used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation-->\n| agreeddate4 = <!--used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation-->\n| agreedvote4 = <!--used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation-->\n| passedbody4 = \n| passeddate4 = \n| passedvote4 = \n| signedpresident = Donald Trump\n| signeddate = March 27, 2020\n| unsignedpresident = <!--used when passed without presidential signing-->\n| unsigneddate = <!--used when passed without presidential signing-->\n| vetoedpresident = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| vetoeddate = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddenbody1 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddendate1 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddenvote1 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddenbody2 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddendate2 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddenvote2 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| amendments = \n| SCOTUS cases = \n}}\n\nThe '''Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act''' ({{USBill|116|HR|748}}),<!--NOTE: H.R. 748 is the correct bill that was passed by the Senate. See [https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/20059055/final-final-cares-act.pdf]--><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fedweek.com/fedweek/house-coronavirus-relief-bill-would-boost-federal-employee-benefits/|title=House Coronavirus Relief Bill Would Boost Federal Employee Benefits|date=2020-03-25|website=FEDweek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> also known as the '''CARES Act''',<ref name=\"ABC News Senate scrambles\">{{cite web |last1=Parkinson |first1=John |title=Senate scrambles to strike deal on $1T pandemic relief for businesses, families |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-scrambles-strike-deal-1t-pandemic-relief-business/story?id=69713460 |website=[[ABC News]] |location=New York City|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> is a law meant to address the economic fallout of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]. It was introduced in the [[United States Senate]] by [[Senate Majority Leader|Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] ([[U.S. Republican Party|R]]-[[Kentucky|KY]]).<ref name=\"The Hill McConnell introduces\">{{cite newspaper |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=McConnell introduces third coronavirus relief proposal |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488527-mcconnell-introduces-third-coronavirus-relief-proposal |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |publisher=[[Capitol News Company]]|location=New York City|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original bill included $500 billion in checks for Americans,<ref name=\"ABC News Senate scrambles\" /> \"$208 billion in loans for major industries that have been impacted by the coronavirus\", and \"$300 billion for small businesses\".<ref name=\"The Hill McConnell introduces\" /> As a result of bipartisan negotiations, the bill grew to $2{{nbsp}}trillion in the version unanimously passed by the Senate on March 25, 2020.<ref name=CochraneStolberg>Emily Cochrane & Sheryl Gay Stolberg, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/politics/coronavirus-house-voting.html $2 Trillion Coronavirus Stimulus Bill Is Signed Into Law], ''New York Times'' (March 27, 2020).</ref><ref name=\"CNBC Senate passes $2 trillion\">{{cite web |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=Senate passes $2 trillion coronavirus stimulus package, sending it to the House |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/25/senate-passes-2-trillion-coronavirus-stimulus-package.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The next day it was passed in the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] via [[voice vote]] and signed into law by the [[President of the United States|President]].\n\nUnprecedented in size and scope,<ref name=CochraneStolberg/> the legislation was the largest-ever [[economic stimulus]] package,<ref>Sarah D. Wire, [https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-25/vote-senate-on-2-trillion-economic-stimulus-package-coronavirus Senate passes $2-trillion economic stimulus package], ''Los Angeles Times'' (March 25, 2020).</ref> amounting to 10% of U.S. [[gross domestic product]].<ref name=Kambhampati>Sandhya Kambhampati, [https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-26/coronavirus-stimulus-package-versus-recovery-act The coronavirus stimulus package versus the Recovery Act], ''Los Angeles Times'' (March 26, 2020).</ref> The bill was much larger than the $831 billion [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|2009 stimulus act]] passed in response to the [[global financial crisis]] and [[Great Recession]].<ref name=Kambhampati/>\n\nThe bill is referred to by lawmakers as \"Phase 3\" of Congress's [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|coronavirus]] response.<ref name=\"Vox What we know\">{{cite web |last1=Nilsen |first1=Ella |last2=Zhou |first2=Li |title=What we know about Congress' potential $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus package |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/17/21183846/congress-coronavirus-stimulus-package |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]|location=New York City|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Axios the growing stimulus\">{{cite web |last1=Treene |first1=Alayna |title=The growing coronavirus stimulus packages |url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-stimulus-packages-compared-7613a16f-56d3-4522-a841-23a82fffcb46.html |website=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |publisher=Axios Media Inc.|location=Arlington, Virginia|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The first phase \"was an $8.3 billion bill spurring coronavirus vaccine research and development\" (the [[Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2020]]), which was signed into law on March 6, 2020. The second phase was \"an approximately $104 billion package largely focused on paid sick leave and unemployment benefits for workers and families\" (the [[Families First Coronavirus Response Act]]), which was signed into law on March 18, 2020.<ref name=\"Vox What we know\" />\n\n==Background==\n===Reduction of economic activity===\n\nIn response to the coronavirus pandemic in the [[United States]] there was a dramatic reduction in economic activity, both globally and in the [[United States]], as a result of the enactment of [[social distancing]] measures meant to curb the spread of the virus. These measures included working from home, [[List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|widespread cancellation of events]], [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education|cancellation of classes]] (or moving in-person to online classes), reduction of travel, and the closure of businesses.\n\nIn March it was predicted that without government intervention most airlines around the world would go bankrupt.<ref name=\"CNN Most airlines could be bankrupt\">{{cite web |last1=Ziady |first1=Hanna |title=Most airlines could be bankrupt by May. Governments will have to help |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/business/airlines-bailouts/index.html |website=CNN Business |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On Monday, March 16 the trade group representing the American airline industry requested a $50 billion federal bailout.<ref name=\"airline industry seeks $50 billion\">{{cite web |last1=Wallace |first1=Gregory |last2=Mattingly |first2=Phil |last3=Isidore |first3=Chris |title=US airline industry seeks about $50 billion in federal help |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/business/us-airlines-federal-bailout/index.html |website=CNN Business |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On March 18 the [[National Restaurant Association]] wrote the President of the United States and members of Congress to say they were \"estimating that the industry's sales will decline by $225 billion during the next three months, which will prompt the loss of between five and seven million jobs.\"<ref name=\"The Hill Restaurant industry estimates\">{{cite web |last1=Gangitano |first1=Alex |title=Restaurant industry estimates $225B in losses from coronavirus |url=https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/business-a-lobbying/488223-restaurant-industry-estimates-225b-in-losses-from |website=The Hill |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> The National Restaurant Association requested aid to restaurants in the amount of $145 billion.<ref name=\"The Hill Restaurant industry estimates\" />\n\nIn an effort to gain Republican support for a large stimulus package that at the time was envisioned to be about $1 trillion, [[United States Secretary of the Treasury]] [[Steven Mnuchin]] told Republican Senators that the United States unemployment rate could reach 20% if no government action was taken.<ref name=\"Mnuchin warns senators of 20%\">{{cite web |title=Mnuchin warns senators of 20% U.S. unemployment without coronavirus rescue\u2014source |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-unemployment/mnuchin-warns-senators-of-20-us-unemployment-without-coronavirus-rescue-source-idUSKBN21502N |website=Reuters |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> Almost 3.3 million Americans filed for unemployment in the week ending March 21, \"nearly five times more than the previous record of 695,000 set in 1982\".<ref name=\"BBC News unemployment\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Record number of Americans file for unemployment |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52050426 |website=BBC News |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, [[Goldman Sachs]] predicted the U.S. [[gross domestic product]] would \"decline by 24% in the second quarter of 2020 because of the coronavirus pandemic\".<ref name=\"Insider GS prediction\">{{cite web |last1=Reinicke |first1=Carmen |title=Goldman Sachs now says US GDP will shrink 24% next quarter amid the coronavirus pandemic\u2014which would be 2.5 times bigger than any decline in history |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/us-gdp-drop-record-2q-amid-coronavirus-recession-goldman-sachs-2020-3-1029018308?utm_source=msn.com&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=msn-slideshow&utm_campaign=bodyurl |website=Markets Insider |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Deutsche Bank]] predicted the U.S. economy would shrink by 12.9% in the second quarter of 2020.<ref name=\"Deutsche Bank forecast\">{{cite web |last1=Winck |first1=Ben |title=The worst global recession since World War II: Deutsche Bank just unveiled a bleak new forecast as the coronavirus rocks economies worldwide |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/coronavirus-recession-worst-wwii-economic-recovery-global-deutsche-bank-2020-3-1029012757?utm_source=msn.com&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=msn-slideshow&utm_campaign=bodyurl |website=Markets Insider |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Initial proposals===\n\nIn mid-March 2020, Democratic politicians [[Andrew Yang]], [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]], and [[Tulsi Gabbard]] advocated for universal [[basic income]] in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]];<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clifford |first1=Catherine |title=Andrew Yang, AOC, Harvard professor: Free cash payments would help during coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/andrew-yang-aoc-free-ubi-cash-can-help-during-coronavirus-pandemic.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Relman |first1=Eliza |title=Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez demands the government distribute a universal basic income and implement 'Medicare for all' to fight the coronavirus |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-aoc-demands-universal-basic-income-other-radical-measures-2020-3 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Gabbard suggested that it be a temporary measure until the crisis subsides.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Victor |title=Gabbard pitches 'emergency, temporary' $1,000 payment to every adult as coronavirus outbreak spreads |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/tulsi-gabbard-coronavirus-emergency-temporary-payment |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On March 13, Democratic representatives [[Ro Khanna]] and [[Tim Ryan (Ohio politician)|Tim Ryan]] introduced legislation to provide payments to low-income citizens during the crisis via an [[earned income tax credit]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moreno |first1=J. Edward |title=Lawmakers call for universal basic income amid coronavirus crisis |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/487485-lawmakers-call-for-economic-stimulus-ubi-amid-coronavirus-crisis |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Corbett |first1=Jessica |title=House Democrats Propose Sending Checks of Up to $6,000 to Help Ease Workers' Pain During Coronavirus Pandemic |url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/13/house-democrats-propose-sending-checks-6000-help-ease-workers-pain-during |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Common Dreams |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On March 16, Republican senators [[Mitt Romney]] and [[Tom Cotton]] stated their support for a $1,000 basic income, the former saying it should be a one-time payment to help with short-term costs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lahut |first1=Jake |title=Tom Cotton is calling for Americans to get cash payments through the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-calling-for-americans-to-get-100-month-coronavirus-2020-3 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March, the [[Trump administration]] indicated that some payment would be given to non-millionaires as part of a stimulus package.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Trump wants to send Americans checks 'immediately' in response to coronavirus, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-wants-to-send-money-to-americans-in-next-two-weeks-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Kasie |last2=Caldwell |first2=Leigh Ann |last3=Tsirkin |first3=Julie |last4=Shabad |first4=Rebecca |title=White House eyeing $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus package |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/senate-democrats-have-prepped-third-coronavirus-aid-package-n1161506 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=NBC News |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith guidance from the White House, Senate Majority Leader [[Mitch McConnell]] proposed a third stimulus package amounting to more than $1&nbsp;trillion.{{efn|This included $300&nbsp;billion to help small businesses with forgivable loans up to $10&nbsp;million<ref name=hurdles/> and $200&nbsp;billion to support industries such as airlines, cruise companies, and hotels through loans and other measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stone |first1=Peter |title=Washington lobbyists in frenzied battle to secure billion-dollar coronavirus bailouts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-washington-lobbyists-bailout |work=The Guardian |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Democrats advocated for banning stock {{nowrap|buy-backs}} to prevent these funds from being used to make a profit.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Press |first1=Associated |title=Congress and White House resume talks on $1tn pandemic rescue deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/21/us-coronavirus-economic-rescue-trump |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>}} It was suggested that $200\u2013500&nbsp;billion would fund tax rebate checks to Americans who made between $2,500 and $75,000 in 2018 to help cover short-term costs<ref name=trillion>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Kasie |last2=Caldwell |first2=Leigh Ann |last3=Tsirkin |first3=Julie |last4=Shabad |first4=Rebecca |title=White House eyeing $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus package |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/senate-democrats-have-prepped-third-coronavirus-aid-package-n1161506 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=NBC News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Trump wants to send Americans checks 'immediately' in response to coronavirus, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-wants-to-send-money-to-americans-in-next-two-weeks-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Fox News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> via one or two payments of $600\u20131,200 per adult and $500 per child.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Breuninger |first1=Kevin |title=Trump wants direct payments of $1,000 for adults, $500 for kids in coronavirus stimulus bill, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/coronavirus-trump-wants-payments-of-1000-for-adults-500-for-kids.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Re |first1=Gregg |title=McConnell's coronavirus stimulus plan would provide payments of $1,200 per person, $2,400 for couples |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/mcconnell-coronavirus-stimulus-plan-payments |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Fox News |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=rebate/>{{efn|It is unclear whether the rebates would be tax-free.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Konish |first1=Lorie |title=Here's how your coronavirus rescue check from the government could be taxed |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/20/heres-how-your-rescue-check-from-the-government-could-be-taxed.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>}} Democrats prepared a $750&nbsp;billion package as a {{nowrap|counter-offer}},<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=McConnell takes reins of third coronavirus bill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488338-mcconnell-takes-reins-of-third-coronavirus-bill |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Caygle |first1=Heather |last2=Bresnahan |first2=John |last3=Ferris |first3=Sarah |title=Pelosi looks to lay down marker on next stimulus plan |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/18/nancy-pelosi-coronavirus-stimulus-plan-136142 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> which focused on expanding [[unemployment benefits]] instead of tax rebates.<ref name=rebate>{{cite news |last1=Bolton |first1=Alexander |title=Democrats balk at $1,200 rebate checks in stimulus plan |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488677-democrats-balk-at-1200-rebate-checks-in-stimulus-plan |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> A compromise plan was made to set aside $250&nbsp;billion for tax rebates and the same amount for unemployment.<ref name=hurdles>{{cite news |last1=Mattingly |first1=Phil |title=Stimulus package could top $2 trillion as negotiators look to clear final major hurdles |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/21/politics/stimulus-package-negotiations-congress-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=CNN |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Provisions==\n\n[[File:CARES ACT - Relief Amounts.png|thumb|right|400px|CARES Act relief amounts by category ($ billions), totaling $2.1 trillion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/relief-package-would-limit-coronavirus-damage-not-restore-economy-11585215006|title=Relief Package Would Limit Coronavirus Damage, Not Restore Economy|website=www.wsj.com|language=English|date=March 26, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020 }}</ref>]]\n\nThe Act contains the following provisions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/116/hr748/text|title= H.R. 748: Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act |date= March 27, 2020 |work = [[govtrack]] |publisher= Civic Impulse, LLC }}</ref> \n\n* Allocates up to $500 billion for assistance to eligible businesses, states, and municipalities, with not more than $25 billion designated for passenger air carriers, not more than $4 billion for air cargo carriers, and not more than $17 billion for businesses critical to maintaining national security.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foley.com/en/insights/publications/2020/03/senate-passes-coronavirus-cares-act|title=Senate Passes the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act (\"CARES Act\") |work= Foley & Lardner LLP| language=English|access-date=March 27, 2020 }}</ref><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 4003(b)</ref>\n* Creates a $349 billion loan program for small businesses with funds available for loans originated from February 15 through June 30, 2020.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 1102, amending the Small Business Act {{USC|15|636}}(a)</ref>\n* Allocates $130 billion in relief to the medical and hospital industries.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Provides credits against the 2020 personal income tax for eligible individuals who are neither nonresident aliens nor claimed as dependents by another taxpayer.\n** $1,200 to each individual or $2,400 to each married couple filing jointly, and\n** $500 for each dependent who is a qualifying child under age 17 as of December 31, 2020.\n** The credits are reduced, but not below zero, by each 5 percent of so much of the taxpayers' adjusted gross income as exceeds $150,000 for a joint return; $112,500 for a head of household; or $75,000 for other taxpayers.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 2201, amending {{USC|26|6428}}</ref>\n* Expands eligibility for [[Unemployment benefits in the United States|unemployment insurance]] and provides people with an additional $600 per week on top of the unemployment amount determined by each state.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 2102</ref> [[Gig worker]]s and [[freelancer]]s are covered by unemployment insurance for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/30/cares-act-will-be-an-economic-lifeline-for-gig-workers-freelancers.html|title=The historic $2 trillion CARES Act will be an economic lifeline for gig workers and freelancers|first=Elaine|last=Pofeldt|website=CNBC.com|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n* Expands [[telehealth]] services in [[Medicare]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 3212</ref> \n* Provides the [[U.S. Secretary of the Treasury|Secretary of the Treasury]] with the authority to make loans or loan guarantees to states, municipalities, and eligible businesses.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 4003(b)(4)</ref>\n\n== Breakdown of provisions ==\n\nDivision A: Keeping Workers Paid and Employed, Health Care System Enhancements, and Economic Stabilization\n* Title I: [[Keeping American Workers Paid and Employed Act]]\n* Title II: [[Relief for Workers Affected by Coronavirus Act]]\n** Subtitle A: Unemployment Insurance Provisions\n** Subtitle B: Rebates And Other Individual Provisions\n** Subtitle C: Business Provisions\n* Title III: Supporting America's Health Care System in the Fight Against the Coronavirus\n** Subtitle A: Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act\n*** Part I: Addressing Supply Shortages\n**** Subpart A: Medical Product Supplies\n**** Subpart B: Mitigating Emergency Drug Shortages\n**** Subpart C: Preventing Medical Device Shortages\n*** Part II: Access to Health Care for Covid\u201319 Patients\n**** Subpart A: Coverage of Testing and Preventive Services\n**** Subpart B: Support for Health Care Providers\n**** Subpart C: Miscellaneous Provisions\n*** Part III: Innovation\n*** Part IV: Health Care Workforce\n** Subtitle B: Education Provisions: [[COVID\u201319 Pandemic Education Relief Act of 2020]]\n** Subtitle C: Labor Provisions\n** Subtitle D: Finance Committee\n** Subtitle E: Health and Human Services Extenders\n*** Part I: Medicare Provisions\n*** Part II: Medicaid Provisions\n*** Part III: Human Services and Other Health Programs\n*** Part IV: Public Health Provisions\n*** Part V: Miscellaneous Provisions\n** Subtitle F: Over-the-Counter Drugs\n*** Part I: Otc Drug Review\n*** Part II: User Fees\n* Title IV: Economic Stabilization and Assistance to Severely Distressed Sectors of the United States Economy\n** Subtitle A: [[Coronavirus Economic Stabilization Act of 2020]]\n** Subtitle B: Air Carrier Worker Support\n* Title V: Coronavirus Relief Funds\n* Title VI: Miscellaneous Provisions\n\nDivision B: [[Emergency Appropriations for Coronavirus Health Response and Agency Operations]]\n\n==Legislative history==\n===Initial criticism and negotiations===\n\nThe House initially passed a tax cut bill in mid-2019 and sent it to the Senate, which then used it as a [[shell bill]] and added an [[substitute amendment|amendment in the nature of a substitute]], fulfilling the constitutional requirement that all bills for raising revenue must originate in the House. After the new bill was released by the Senate, Speaker of the House [[Nancy Pelosi]] ([[U.S. Democratic Party|D]]-[[California|CA]]) issued a statement that read in part: \"We are beginning to review Senator McConnell's proposal and on first reading, it is not at all pro-worker and instead puts corporations way ahead of workers.\"<ref name=\"CNN Republicans unveil $1 trillion\">{{cite web |last1=Mattingly |first1=Phil |last2=Foran |first2=Clare |last3=Barrett |first3=Ted |title=Senate Republicans unveil $1 trillion economic stimulus package to address coronavirus fallout |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/coronavirus-economic-stimulus-senate-republicans/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting Systems]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\nSenate Minority Leader [[Chuck Schumer]] (D-[[New York (state)|NY]]) criticized the fact that Democrats were not involved by Republicans in drafting the bill.<ref name=\"NPR Republicans Unveil\">{{cite web |last1=Snell |first1=Kelsey |last2=Grisales |first2=Claudia |last3=Davis |first3=Susan |last4=Walsh |first4=Deirdre |title=Senate Republicans Unveil New Coronavirus Relief Package |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818253789/congress-awaits-gop-relief-plan-as-first-lawmakers-test-positive-for-coronavirus |website=[[NPR]]|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAmong Senate Republicans there was \"significant debate and disagreement\" regarding \"President [[Donald Trump]]'s proposal to provide most Americans with $1,000-plus checks to boost spending and stimulate the economy\".<ref name=\"CNN Republicans unveil $1 trillion\" /> Senator [[Richard Shelby]] (R-[[Alabama|AL]]), the Republican chair of the [[Senate Appropriations Committee]], stated \"I personally think that if we're going to help people we should direct the cash payments maybe as a supplement to unemployment, not to the people who are working every day, just a blank check to everybody in America making up to $75,000.\"<ref name=\"CNN Republicans unveil $1 trillion\" />\n\n===Early procedural votes===\n\nOn the evening of Sunday March 22, 2020, Senate Democrats blocked the bill in a key procedural vote; the vote was 47\u201347, while 60 votes were needed to proceed.<ref name=\"CNBC 5 Things Monday\">{{cite web |last1=Belvedere |first1=Matthew |title=5 things to know before the stock market opens Monday |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/5-things-to-know-before-the-stock-market-opens-march-23-2020.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Immediately thereafter, \"[[Dow Jones Industrial Average|Dow]] futures hit their 5% 'limit down' overnight, and were off 600 points at one stage Monday morning.\"<ref name=\"CNBC 5 Things Monday\" /><ref name=\"National Law Review votes fails\">{{cite web |last1=Mill |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Muhyung |last3=Webb |first3=Sean |title=Coronavirus: CARES Act Vote Fails in Senate; Summary of the Tax Provisions of the Bill |url=https://content.natlawreview.com/article/coronavirus-cares-act-vote-fails-senate-summary-tax-provisions-bill |website=National Law Review |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response, Mitch McConnell \"announced another procedural vote on the package timed for 9:45 a.m. Monday\u2014minutes after the stock market opens\u2014but it was blocked by Democrats who don't want to be forced to take the vote.\"<ref name=\"CNN GOP ramps up pressure\">{{cite web |last1=Mattingly |first1=Phil |last2=Foran |first2=Clare |last3=Barrett |first3=Ted |title=Senate GOP ramps up pressure on Democrats over coronavirus stimulus package with Monday vote |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/stimulus-package-coronavirus-negotiations-congress/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The second key procedural vote on the CARES Act, a cloture vote to end debate, failed the afternoon of Monday, March 23; 60 votes were needed, but it failed 49\u201346.<ref name=\"ABC Senate showdown\">{{cite web |last1=Parkinson |first1=John |title=Senate showdown over pandemic relief stalls as Pelosi preps Democratic bill |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-showdown-pandemic-relief-stalls-pelosi-preps-democraticbill/story?id=69749675 |website=ABC News |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"National Law Review votes fails\" /> Both procedural votes were on a \"shell\" bill framed to repeal an [[Obamacare]] tax which passed the House on July 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where do you stand? |url=https://www.countable.us/bills/hr748-116 |website=www.countable.us |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> For procedural reasons, the text will be replaced by the new language passed by the Senate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.countable.us/articles/43144-s-status-phase-3-coronavirus-relief-bill|title=What's the Status of the 'Phase 3' Coronavirus Relief Bill?|website=www.countable.us|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"The Hill Senate fails\">{{cite web |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=Senate fails to advance coronavirus stimulus bill for second time in two days |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/489033-senate-fails-to-advance-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-for-second-time-in-two-days |website=The Hill |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nProcedural votes for the bill were made more difficult by the fact that five Republican Senators were in self-quarantine: Senator [[Rand Paul]], who had tested positive for [[coronavirus disease 2019]], as well as Senators [[Mike Lee (American politician)|Mike Lee]], Mitt Romney, [[Cory Gardner]], and [[Rick Scott]].<ref name=\"CNN GOP ramps up pressure\" />\n\nNancy Pelosi indicated that the House would prepare its own bill, expected to exceed $2.5&nbsp;trillion, as a counter-offer,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=House Democrats to introduce a $2.5 trillion coronavirus stimulus plan as Senate bill stalls |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/coronavirus-updates-pelosi-to-release-stimulus-bill-as-senate-plan-stalls.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> which was criticized by Republicans as \"a progressive wishlist seemingly unrelated to the crisis\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pelosis-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-includes-return-of-obamaphones-climate-change-wishlist|title=Pelosi's coronavirus stimulus includes return of 'Obamaphones', other unrelated items, GOP says|last=Re|first=Gregg|date=March 23, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324041402/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pelosis-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-includes-return-of-obamaphones-climate-change-wishlist|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Senate agreement===\n\nEarly in the morning of Wednesday March 25, Senate leaders announced they had come to an agreement on a modified version of the CARES Act,<ref name=\"NPR Senate Reaches Historic Deal\">{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Susan |last2=Grisales |first2=Claudia |last3=Snell |first3=Kelsey |title=Senate Reaches Historic Deal On $2 Trillion Coronavirus Economic Rescue Package |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/25/818881845/senate-reaches-historic-deal-on-2t-coronavirus-economic-rescue-package |website=NPR |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> the full text of which exceeds 300 pages.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stein |first1=Jeff |title=What's in the $2.2 trillion coronavirus Senate stimulus package |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/26/senate-stimulus-bill-coronavirus-2-trillion-list-what-is-in-it/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Mitch McConnell \"announced news of a breakthrough on the Senate floor shortly after 1:30{{nbsp}}a.m. Wednesday.\"<ref name=\"NPR Senate Reaches Historic Deal\" />\n\nOn the floor of the Senate, McConnell stated \"the Senate has reached a bipartisan agreement on a historic relief package for this pandemic\" and that \"this is a wartime level of investment for our nation.\"<ref name=\"NBC White House, Senate reach deal\">{{cite web |last1=Egan |first1=Lauren |last2=Tsirkin |first2=Julie |last3=Shabad |first3=Rebecca |title=White House, Senate reach deal on massive $2 trillion coronavirus spending bill |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/white-house-senate-reach-deal-massive-2-trillion-coronavirus-spending-n1168136 |website=NBC News |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> McConnell continued the analogy to war by stating that the CARES Act would provide \"ammunition\" to health care workers who are the \"frontline heroes who put themselves at risk to care for patients\" by providing them \"the ammunition they need\".<ref name=\"C-SPAN Senate agreement\">{{cite web |title=MARCH 24, 2020 Senate Session, Part 2 |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?470620-22/white-house-senate-leaders-reach-deal-2-trillion-economic-aid-package&start=14892 |website=C-SPAN |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Chuck Schumer stated on the Senate floor that \"Like all compromises, this bill is far from perfect, but we believe the legislation has been improved significantly to warrant its quick consideration and passage, and because many Democrats and Republicans were willing to do the serious and hard work, the bill is much better off than where it started.\"<ref name=\"NBC White House, Senate reach deal\" />\n[[File:FINAL-FINAL-CARES-ACT.pdf|thumb|CARES Act as negotiated by the Senate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/25/820759545/read-2-trillion-coronavirus-relief-bill|title=READ: $2 Trillion Coronavirus Relief Bill|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>]]\n\nThe result of the agreement between Senate leaders and the White House was a mammoth $2 trillion bill that \"is the largest economic relief bill in U.S. history\".<ref name=\"NPR Senate trudging\">{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=Andrew |last2=Lisa |first2=Mascaro |title=Senate trudging toward vote on virus rescue package |url=https://apnews.com/edd230801c0e181169915e67b1fd64c6 |website=NPR |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The bill was criticized by Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]].<ref name=\"NPR Senate trudging\" /> Republican Senators [[Lindsey Graham]], [[Tim Scott]], [[Ben Sasse]], and Rick Scott expressed concern the bill's strong unemployment provisions \"encourage employees to be laid off instead of working\".<ref name=\"Politico Senate back on track\">{{cite web |last1=Zanona |first1=Melanie |last2=Ferris |first2=Sarah |last3=Caygle |first3=Heather |title=Senate back on track to vote on massive coronavirus package |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/25/senate-vote-coronavirus-rescue-package-deal-148135 |website=Politico |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] then threatened to block the legislation and impose more stringent conditions for the $500 billion earmarked for corporate bailouts if the unemployment provision was removed by the proposed amendment of the four Republican Senators.<ref>{{cite web |last=Zachary |first=Basu |title=Senators threaten to delay coronavirus relief bill with last-minute objections |url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-relief-bill-lindsey-graham-bernie-sanders-619d2d7e-fea5-4884-ae48-a80fcb029e40.html |website=Axios |date= |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> To address these concerns, Senate leaders \"agreed to allow an amendment vote on the floor\".<ref name=\"Politico Senate back on track\" /> The Republican-led amendment to cap unemployment benefits failed in a 48\u201348 vote.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mu\u00f1oz |first1=Gabriella |last2=Boyer |first2=Dave |title=Senate rejects coronavirus stimulus package amendment to cap unemployment benefits |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/mar/25/sasse-amendment-fix-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-unem/ |website=Washington Times |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLate in the night of Wednesday, March 25, 2020, the Senate passed the $2 trillion bill in a unanimous 96\u20130 vote. The four Senators not voting were Rand Paul (who did not vote after testing positive for [[coronavirus disease 2019]]), Mitt Romney and Mike Lee (who were both in isolation after contact with Senator Paul), as well as Senator [[John Thune]] who \"missed the vote after feeling ill\".<ref name=\"CNBC Senate passes $2 trillion\" />\n\n===House vote===\n\nOn March 25, Pelosi stated that \"many of the provisions in there have been greatly improved because of negotiation,\" and hoped to pass the bill by unanimous consent.<ref name=historic>{{cite news |last1=Raju |first1=Manu |last2=Barrett |first2=Ted |last3=Foran |first3=Clare |last4=Wilson |first4=Kristin |title=White House, Senate reach historic $2 trillion stimulus deal amid growing coronavirus fears |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/stimulus-senate-action-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=CNN |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRepresentative [[Thomas Massie]] attempted to maneuver for a [[roll-call vote]], but there was insufficient demand [[Procedures of the United States Congress#Quorum and vote|among the quorum present]]; the House passed the bill by [[voice vote]] on March 27.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hughes |first=Siobhan |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-lawmakers-race-to-washington-to-ensure-coronavirus-stimulus-passes-11585318472 |title=House Passes $2 Trillion Coronavirus Stimulus Package |date=March 27, 2020 |work=Wall Street Journal |access-date=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Andrews |first2=Natalie |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Massie's threat to demand a recorded vote nonetheless \"compelled dozens, if not hundreds, of lawmakers to return to Capitol Hill from their home districts, navigating across interstates and through airports at a time when public health officials have urged Americans to avoid nonessential travel and gathering in large groups.\"<ref name=\"Politico parties pile on Massie\">{{cite web |last1=Forgey |first1=Quint |title=Both parties pile on Massie after effort to force recorded vote flops |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/27/trump-congressman-thomas-massie-coronavirus-vote-151523 |website=Politico |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> Massie's actions received bipartisan criticism. Former Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] tweeted \"Congressman Massie has tested positive for being an asshole. He must be quarantined to prevent the spread of his massive stupidity,\"<ref name=\"Kerry Massie Tweet\">{{cite web |title=John Kerry 10:55 a.m.\u2014Mar 27, 2020 Tweet |url=https://twitter.com/JohnKerry/status/1243552337429438464 |website=Twitter |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> a message which was shared by President Trump on Twitter.<ref name=\"Politico parties pile on Massie\" /> Republican Representative [[Peter T. King]] called Massie's actions \"disgraceful\" and \"irresponsible\".<ref name=\"Politico parties pile on Massie\" />\n\n===Signed into law and signing statement===\n\n[[File:CARES Act Enrolled Bill.pdf|thumb|CARES Act as signed into law]]\n\nA few hours after the House passed the bill, it was signed into law by President Trump.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Zeballos-Roig |first=Joseph |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-signs-coronavirus-economic-relief-aid-bill-checks-for-americans-2020-3 |title=Trump signs the $2 trillion coronavirus economic relief bill into law, which includes checks for Americans and business loans |date=March 27, 2020 |work=Business Insider |access-date=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a [[signing statement]], Trump suggested that he could gag the Special Inspector General for Pandemic Recovery (SIGPR), an oversight position created by the legislation to monitor loans and investments from a $500 billion corporate bailout fund established by the legislation.<ref name=Signingstmt>[[Charlie Savage]], [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/trump-signing-statement-coronavirus.html Trump Suggests He Can Gag Inspector General for Stimulus Bailout Program], ''New York Times'' (March 27, 2020).</ref> A provision in the legislation empowers the special inspector general to audit the use of the fund; requires the [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department]] and other executive-branch entities to provide information to the special inspector general; and directs the special inspector general to report to Congress \"without delay\" if an agency unreasonably withholds requested information.<ref name=Signingstmt/> In his signing statement, Trump suggested that his constitutional powers as president enabled him to block the SIGPR's reports to Congress.<ref name=Signingstmt/> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', the statement was consistent with Trump's \"history of trying to keep damaging information acquired by an inspector general from reaching Congress.\"<ref name=Signingstmt/>\n\n==Commentary==\n===Bi-partisan passage===\nCongress passed CARES quickly and with unanimity from both parties, despite its $2.2 trillion price-tag, indicating from one perspective the severity of the crisis.<ref name=\"WaPo_Phillips\"/> In contrast, in the depths of the [[Great Recession]], no Republicans in the House and only 3 in the Senate supported Obama's $800 billion stimulus, known as the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]] (ARRA).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rogers |first=David |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2009/02/senate-passes-787-billion-stimulus-bill-018837? |title=Senate passes $787 billion stimulus bill |date=February 13, 2009 |work=Politico.com |access-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Writing in ''The New Republic'', journalist Alex Shephard \"wondered how the Republican Party, which had spent the Obama years railing about the need to trim the deficit and debt, had come to embrace big spending.\" He interviewed one White House aide, who stated that Trump focuses on the markets and economy, not the national debt. However, Shephard expressed skepticism that Republicans would vote to support a major spending request under a hypothetical future Democratic President. He further explained that much of the media attention to ARRA focused on its impact on the deficit and the need for the Obama administration to persuade the public to support it, narratives almost entirely absent in the passage of CARES. Shephard opined that: \"[Then-Senate minority leader] [[Mitch McConnell|Mitch McConnell's]] strategy was to actually undermine Obama at every turn, with unified and total Republican opposition, whatever it might cost voters.\"<ref name=\"Shep_TNR\">{{Cite news |last=Shephard |first=Alex |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/157089/tale-two-stimulus-packages |title=A Tale of Two Stimulus Packages |date=March 30, 2020 |work=The New Republic |access-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> President Trump remarked upon passage of CARES in the Senate that: \"The Democrats have treated us fairly...I really believe we've had a very good back-and-forth. And I say that with respect to [Senate Minority Leader] [[Chuck Schumer]]\".<ref name=\"WaPo_Phillips\">{{Cite news |last=Phillips |first=Amber |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/26/totally-unprecedented-living-memory-congresss-bipartisanship-coronavirus-underscores-what-crisis-this-is/ |title='Totally unprecedented in living memory\u2019: Congress\u2019s bipartisanship on coronavirus underscores what a crisis this is |date=March 26, 2020 |work=washingtonpost.com |access-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n{{Div col}}\n* [[List of bills in the 116th United States Congress]]\n* [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[2020 in United States politics and government]]\n* [[2020s in United States political history]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{cite news|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|title=What's in the $2 Trillion Senate Coronavirus Bill|date= March 26, 2020 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-in-the-2-trillion-senate-coronavirus-bill-11585185450}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.republicanleader.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/CARES%20Act%20Final%20-%20Mar%202020.pdf Full text of the original bill as proposed by Mitch McConnell on March 19, 2020]\n<!-- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:FINAL-FINAL-CARES-ACT.pdf#file is also another choice, referenced earlier in the article. It's not clear how best to resolve this. -->\n* [https://www.congress.gov/116/bills/hr748/BILLS-116hr748enr.pdf Full text of the enrolled bill as passed by the Senate on March 25, 2020 and voted by the House on March 27, 2020]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Law associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Acts of the 116th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:United States federal health legislation]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox United States proposed legislation\n| name = Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act\n| image_seal = <!--Defaults to the Great Seal-->\n| fullname = To amend the Internal Revenue Code of 1986 to repeal the excise tax on high cost employer-sponsored health coverage.\n| acronym = CARES Act\n| nickname = <!--Unofficial name used by the press or general public-->\n| introduced in the = 116th\n| sponsored by = \n| number of co-sponsors = <!--give a number; could add a time period such as \"when introduced\"-->\n| public law url = \n| cite public law = {{USPL|116|136}}<!--{{USPL|XXX|YY}} where X is the congress number and Y is the law number-->\n| cite statutes at large = <!--{{usstat}} can be used-->\n| acts affected = <!--list, if applicable; make wikilinks where possible-->\n| acts repealed = <!--list, if applicable; make wikilinks where possible-->\n| title affected = <!--US code titles changed-->\n| sections created = <!--{{USC}} can be used-->\n| sections affected = <!--list, if applicable; make wikilinks where possible-->\n| agenciesaffected = <!--list of federal agencies that would be affected by the legislation, wikilinks where possible-->\n| authorizationsofappropriations = <!--a dollar amount, with dollar sign, possibly including a time period-->\n| appropriations = <!--a dollar amount, with dollar sign, possibly including a time period-->\n| leghisturl = \n| introducedin = House\n| introducedbill = {{USBill|116|HR|748}} (Middle Class Health Benefits Tax Repeal Act of 2019)\n| introduceddate = January 24, 2019 \n| introducedby = [[Joe Courtney (politician)|Joe Courtney]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Connecticut|CT]])\n| committees = [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Ways and Means]]\n| passedbody1 = House\n| passeddate1 = July 17, 2019\n| passedvote1 = [http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2019/roll493.xml 419\u20136]\n| passedbody2 = Senate\n| passedas2 = Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act\n| passeddate2 = March 25, 2020\n| passedvote2 = [https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=116&session=2&vote=00080 96\u20130]\n| conferencedate = \n| passedbody3 = \n| passeddate3 = \n| passedvote3 = \n| agreedbody3 = House\n| agreeddate3 = March 27, 2020\n| agreedvote3 = [[voice vote]]\n| agreedbody4 = <!--used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation-->\n| agreeddate4 = <!--used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation-->\n| agreedvote4 = <!--used if agreedbody3 further amends legislation-->\n| passedbody4 = \n| passeddate4 = \n| passedvote4 = \n| signedpresident = Donald Trump\n| signeddate = March 27, 2020\n| unsignedpresident = <!--used when passed without presidential signing-->\n| unsigneddate = <!--used when passed without presidential signing-->\n| vetoedpresident = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| vetoeddate = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddenbody1 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddendate1 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddenvote1 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddenbody2 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddendate2 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| overriddenvote2 = <!--used when passed by overriding presidential veto-->\n| amendments = \n| SCOTUS cases = \n}}\n\nThe '''Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act''' ({{USBill|116|HR|748}}),<!--NOTE: H.R. 748 is the correct bill that was passed by the Senate. See [https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/20059055/final-final-cares-act.pdf]--><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fedweek.com/fedweek/house-coronavirus-relief-bill-would-boost-federal-employee-benefits/|title=House Coronavirus Relief Bill Would Boost Federal Employee Benefits|date=2020-03-25|website=FEDweek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> also known as the '''CARES Act''',<ref name=\"ABC News Senate scrambles\">{{cite web |last1=Parkinson |first1=John |title=Senate scrambles to strike deal on $1T pandemic relief for businesses, families |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-scrambles-strike-deal-1t-pandemic-relief-business/story?id=69713460 |website=[[ABC News]] |location=New York City|date=March 20, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> is a law meant to address the economic fallout of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]. It was introduced in the [[United States Senate]] by [[Senate Majority Leader|Majority Leader]] [[Mitch McConnell]] ([[U.S. Republican Party|R]]-[[Kentucky|KY]]).<ref name=\"The Hill McConnell introduces\">{{cite newspaper |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=McConnell introduces third coronavirus relief proposal |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488527-mcconnell-introduces-third-coronavirus-relief-proposal |newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |publisher=[[Capitol News Company]]|location=New York City|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original bill included $500 billion in checks for Americans,<ref name=\"ABC News Senate scrambles\" /> \"$208 billion in loans for major industries that have been impacted by the coronavirus\", and \"$300 billion for small businesses\".<ref name=\"The Hill McConnell introduces\" /> As a result of bipartisan negotiations, the bill grew to $2{{nbsp}}trillion in the version unanimously passed by the Senate on March 25, 2020.<ref name=CochraneStolberg>Emily Cochrane & Sheryl Gay Stolberg, [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/politics/coronavirus-house-voting.html $2 Trillion Coronavirus Stimulus Bill Is Signed Into Law], ''New York Times'' (March 27, 2020).</ref><ref name=\"CNBC Senate passes $2 trillion\">{{cite web |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=Senate passes $2 trillion coronavirus stimulus package, sending it to the House |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/25/senate-passes-2-trillion-coronavirus-stimulus-package.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The next day it was passed in the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] via [[voice vote]] and signed into law by the [[President of the United States|President]].\n\nUnprecedented in size and scope,<ref name=CochraneStolberg/> the legislation was the largest-ever [[economic stimulus]] package,<ref>Sarah D. Wire, [https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-25/vote-senate-on-2-trillion-economic-stimulus-package-coronavirus Senate passes $2-trillion economic stimulus package], ''Los Angeles Times'' (March 25, 2020).</ref> amounting to 10% of U.S. [[gross domestic product]].<ref name=Kambhampati>Sandhya Kambhampati, [https://www.latimes.com/politics/story/2020-03-26/coronavirus-stimulus-package-versus-recovery-act The coronavirus stimulus package versus the Recovery Act], ''Los Angeles Times'' (March 26, 2020).</ref> The bill was much larger than the $831 billion [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009|2009 stimulus act]] passed in response to the [[global financial crisis]] and [[Great Recession]].<ref name=Kambhampati/>\n\nThe bill is referred to by lawmakers as \"Phase 3\" of Congress's [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|coronavirus]] response.<ref name=\"Vox What we know\">{{cite web |last1=Nilsen |first1=Ella |last2=Zhou |first2=Li |title=What we know about Congress' potential $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus package |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/3/17/21183846/congress-coronavirus-stimulus-package |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]]|location=New York City|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Axios the growing stimulus\">{{cite web |last1=Treene |first1=Alayna |title=The growing coronavirus stimulus packages |url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-stimulus-packages-compared-7613a16f-56d3-4522-a841-23a82fffcb46.html |website=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |publisher=Axios Media Inc.|location=Arlington, Virginia|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> The first phase \"was an $8.3 billion bill spurring coronavirus vaccine research and development\" (the [[Coronavirus Preparedness and Response Supplemental Appropriations Act, 2020]]), which was signed into law on March 6, 2020. The second phase was \"an approximately $104 billion package largely focused on paid sick leave and unemployment benefits for workers and families\" (the [[Families First Coronavirus Response Act]]), which was signed into law on March 18, 2020.<ref name=\"Vox What we know\" />\n\n==Background==\n===Reduction of economic activity===\n\nIn response to the coronavirus pandemic in the [[United States]] there was a dramatic reduction in economic activity, both globally and in the [[United States]], as a result of the enactment of [[social distancing]] measures meant to curb the spread of the virus. These measures included working from home, [[List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|widespread cancellation of events]], [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education|cancellation of classes]] (or moving in-person to online classes), reduction of travel, and the closure of businesses.\n\nIn March it was predicted that without government intervention most airlines around the world would go bankrupt.<ref name=\"CNN Most airlines could be bankrupt\">{{cite web |last1=Ziady |first1=Hanna |title=Most airlines could be bankrupt by May. Governments will have to help |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/business/airlines-bailouts/index.html |website=CNN Business |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On Monday, March 16 the trade group representing the American airline industry requested a $50 billion federal bailout.<ref name=\"airline industry seeks $50 billion\">{{cite web |last1=Wallace |first1=Gregory |last2=Mattingly |first2=Phil |last3=Isidore |first3=Chris |title=US airline industry seeks about $50 billion in federal help |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/16/business/us-airlines-federal-bailout/index.html |website=CNN Business |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> On March 18 the [[National Restaurant Association]] wrote the President of the United States and members of Congress to say they were \"estimating that the industry's sales will decline by $225 billion during the next three months, which will prompt the loss of between five and seven million jobs.\"<ref name=\"The Hill Restaurant industry estimates\">{{cite web |last1=Gangitano |first1=Alex |title=Restaurant industry estimates $225B in losses from coronavirus |url=https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/business-a-lobbying/488223-restaurant-industry-estimates-225b-in-losses-from |website=The Hill |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> The National Restaurant Association requested aid to restaurants in the amount of $145 billion.<ref name=\"The Hill Restaurant industry estimates\" />\n\nIn an effort to gain Republican support for a large stimulus package that at the time was envisioned to be about $1 trillion, [[United States Secretary of the Treasury]] [[Steven Mnuchin]] told Republican Senators that the United States unemployment rate could reach 20% if no government action was taken.<ref name=\"Mnuchin warns senators of 20%\">{{cite web |title=Mnuchin warns senators of 20% U.S. unemployment without coronavirus rescue\u2014source |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-usa-unemployment/mnuchin-warns-senators-of-20-us-unemployment-without-coronavirus-rescue-source-idUSKBN21502N |website=Reuters |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> Almost 3.3 million Americans filed for unemployment in the week ending March 21, \"nearly five times more than the previous record of 695,000 set in 1982\".<ref name=\"BBC News unemployment\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Record number of Americans file for unemployment |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52050426 |website=BBC News |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, [[Goldman Sachs]] predicted the U.S. [[gross domestic product]] would \"decline by 24% in the second quarter of 2020 because of the coronavirus pandemic\".<ref name=\"Insider GS prediction\">{{cite web |last1=Reinicke |first1=Carmen |title=Goldman Sachs now says US GDP will shrink 24% next quarter amid the coronavirus pandemic\u2014which would be 2.5 times bigger than any decline in history |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/us-gdp-drop-record-2q-amid-coronavirus-recession-goldman-sachs-2020-3-1029018308?utm_source=msn.com&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=msn-slideshow&utm_campaign=bodyurl |website=Markets Insider |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> [[Deutsche Bank]] predicted the U.S. economy would shrink by 12.9% in the second quarter of 2020.<ref name=\"Deutsche Bank forecast\">{{cite web |last1=Winck |first1=Ben |title=The worst global recession since World War II: Deutsche Bank just unveiled a bleak new forecast as the coronavirus rocks economies worldwide |url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/coronavirus-recession-worst-wwii-economic-recovery-global-deutsche-bank-2020-3-1029012757?utm_source=msn.com&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=msn-slideshow&utm_campaign=bodyurl |website=Markets Insider |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Initial proposals===\n\nIn mid-March 2020, Democratic politicians [[Andrew Yang]], [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]], and [[Tulsi Gabbard]] advocated for universal [[basic income]] in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]];<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clifford |first1=Catherine |title=Andrew Yang, AOC, Harvard professor: Free cash payments would help during coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/13/andrew-yang-aoc-free-ubi-cash-can-help-during-coronavirus-pandemic.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Relman |first1=Eliza |title=Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez demands the government distribute a universal basic income and implement 'Medicare for all' to fight the coronavirus |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-aoc-demands-universal-basic-income-other-radical-measures-2020-3 |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Gabbard suggested that it be a temporary measure until the crisis subsides.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Victor |title=Gabbard pitches 'emergency, temporary' $1,000 payment to every adult as coronavirus outbreak spreads |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/tulsi-gabbard-coronavirus-emergency-temporary-payment |accessdate=14 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> On March 13, Democratic representatives [[Ro Khanna]] and [[Tim Ryan (Ohio politician)|Tim Ryan]] introduced legislation to provide payments to low-income citizens during the crisis via an [[earned income tax credit]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Moreno |first1=J. Edward |title=Lawmakers call for universal basic income amid coronavirus crisis |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/487485-lawmakers-call-for-economic-stimulus-ubi-amid-coronavirus-crisis |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Corbett |first1=Jessica |title=House Democrats Propose Sending Checks of Up to $6,000 to Help Ease Workers' Pain During Coronavirus Pandemic |url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/13/house-democrats-propose-sending-checks-6000-help-ease-workers-pain-during |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Common Dreams |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> On March 16, Republican senators [[Mitt Romney]] and [[Tom Cotton]] stated their support for a $1,000 basic income, the former saying it should be a one-time payment to help with short-term costs.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lahut |first1=Jake |title=Tom Cotton is calling for Americans to get cash payments through the coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tom-cotton-calling-for-americans-to-get-100-month-coronavirus-2020-3 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Business Insider |date=16 March 2020}}</ref> On 17 March, the [[Trump administration]] indicated that some payment would be given to non-millionaires as part of a stimulus package.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Trump wants to send Americans checks 'immediately' in response to coronavirus, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-wants-to-send-money-to-americans-in-next-two-weeks-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=17 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Kasie |last2=Caldwell |first2=Leigh Ann |last3=Tsirkin |first3=Julie |last4=Shabad |first4=Rebecca |title=White House eyeing $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus package |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/senate-democrats-have-prepped-third-coronavirus-aid-package-n1161506 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=NBC News |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWith guidance from the White House, Senate Majority Leader [[Mitch McConnell]] proposed a third stimulus package amounting to more than $1&nbsp;trillion.{{efn|This included $300&nbsp;billion to help small businesses with forgivable loans up to $10&nbsp;million<ref name=hurdles/> and $200&nbsp;billion to support industries such as airlines, cruise companies, and hotels through loans and other measures.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stone |first1=Peter |title=Washington lobbyists in frenzied battle to secure billion-dollar coronavirus bailouts |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/20/coronavirus-washington-lobbyists-bailout |work=The Guardian |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Democrats advocated for banning stock {{nowrap|buy-backs}} to prevent these funds from being used to make a profit.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Press |first1=Associated |title=Congress and White House resume talks on $1tn pandemic rescue deal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/21/us-coronavirus-economic-rescue-trump |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>}} It was suggested that $200\u2013500&nbsp;billion would fund tax rebate checks to Americans who made between $2,500 and $75,000 in 2018 to help cover short-term costs<ref name=trillion>{{cite news |last1=Hunt |first1=Kasie |last2=Caldwell |first2=Leigh Ann |last3=Tsirkin |first3=Julie |last4=Shabad |first4=Rebecca |title=White House eyeing $1 trillion coronavirus stimulus package |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/senate-democrats-have-prepped-third-coronavirus-aid-package-n1161506 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=NBC News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Singman |first1=Brooke |title=Trump wants to send Americans checks 'immediately' in response to coronavirus, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/trump-wants-to-send-money-to-americans-in-next-two-weeks-amid-coronavirus-outbreak |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Fox News |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> via one or two payments of $600\u20131,200 per adult and $500 per child.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Breuninger |first1=Kevin |title=Trump wants direct payments of $1,000 for adults, $500 for kids in coronavirus stimulus bill, Mnuchin says |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/coronavirus-trump-wants-payments-of-1000-for-adults-500-for-kids.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Re |first1=Gregg |title=McConnell's coronavirus stimulus plan would provide payments of $1,200 per person, $2,400 for couples |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/mcconnell-coronavirus-stimulus-plan-payments |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=Fox News |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=rebate/>{{efn|It is unclear whether the rebates would be tax-free.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Konish |first1=Lorie |title=Here's how your coronavirus rescue check from the government could be taxed |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/20/heres-how-your-rescue-check-from-the-government-could-be-taxed.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>}} Democrats prepared a $750&nbsp;billion package as a {{nowrap|counter-offer}},<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=McConnell takes reins of third coronavirus bill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488338-mcconnell-takes-reins-of-third-coronavirus-bill |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Caygle |first1=Heather |last2=Bresnahan |first2=John |last3=Ferris |first3=Sarah |title=Pelosi looks to lay down marker on next stimulus plan |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/18/nancy-pelosi-coronavirus-stimulus-plan-136142 |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Politico |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> which focused on expanding [[unemployment benefits]] instead of tax rebates.<ref name=rebate>{{cite news |last1=Bolton |first1=Alexander |title=Democrats balk at $1,200 rebate checks in stimulus plan |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/488677-democrats-balk-at-1200-rebate-checks-in-stimulus-plan |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=The Hill |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> A compromise plan was made to set aside $250&nbsp;billion for tax rebates and the same amount for unemployment.<ref name=hurdles>{{cite news |last1=Mattingly |first1=Phil |title=Stimulus package could top $2 trillion as negotiators look to clear final major hurdles |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/21/politics/stimulus-package-negotiations-congress-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 22, 2020 |work=CNN |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Provisions==\n\n[[File:CARES ACT - Relief Amounts.png|thumb|right|400px|CARES Act relief amounts by category ($ billions), totaling $2.1 trillion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/relief-package-would-limit-coronavirus-damage-not-restore-economy-11585215006|title=Relief Package Would Limit Coronavirus Damage, Not Restore Economy|website=www.wsj.com|language=English|date=March 26, 2020|access-date=March 27, 2020 }}</ref>]]\n\nThe Act contains the following provisions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/116/hr748/text|title= H.R. 748: Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act |date= March 27, 2020 |work = [[govtrack]] |publisher= Civic Impulse, LLC }}</ref> \n\n* Allocates up to $500 billion for assistance to eligible businesses, states, and municipalities, with not more than $25 billion designated for passenger air carriers, not more than $4 billion for air cargo carriers, and not more than $17 billion for businesses critical to maintaining national security.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foley.com/en/insights/publications/2020/03/senate-passes-coronavirus-cares-act|title=Senate Passes the Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act (\"CARES Act\") |work= Foley & Lardner LLP| language=English|access-date=March 27, 2020 }}</ref><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 4003(b)</ref>\n* Creates a $349 billion loan program for small businesses with funds available for loans originated from February 15 through June 30, 2020.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 1102, amending the Small Business Act {{USC|15|636}}(a)</ref>\n* Allocates $130 billion in relief to the medical and hospital industries.<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Provides credits against the 2020 personal income tax for eligible individuals who are neither nonresident aliens nor claimed as dependents by another taxpayer.\n** $1,200 to each individual or $2,400 to each married couple filing jointly, and\n** $500 for each dependent who is a qualifying child under age 17 as of December 31, 2020.\n** The credits are reduced, but not below zero, by each 5 percent of so much of the taxpayers' adjusted gross income as exceeds $150,000 for a joint return; $112,500 for a head of household; or $75,000 for other taxpayers.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 2201, amending {{USC|26|6428}}</ref>\n* Expands eligibility for [[Unemployment benefits in the United States|unemployment insurance]] and provides people with an additional $600 per week on top of the unemployment amount determined by each state.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 2102</ref> [[Gig worker]]s and [[freelancer]]s are covered by unemployment insurance for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/30/cares-act-will-be-an-economic-lifeline-for-gig-workers-freelancers.html|title=The historic $2 trillion CARES Act will be an economic lifeline for gig workers and freelancers|first=Elaine|last=Pofeldt|website=CNBC.com|date=March 30, 2020|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n* Expands [[telehealth]] services in [[Medicare]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 3212</ref> \n* Provides the [[U.S. Secretary of the Treasury|Secretary of the Treasury]] with the authority to make loans or loan guarantees to states, municipalities, and eligible businesses.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act, Section 4003(b)(4)</ref>\n\n== Breakdown of provisions ==\n\nDivision A: Keeping Workers Paid and Employed, Health Care System Enhancements, and Economic Stabilization\n* Title I: [[Keeping American Workers Paid and Employed Act]]\n* Title II: [[Relief for Workers Affected by Coronavirus Act]]\n** Subtitle A: Unemployment Insurance Provisions\n** Subtitle B: Rebates And Other Individual Provisions\n** Subtitle C: Business Provisions\n* Title III: Supporting America's Health Care System in the Fight Against the Coronavirus\n** Subtitle A: Coronavirus Aid, Relief, and Economic Security Act\n*** Part I: Addressing Supply Shortages\n**** Subpart A: Medical Product Supplies\n**** Subpart B: Mitigating Emergency Drug Shortages\n**** Subpart C: Preventing Medical Device Shortages\n*** Part II: Access to Health Care for Covid\u201319 Patients\n**** Subpart A: Coverage of Testing and Preventive Services\n**** Subpart B: Support for Health Care Providers\n**** Subpart C: Miscellaneous Provisions\n*** Part III: Innovation\n*** Part IV: Health Care Workforce\n** Subtitle B: Education Provisions: [[COVID\u201319 Pandemic Education Relief Act of 2020]]\n** Subtitle C: Labor Provisions\n** Subtitle D: Finance Committee\n** Subtitle E: Health and Human Services Extenders\n*** Part I: Medicare Provisions\n*** Part II: Medicaid Provisions\n*** Part III: Human Services and Other Health Programs\n*** Part IV: Public Health Provisions\n*** Part V: Miscellaneous Provisions\n** Subtitle F: Over-the-Counter Drugs\n*** Part I: Otc Drug Review\n*** Part II: User Fees\n* Title IV: Economic Stabilization and Assistance to Severely Distressed Sectors of the United States Economy\n** Subtitle A: [[Coronavirus Economic Stabilization Act of 2020]]\n** Subtitle B: Air Carrier Worker Support\n* Title V: Coronavirus Relief Funds\n* Title VI: Miscellaneous Provisions\n\nDivision B: [[Emergency Appropriations for Coronavirus Health Response and Agency Operations]]\n\n==Legislative history==\n===Initial criticism and negotiations===\n\nThe House initially passed a tax cut bill in mid-2019 and sent it to the Senate, which then used it as a [[shell bill]] and added an [[substitute amendment|amendment in the nature of a substitute]], fulfilling the constitutional requirement that all bills for raising revenue must originate in the House. After the new bill was released by the Senate, Speaker of the House [[Nancy Pelosi]] ([[U.S. Democratic Party|D]]-[[California|CA]]) issued a statement that read in part: \"We are beginning to review Senator McConnell's proposal and on first reading, it is not at all pro-worker and instead puts corporations way ahead of workers.\"<ref name=\"CNN Republicans unveil $1 trillion\">{{cite web |last1=Mattingly |first1=Phil |last2=Foran |first2=Clare |last3=Barrett |first3=Ted |title=Senate Republicans unveil $1 trillion economic stimulus package to address coronavirus fallout |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/19/politics/coronavirus-economic-stimulus-senate-republicans/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting Systems]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\nSenate Minority Leader [[Chuck Schumer]] (D-[[New York (state)|NY]]) criticized the fact that Democrats were not involved by Republicans in drafting the bill.<ref name=\"NPR Republicans Unveil\">{{cite web |last1=Snell |first1=Kelsey |last2=Grisales |first2=Claudia |last3=Davis |first3=Susan |last4=Walsh |first4=Deirdre |title=Senate Republicans Unveil New Coronavirus Relief Package |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/19/818253789/congress-awaits-gop-relief-plan-as-first-lawmakers-test-positive-for-coronavirus |website=[[NPR]]|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAmong Senate Republicans there was \"significant debate and disagreement\" regarding \"President [[Donald Trump]]'s proposal to provide most Americans with $1,000-plus checks to boost spending and stimulate the economy\".<ref name=\"CNN Republicans unveil $1 trillion\" /> Senator [[Richard Shelby]] (R-[[Alabama|AL]]), the Republican chair of the [[Senate Appropriations Committee]], stated \"I personally think that if we're going to help people we should direct the cash payments maybe as a supplement to unemployment, not to the people who are working every day, just a blank check to everybody in America making up to $75,000.\"<ref name=\"CNN Republicans unveil $1 trillion\" />\n\n===Early procedural votes===\n\nOn the evening of Sunday March 22, 2020, Senate Democrats blocked the bill in a key procedural vote; the vote was 47\u201347, while 60 votes were needed to proceed.<ref name=\"CNBC 5 Things Monday\">{{cite web |last1=Belvedere |first1=Matthew |title=5 things to know before the stock market opens Monday |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/5-things-to-know-before-the-stock-market-opens-march-23-2020.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Immediately thereafter, \"[[Dow Jones Industrial Average|Dow]] futures hit their 5% 'limit down' overnight, and were off 600 points at one stage Monday morning.\"<ref name=\"CNBC 5 Things Monday\" /><ref name=\"National Law Review votes fails\">{{cite web |last1=Mill |first1=David |last2=Lee |first2=Muhyung |last3=Webb |first3=Sean |title=Coronavirus: CARES Act Vote Fails in Senate; Summary of the Tax Provisions of the Bill |url=https://content.natlawreview.com/article/coronavirus-cares-act-vote-fails-senate-summary-tax-provisions-bill |website=National Law Review |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response, Mitch McConnell \"announced another procedural vote on the package timed for 9:45 a.m. Monday\u2014minutes after the stock market opens\u2014but it was blocked by Democrats who don't want to be forced to take the vote.\"<ref name=\"CNN GOP ramps up pressure\">{{cite web |last1=Mattingly |first1=Phil |last2=Foran |first2=Clare |last3=Barrett |first3=Ted |title=Senate GOP ramps up pressure on Democrats over coronavirus stimulus package with Monday vote |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/stimulus-package-coronavirus-negotiations-congress/index.html |website=CNN |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> The second key procedural vote on the CARES Act, a cloture vote to end debate, failed the afternoon of Monday, March 23; 60 votes were needed, but it failed 49\u201346.<ref name=\"ABC Senate showdown\">{{cite web |last1=Parkinson |first1=John |title=Senate showdown over pandemic relief stalls as Pelosi preps Democratic bill |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/senate-showdown-pandemic-relief-stalls-pelosi-preps-democraticbill/story?id=69749675 |website=ABC News |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"National Law Review votes fails\" /> Both procedural votes were on a \"shell\" bill framed to repeal an [[Obamacare]] tax which passed the House on July 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Where do you stand? |url=https://www.countable.us/bills/hr748-116 |website=www.countable.us |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> For procedural reasons, the text will be replaced by the new language passed by the Senate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.countable.us/articles/43144-s-status-phase-3-coronavirus-relief-bill|title=What's the Status of the 'Phase 3' Coronavirus Relief Bill?|website=www.countable.us|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref name=\"The Hill Senate fails\">{{cite web |last1=Carney |first1=Jordain |title=Senate fails to advance coronavirus stimulus bill for second time in two days |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/489033-senate-fails-to-advance-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-for-second-time-in-two-days |website=The Hill |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nProcedural votes for the bill were made more difficult by the fact that five Republican Senators were in self-quarantine: Senator [[Rand Paul]], who had tested positive for [[coronavirus disease 2019]], as well as Senators [[Mike Lee (American politician)|Mike Lee]], Mitt Romney, [[Cory Gardner]], and [[Rick Scott]].<ref name=\"CNN GOP ramps up pressure\" />\n\nNancy Pelosi indicated that the House would prepare its own bill, expected to exceed $2.5&nbsp;trillion, as a counter-offer,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pramuk |first1=Jacob |title=House Democrats to introduce a $2.5 trillion coronavirus stimulus plan as Senate bill stalls |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/23/coronavirus-updates-pelosi-to-release-stimulus-bill-as-senate-plan-stalls.html |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> which was criticized by Republicans as \"a progressive wishlist seemingly unrelated to the crisis\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pelosis-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-includes-return-of-obamaphones-climate-change-wishlist|title=Pelosi's coronavirus stimulus includes return of 'Obamaphones', other unrelated items, GOP says|last=Re|first=Gregg|date=March 23, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324041402/https://www.foxnews.com/politics/pelosis-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-includes-return-of-obamaphones-climate-change-wishlist|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Senate agreement===\n\nEarly in the morning of Wednesday March 25, Senate leaders announced they had come to an agreement on a modified version of the CARES Act,<ref name=\"NPR Senate Reaches Historic Deal\">{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Susan |last2=Grisales |first2=Claudia |last3=Snell |first3=Kelsey |title=Senate Reaches Historic Deal On $2 Trillion Coronavirus Economic Rescue Package |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/25/818881845/senate-reaches-historic-deal-on-2t-coronavirus-economic-rescue-package |website=NPR |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> the full text of which exceeds 300 pages.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stein |first1=Jeff |title=What's in the $2.2 trillion coronavirus Senate stimulus package |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2020/03/26/senate-stimulus-bill-coronavirus-2-trillion-list-what-is-in-it/ |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=25 March 2020}}</ref> Mitch McConnell \"announced news of a breakthrough on the Senate floor shortly after 1:30{{nbsp}}a.m. Wednesday.\"<ref name=\"NPR Senate Reaches Historic Deal\" />\n\nOn the floor of the Senate, McConnell stated \"the Senate has reached a bipartisan agreement on a historic relief package for this pandemic\" and that \"this is a wartime level of investment for our nation.\"<ref name=\"NBC White House, Senate reach deal\">{{cite web |last1=Egan |first1=Lauren |last2=Tsirkin |first2=Julie |last3=Shabad |first3=Rebecca |title=White House, Senate reach deal on massive $2 trillion coronavirus spending bill |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/white-house-senate-reach-deal-massive-2-trillion-coronavirus-spending-n1168136 |website=NBC News |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> McConnell continued the analogy to war by stating that the CARES Act would provide \"ammunition\" to health care workers who are the \"frontline heroes who put themselves at risk to care for patients\" by providing them \"the ammunition they need\".<ref name=\"C-SPAN Senate agreement\">{{cite web |title=MARCH 24, 2020 Senate Session, Part 2 |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?470620-22/white-house-senate-leaders-reach-deal-2-trillion-economic-aid-package&start=14892 |website=C-SPAN |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref> Chuck Schumer stated on the Senate floor that \"Like all compromises, this bill is far from perfect, but we believe the legislation has been improved significantly to warrant its quick consideration and passage, and because many Democrats and Republicans were willing to do the serious and hard work, the bill is much better off than where it started.\"<ref name=\"NBC White House, Senate reach deal\" />\n[[File:FINAL-FINAL-CARES-ACT.pdf|thumb|CARES Act as negotiated by the Senate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/25/820759545/read-2-trillion-coronavirus-relief-bill|title=READ: $2 Trillion Coronavirus Relief Bill|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>]]\n\nThe result of the agreement between Senate leaders and the White House was a mammoth $2 trillion bill that \"is the largest economic relief bill in U.S. history\".<ref name=\"NPR Senate trudging\">{{cite web |last1=Taylor |first1=Andrew |last2=Lisa |first2=Mascaro |title=Senate trudging toward vote on virus rescue package |url=https://apnews.com/edd230801c0e181169915e67b1fd64c6 |website=NPR |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The bill was criticized by Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and New York Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]].<ref name=\"NPR Senate trudging\" /> Republican Senators [[Lindsey Graham]], [[Tim Scott]], [[Ben Sasse]], and Rick Scott expressed concern the bill's strong unemployment provisions \"encourage employees to be laid off instead of working\".<ref name=\"Politico Senate back on track\">{{cite web |last1=Zanona |first1=Melanie |last2=Ferris |first2=Sarah |last3=Caygle |first3=Heather |title=Senate back on track to vote on massive coronavirus package |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/25/senate-vote-coronavirus-rescue-package-deal-148135 |website=Politico |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] then threatened to block the legislation and impose more stringent conditions for the $500 billion earmarked for corporate bailouts if the unemployment provision was removed by the proposed amendment of the four Republican Senators.<ref>{{cite web |last=Zachary |first=Basu |title=Senators threaten to delay coronavirus relief bill with last-minute objections |url=https://www.axios.com/coronavirus-relief-bill-lindsey-graham-bernie-sanders-619d2d7e-fea5-4884-ae48-a80fcb029e40.html |website=Axios |date= |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> To address these concerns, Senate leaders \"agreed to allow an amendment vote on the floor\".<ref name=\"Politico Senate back on track\" /> The Republican-led amendment to cap unemployment benefits failed in a 48\u201348 vote.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mu\u00f1oz |first1=Gabriella |last2=Boyer |first2=Dave |title=Senate rejects coronavirus stimulus package amendment to cap unemployment benefits |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/mar/25/sasse-amendment-fix-coronavirus-stimulus-bill-unem/ |website=Washington Times |accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nLate in the night of Wednesday, March 25, 2020, the Senate passed the $2 trillion bill in a unanimous 96\u20130 vote. The four Senators not voting were Rand Paul (who did not vote after testing positive for [[coronavirus disease 2019]]), Mitt Romney and Mike Lee (who were both in isolation after contact with Senator Paul), as well as Senator [[John Thune]] who \"missed the vote after feeling ill\".<ref name=\"CNBC Senate passes $2 trillion\" />\n\n===House vote===\n\nOn March 25, Pelosi stated that \"many of the provisions in there have been greatly improved because of negotiation,\" and hoped to pass the bill by unanimous consent.<ref name=historic>{{cite news |last1=Raju |first1=Manu |last2=Barrett |first2=Ted |last3=Foran |first3=Clare |last4=Wilson |first4=Kristin |title=White House, Senate reach historic $2 trillion stimulus deal amid growing coronavirus fears |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/25/politics/stimulus-senate-action-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 25, 2020 |work=CNN |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nRepresentative [[Thomas Massie]] attempted to maneuver for a [[roll-call vote]], but there was insufficient demand [[Procedures of the United States Congress#Quorum and vote|among the quorum present]]; the House passed the bill by [[voice vote]] on March 27.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hughes |first=Siobhan |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-lawmakers-race-to-washington-to-ensure-coronavirus-stimulus-passes-11585318472 |title=House Passes $2 Trillion Coronavirus Stimulus Package |date=March 27, 2020 |work=Wall Street Journal |access-date=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live |last2=Andrews |first2=Natalie |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Massie's threat to demand a recorded vote nonetheless \"compelled dozens, if not hundreds, of lawmakers to return to Capitol Hill from their home districts, navigating across interstates and through airports at a time when public health officials have urged Americans to avoid nonessential travel and gathering in large groups.\"<ref name=\"Politico parties pile on Massie\">{{cite web |last1=Forgey |first1=Quint |title=Both parties pile on Massie after effort to force recorded vote flops |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/27/trump-congressman-thomas-massie-coronavirus-vote-151523 |website=Politico |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> Massie's actions received bipartisan criticism. Former Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] tweeted \"Congressman Massie has tested positive for being an asshole. He must be quarantined to prevent the spread of his massive stupidity,\"<ref name=\"Kerry Massie Tweet\">{{cite web |title=John Kerry 10:55 a.m.\u2014Mar 27, 2020 Tweet |url=https://twitter.com/JohnKerry/status/1243552337429438464 |website=Twitter |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref> a message which was shared by President Trump on Twitter.<ref name=\"Politico parties pile on Massie\" /> Republican Representative [[Peter T. King]] called Massie's actions \"disgraceful\" and \"irresponsible\".<ref name=\"Politico parties pile on Massie\" />\n\n===Signed into law and signing statement===\n\n[[File:CARES Act Enrolled Bill.pdf|thumb|CARES Act as signed into law]]\n\nA few hours after the House passed the bill, it was signed into law by President Trump.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Zeballos-Roig |first=Joseph |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/trump-signs-coronavirus-economic-relief-aid-bill-checks-for-americans-2020-3 |title=Trump signs the $2 trillion coronavirus economic relief bill into law, which includes checks for Americans and business loans |date=March 27, 2020 |work=Business Insider |access-date=March 27, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn a [[signing statement]], Trump suggested that he could gag the Special Inspector General for Pandemic Recovery (SIGPR), an oversight position created by the legislation to monitor loans and investments from a $500 billion corporate bailout fund established by the legislation.<ref name=Signingstmt>[[Charlie Savage]], [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/27/us/trump-signing-statement-coronavirus.html Trump Suggests He Can Gag Inspector General for Stimulus Bailout Program], ''New York Times'' (March 27, 2020).</ref> A provision in the legislation empowers the special inspector general to audit the use of the fund; requires the [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department]] and other executive-branch entities to provide information to the special inspector general; and directs the special inspector general to report to Congress \"without delay\" if an agency unreasonably withholds requested information.<ref name=Signingstmt/> In his signing statement, Trump suggested that his constitutional powers as president enabled him to block the SIGPR's reports to Congress.<ref name=Signingstmt/> According to ''[[The New York Times]]'', the statement was consistent with Trump's \"history of trying to keep damaging information acquired by an inspector general from reaching Congress.\"<ref name=Signingstmt/>\n\n==Commentary==\n===Bi-partisan passage===\nCongress passed CARES quickly and with unanimity from both parties, despite its $2.2 trillion price-tag, indicating from one perspective the severity of the crisis.<ref name=\"WaPo_Phillips\"/> In contrast, in the depths of the [[Great Recession]], no Republicans in the House and only 3 in the Senate supported Obama's $800 billion stimulus, known as the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]] (ARRA).<ref>{{Cite news |last=Rogers |first=David |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2009/02/senate-passes-787-billion-stimulus-bill-018837? |title=Senate passes $787 billion stimulus bill |date=February 13, 2009 |work=Politico.com |access-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Writing in ''The New Republic'', journalist Alex Shephard \"wondered how the Republican Party, which had spent the Obama years railing about the need to trim the deficit and debt, had come to embrace big spending.\" He interviewed one White House aide, who stated that Trump focuses on the markets and economy, not the national debt. However, Shephard expressed skepticism that Republicans would vote to support a major spending request under a hypothetical future Democratic President. He further explained that much of the media attention to ARRA focused on its impact on the deficit and the need for the Obama administration to persuade the public to support it, narratives almost entirely absent in the passage of CARES. Shephard opined that: \"[Then-Senate minority leader Mitch] [[Mitch McConnell|Mitch McConnell's]] strategy was to actually undermine Obama at every turn, with unified and total Republican opposition, whatever it might cost voters.\"<ref name=\"Shep_TNR\">{{Cite news |last=Shephard |first=Alex |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/157089/tale-two-stimulus-packages |title=A Tale of Two Stimulus Packages |date=March 30, 2020 |work=The New Republic |access-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> President Trump remarked upon passage of CARES in the Senate that: \"The Democrats have treated us fairly...I really believe we've had a very good back-and-forth. And I say that with respect to [Senate Minority Leader] [[Chuck Schumer]]\".<ref name=\"WaPo_Phillips\">{{Cite news |last=Phillips |first=Amber |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/03/26/totally-unprecedented-living-memory-congresss-bipartisanship-coronavirus-underscores-what-crisis-this-is/ |title='Totally unprecedented in living memory\u2019: Congress\u2019s bipartisanship on coronavirus underscores what a crisis this is |date=March 26, 2020 |work=washingtonpost.com |access-date=March 31, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n==See also==\n\n{{Div col}}\n* [[List of bills in the 116th United States Congress]]\n* [[Financial impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n* [[2020 in United States politics and government]]\n* [[2020s in United States political history]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{cite news|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|title=What's in the $2 Trillion Senate Coronavirus Bill|date= March 26, 2020 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/whats-in-the-2-trillion-senate-coronavirus-bill-11585185450}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.republicanleader.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/CARES%20Act%20Final%20-%20Mar%202020.pdf Full text of the original bill as proposed by Mitch McConnell on March 19, 2020]\n<!-- https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:FINAL-FINAL-CARES-ACT.pdf#file is also another choice, referenced earlier in the article. It's not clear how best to resolve this. -->\n* [https://www.congress.gov/116/bills/hr748/BILLS-116hr748enr.pdf Full text of the enrolled bill as passed by the Senate on March 25, 2020 and voted by the House on March 27, 2020]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Law associated with the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Acts of the 116th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:United States federal health legislation]]\n", "name_user": "Farcaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBi-partisan passage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coronavirus_Aid,_Relief,_and_Economic_Security_Act"}
{"title_page": "Author's Pet", "text_new": "{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = \n| image           = Author'sPet Cover.jpg\n| image_size      = 230px\n| caption         = Cover of ''Author's Pet'' as published by Magazine Magazine\n| ja_kanji        = \u4f5c\u5bb6\u3001\u30c9\u30ec\u30a4\u3092\u98fc\u3046\u3002\n| ja_romaji       = Sakka, Dorei wo Kau\n| genre           = [[Yaoi]], [[Romance novel|Romance]]\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| title           = \n| author          = [[Deathco Cotorino]]\n| illustrator     = \n| publisher       = [[Magazine Magazine]]\n| publisher_en    = {{English anime licensee | NA= [[Digital Manga Publishing]]}}\n| demographic     = ''[[Josei manga|Josei]]''\n| magazine        = \n| magazine_en     = \n| published       = August 26, 2008\n| first           = \n| last            = \n| volumes         = 1\n| volume_list     = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Author's Pet'''''|\u4f5c\u5bb6\u3001\u30c9\u30ec\u30a4\u3092\u98fc\u3046\u3002|Sakka, Dorei wo Kau|lead=yes}} is a [[one-shot (comics)|one-shot]] Japanese [[manga]] written and illustrated by [[Deathco Cotorino]]. It is licensed in North America by [[Digital Manga Publishing]], which released the manga through its imprint, Jun\u00e9, on August 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.junemanga.com/books/59/|title=Author's Pet|publisher=[[Digital Manga Publishing]]|accessdate=2009-06-16|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519085613/http://www.junemanga.com/books/59/|archivedate=19 May 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n\nPoor Yuuta!\nHe didn't mean to knock the man down the stairs, but now he's stuck playing slave to the cranky and gorgeous novelist Tsubaki Nishijima. Yuuta must type out the writer's latest novel word-for-steamy-word, while hiding the fact he's falling in love with his master! Will fact and fiction merge, or will a new romance end in tragedy?\n\nSome boys like to be playful pets, and other boys like to snarl and bite... but all the boys in AUTHOR\u2019S PET know what it truly takes to please their masters! Whether they're lowly shop assistance or frightened freshmen, each of these men won't stop until they've licked, kicked, and teased their way into your heart! Ready to play rough?\n\n== Chapters ==\n\n'''Chapter 1: I'll Have You Make Up for This'''\nHigh school student, Yuuta Oohashi knocks Tsubaki Nishijima down the stairs. In exchange for crippling his arm, the novelist Tsubaki demands Yuuta to work as slave for him every day! Today's job is to take exact dictation of Tsubaki's words for his work in progress novel. Whaaat? What's with this perverted depiction of \"Come\u201d...!!! Isn't this sexual harassment?\n\n'''Chapter 2: I'll Have You Change Your Job'''\nTsubaki Nishijima and Yuuta Oohashi now live together happily as lovers. Tsubaki is still recovering from his injury but Yuuta is doing his best to work part-time as Tsubaki's \"Slave.\" Tsubaki is working non-stop on his novel while Yuuta is caring for him along with getting paid for doing so. Yuuta feels awkward for doing such things and decides maybe working for Tsubaki and getting paid for doing so isn't such a great idea... But his feelings for Tsubaki don't hold back and make.\n\n'''Chapter 3: To Keep a Cat'''\nNaruse was walking home from work one night when he sees a boy all beaten up. He takes him in to his place and cares for him while the boy was sleeping. As the boy awoke Naruse found out that the boy, Mutsuki, was beaten badly by his rough ex-boyfriend. Naruse was only letting Mutsuki stay until he was recovered then he was out. Naruse couldn't let Mutsuki go back to his old life involved with having sex for money so he let him stay, however, Mutsuki didn't want his feelings for Naruse to ruin him again and is unsure of what to do.\n\n'''Chapter 4: The Helplessly Romantic Type'''\nYoung nineteen-year-old Saki works at Honma Motors with his dad being the president. He still currently in training in fixing motorcycles and cars but the rest of the staff are exclaiming he is doing an excellent job. Feeling the best when he is at work because the person he loves is working for Honma Motors as well. The top Manager of Honma Motors and the person Saki loves is named Sasaragawa. They played together when they were kids. Even though Sasaragawa doesn't want Saki hugging him in public while they are working there is something going on between them behind fixing motorcycles and cars.\n\n'''Chapter 5: Love Battle In The Dorms'''\nThe \"Miyako Inn\" is a city dorm for male college students. A freshman is moving into the dorms named Noriaki Mukai. He meets Youhei Kikuchi, a second year and Oohashi, a senior. Oohashi claims Kikuchi as his \"pet\" and Mukai can't touch him, they have a drinking competition to see who gets Kikuchi and end up passing out; failing the bet. Mukai wants to impress Kikuchi as much as he can, but when he witnesses a heart-wrenching event, he's unsure if his feelings should be going towards Kikuchi after all.\n\n'''Chapter 6: Open 24 Hours'''\nSakamoto works at a convenience store that sells a variety of cakes. A man, exactly at eleven at night always comes and buys a ton of cakes. Who could they be for? Eventually, Sakamoto finds out \"The Awful Cake Man's\" name is actually Shirokawa. Sakamoto decides to cook an actual dinner at his place and gets to know more about this man with his cake sweet tooth. An unfortunate event happens with Sakamoto's job and doesn't know if he could work anywhere else... until Shirokawa springs an idea on him.\n\n==Reception==\nActiveAnime's Holly Ellingwood commends the manga for its attractive art style \"with some explicit scenes that are not overly graphic yet very tender\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://activeanime.com/html/2008/08/08/author%E2%80%99s-pet-advance-review/ |title=Author\u2019S Pet (Advance Review) |last=Ellingwood |first=Holly |date=August 8, 2008 |publisher=ActiveAnime |accessdate=2009-06-16 }}<!-- http://web.archive.org/web/20081123031547/http://www.activeanime.com/html/content/view/3684/57/ --></ref> Mania.com's Danielle van Gorder comments on the variety of the length of the stories and the stories themselves allowed the book to remain \"fresh and unpredictable, despite the general lack of development\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/authors-pet_article_86628.html |title=Author's Pet |last=Van Gorder |first=Danielle |date=September 18, 2008 |publisher=Mania.com |accessdate=2009-06-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801011255/http://www.mania.com/authors-pet_article_86628.html |archivedate=2009-08-01 }}</ref> Comic Book Bin's Leroy Douresseaux comments that the manga's \"tales are fun, sexy, comic romps full of good-natured, lustful ribbing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbookbin.com/authorspet001.html|title=Deathco Cotorino's Author's Pet (Yaoi)|last=Douresseaux|first=Leroy|date=September 25, 2008|publisher=Comic Book Bin|accessdate=2009-06-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Ann|manga|13735}}\n\n[[Category:2008 manga]]\n[[Category:Digital Manga Publishing titles]]\n[[Category:Drama anime and manga]]\n[[Category:Manga anthologies]]\n[[Category:Josei manga]]\n[[Category:Yaoi anime and manga]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox animanga/Header\n| name            = \n| image           = Author'sPet Cover.jpg\n| image_size      = 230px\n| caption         = Cover of ''Author's Pet'' as published by Magazine Magazine\n| ja_kanji        = \u4f5c\u5bb6\u3001\u30c9\u30ec\u30a4\u3092\u98fc\u3046\u3002\n| ja_romaji       = Sakka, Dorei wo Kau\n| genre           = [[Yaoi]], [[Romance novel|Romance]]\n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Print\n| type            = manga\n| title           = \n| author          = [[Deathco Cotorino]]\n| illustrator     = \n| publisher       = [[Magazine Magazine]]\n| publisher_en    = {{English anime licensee | NA= [[Digital Manga Publishing]]}}\n| demographic     = ''[[Josei manga|Josei]]''\n| magazine        = \n| magazine_en     = \n| published       = August 26, 2008\n| first           = \n| last            = \n| volumes         = 1\n| volume_list     = \n}}\n{{Infobox animanga/Footer}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Author's Pet'''''|\u4f5c\u5bb6\u3001\u30c9\u30ec\u30a4\u3092\u98fc\u3046\u3002|Sakka, Dorei wo Kau|lead=yes}} is a [[one-shot (comics)|one-shot]] Japanese [[manga]] written and illustrated by [[Deathco Cotorino]]. It is licensed in North America by [[Digital Manga Publishing]], which released the manga through its imprint, Jun\u00e9, on August 26, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.junemanga.com/books/59/|title=Author's Pet|publisher=[[Digital Manga Publishing]]|accessdate=2009-06-16|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519085613/http://www.junemanga.com/books/59/|archivedate=19 May 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n\nPoor Yuuta!\nHe didn\u2019t mean to knock the man down the stairs, but now he\u2019s stuck playing slave to the cranky and gorgeous novelist Tsubaki Nishijima. Yuuta must type out the writer\u2019s latest novel word-for-steamy-word, while hiding the fact he\u2019s falling in love with his master! Will fact and fiction merge, or will a new romance end in tragedy?\n\nSome boys like to be playful pets, and other boys like to snarl and bite\u2026 but all the boys in AUTHOR\u2019S PET know what it truly takes to please their masters! Whether they\u2019re lowly shop assistance or frightened freshmen, each of these men won't stop until they\u2019ve licked, kicked, and teased their way into your heart! Ready to play rough?\n\n== Chapters ==\n\n'''Chapter 1: I\u2019ll Have You Make Up for This'''\nHigh school student, Yuuta Oohashi knocks Tsubaki Nishijima down the stairs. In exchange for crippling his arm, the novelist Tsubaki demands Yuuta to work as slave for him every day! Today's job is to take exact dictation of Tsubaki's words for his work in progress novel. Whaaat? What's with this perverted depiction of \"Come\u201d...!!! Isn't this sexual harassment?\n\n'''Chapter 2: I\u2019ll Have You Change Your Job'''\nTsubaki Nishijima and Yuuta Oohashi now live together happily as lovers. Tsubaki is still recovering from his injury but Yuuta is doing his best to work part-time as Tsubaki's \"Slave.\" Tsubaki is working non-stop on his novel while Yuuta is caring for him along with getting paid for doing so. Yuuta feels awkward for doing such things and decides maybe working for Tsubaki and getting paid for doing so isn't such a great idea... But his feelings for Tsubaki don't hold back and make.\n\n'''Chapter 3: To Keep a Cat'''\nNaruse was walking home from work one night when he sees a boy all beaten up. He takes him in to his place and cares for him while the boy was sleeping. As the boy awoke Naruse found out that the boy, Mutsuki, was beaten badly by his rough ex-boyfriend. Naruse was only letting Mutsuki stay until he was recovered then he was out. Naruse couldn't let Mutsuki go back to his old life involved with having sex for money so he let him stay, however, Mutsuki didn't want his feelings for Naruse to ruin him again and is unsure of what to do.\n\n'''Chapter 4: The Helplessly Romantic Type'''\nYoung nineteen-year-old Saki works at Honma Motors with his dad being the president. He still currently in training in fixing motorcycles and cars but the rest of the staff are exclaiming he is doing an excellent job. Feeling the best when he is at work because the person he loves is working for Honma Motors as well. The top Manager of Honma Motors and the person Saki loves is named Sasaragawa. They played together when they were kids. Even though Sasaragawa doesn't want Saki hugging him in public while they are working there is something going on between them behind fixing motorcycles and cars.\n\n'''Chapter 5: Love Battle In The Dorms'''\nThe \"Miyako Inn\" is a city dorm for male college students. A freshman is moving into the dorms named Noriaki Mukai. He meets Youhei Kikuchi, a second year and Oohashi, a senior. Oohashi claims Kikuchi as his \"pet\" and Mukai can't touch him, they have a drinking competition to see who gets Kikuchi and end up passing out; failing the bet. Mukai wants to impress Kikuchi as much as he can, but when he witnesses a heart-wrenching event, he's unsure if his feelings should be going towards Kikuchi after all.\n\n'''Chapter 6: Open 24 Hours'''\nSakamoto works at a convenience store that sells a variety of cakes. A man, exactly at eleven at night always comes and buys a ton of cakes. Who could they be for? Eventually, Sakamoto finds out \"The Awful Cake Man's\" name is actually Shirokawa. Sakamoto decides to cook an actual dinner at his place and gets to know more about this man with his cake sweet tooth. An unfortunate event happens with Sakamoto's job and doesn't know if he could work anywhere else... until Shirokawa springs an idea on him.\n\n==Reception==\nActiveAnime's Holly Ellingwood commends the manga for its attractive art style \"with some explicit scenes that are not overly graphic yet very tender\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://activeanime.com/html/2008/08/08/author%E2%80%99s-pet-advance-review/ |title=Author\u2019S Pet (Advance Review) |last=Ellingwood |first=Holly |date=August 8, 2008 |publisher=ActiveAnime |accessdate=2009-06-16 }}<!-- http://web.archive.org/web/20081123031547/http://www.activeanime.com/html/content/view/3684/57/ --></ref> Mania.com's Danielle van Gorder comments on the variety of the length of the stories and the stories themselves allowed the book to remain \"fresh and unpredictable, despite the general lack of development\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mania.com/authors-pet_article_86628.html |title=Author's Pet |last=Van Gorder |first=Danielle |date=September 18, 2008 |publisher=Mania.com |accessdate=2009-06-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090801011255/http://www.mania.com/authors-pet_article_86628.html |archivedate=2009-08-01 }